 legal_UN = <!-- N I, II, III, IV / P I, II, III, IV-->\n| legal_UN_comment = \n| legal_status      = <!-- For countries not listed above -->\n\n<!-- Pharmacokinetic data -->\n| bioavailability   = \n| protein_bound     = \n| metabolism        = \n| metabolites       = \n| onset             = \n| elimination_half-life = \n| duration_of_action = \n| excretion         = \n\n<!-- Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number        = 1420477-60-6\n| CAS_supplemental  = \n| PubChem           = 71226662\n| IUPHAR_ligand     = \n| DrugBank          = DB11703\n| ChemSpiderID      = 36764951\n| UNII              = I42748ELQW\n| KEGG              = D10893\n| ChEBI             = \n| ChEMBL            = 3707348\n| NIAID_ChemDB      = \n| PDB_ligand        = \n| synonyms          = ACP-196\n\n<!-- Chemical and physical data -->\n| IUPAC_name        = 4-{8-Amino-3-[(2''S'')-1-(2-butynoyl)-2-pyrrolidinyl]imidazo[1,5-a]pyrazin-1-yl}-''N''-(2-pyridinyl)benzamide\n| C=26 | H=23 | N=7 | O=2\n| molecular_weight  = \n| SMILES            = CC#CC(=O)N1CCC[C@H]1c2nc(c3n2ccnc3N)c4ccc(cc4)C(=O)Nc5ccccn5\n| Jmol              = \n| StdInChI          = 1S/C26H23N7O2/c1-2-6-21(34)32-15-5-7-19(32)25-31-22(23-24(27)29-14-16-33(23)25)17-9-11-18(12-10-17)26(35)30-20-8-3-4-13-28-20/h3-4,8-14,16,19H,5,7,15H2,1H3,(H2,27,29)(H,28,30,35)/t19-/m0/s1\n| StdInChI_comment  = \n| StdInChIKey       = WDENQIQQYWYTPO-IBGZPJMESA-N\n| density           = \n| density_notes     = \n| melting_point     = \n| melting_high      = \n| melting_notes     = \n| boiling_point     = \n| boiling_notes     = \n| solubility        = \n| sol_units         = \n| specific_rotation = \n}}\n\n<!-- Definition and medical uses -->\n'''Acalabrutinib''' (trade name '''Calquence''') is a medication used to treat a type of [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]] known as [[mantle cell lymphoma]].<ref name=AHFS2019>{{cite web |title=Acalabrutinib Monograph for Professionals |url=https://www.drugs.com/monograph/acalabrutinib.html |website=Drugs.com |accessdate=16 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Specifically it is for people who had previously been treated with another therapy.<ref>{{cite press release | title=FDA approves new treatment for adults with mantle cell lymphoma | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=31 October 2017 | url=http://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-new-treatment-adults-mantle-cell-lymphoma | access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> As of 2019, it was unclear whether it improved outcomes.<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n<!-- Side effects and mechanism -->\nCommon side effects include headaches, feeling tired, [[low red blood cells]], [[low platelets]], and [[low white blood cells]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is a second generation [[Bruton's tyrosine kinase]] inhibitor.<ref name=Byrd2015>{{cite journal |title=Acalabrutinib (ACP-196) in Relapsed Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia. |journal = New England Journal of Medicine|volume = 374|issue = 4|pages = 323\u2013332|year=2015 |author=Byrd |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1509981 |pmid = 26641137|display-authors=etal|pmc=4862586 }}</ref><ref name=Jing2016>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Jingjing|last2=Zhang|first2=Mingzhi|last3=Liu|first3=Delong|date=2016-01-01|title=Acalabrutinib (ACP-196): a selective second-generation BTK inhibitor|journal=Journal of Hematology & Oncology|volume=9|pages=21|doi=10.1186/s13045-016-0250-9|issn=1756-8722|pmc=4784459|pmid=26957112}}</ref> \n\n<!-- History and culture -->\nAcalabrutinib was approved for medical use in the United States in 2017.<ref name=AHFS2019/> The wholesale cost as of 2018 in the United States is 14,064 USD per month.<ref>{{cite web |title=In Brief: Acalabrutinib (Calquence) for Mantle Cell Lymphoma (online only) |url=https://secure.medicalletter.org/w1559d |website=The Medical Letter |accessdate=16 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Medical uses==\nIt is used to treat a type of [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]] known as [[mantle cell lymphoma]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is unclear if it results in improved outcomes as of 2019.<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n==Side effects==\nThe most common adverse events were headache, diarrhea and weight gain.<ref name=Jing2016 /> Despite the appearance of a greater occurrence of transient headaches, data suggests a preferred advantage of acalabrutinib over ibrutinib due to expected reduced adverse events of skin rash, severe diarrhea, and bleeding risk.<ref name=Jing2016 />\n\n==Society and culture==\n===Names===\nAcalabrutinib is the [[international nonproprietary name|INN]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO Drug Information - recommended INN|url=http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/druginformation/INN_List113.pdf|website=WHO Drug Information|publisher=World Health Oorganisation|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Regulatory ===\nAs of February 2016, acalabrutinib had received [[orphan drug]] designation in the United States for [[mantle cell lymphoma]] and [[chronic lymphocytic leukemia]] (CLL), <ref>{{cite web | title=Acalabrutinib Orphan Drug Designation and Approval | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/opdlisting/oopd/detailedIndex.cfm?cfgridkey=488915 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web | title=Acalabrutinib Orphan Drug Designation and Approval | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/opdlisting/oopd/detailedIndex.cfm?cfgridkey=477415 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and was similarly designated as an orphan medicinal product by the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) Committee for Orphan Medicinal Products (COMP) for treatment of three indications - CLL/ [[small lymphocytic lymphoma]] (SLL), mantle cell lymphoma (MCL), and lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma ([[Waldenstr\u00f6m's macroglobulinaemia]], WM).<ref>{{cite web | title=EU/3/16/1624 | website=[[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) | date=2 May 2016 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/orphan-designations/eu3161624 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=EU/3/16/1625 | website=[[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) | date=4 May 2016 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/orphan-designations/eu3161625 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=EU/3/16/1626 | website=[[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) | date=4 May 2016 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/orphan-designations/eu3161626 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/901832/000119163816001711/azn201602256k.htm|title=azn201602256k.htm|website=www.sec.gov|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref> Approval would result in a 10-year period of market exclusivity for the stated indications within Europe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://seekingalpha.com/news/3140106-astrazeneca-acerta-pharmas-acalabrutinib-tagged-orphan-drug-europe-three-indications|title=AstraZeneca and Acerta Pharma's acalabrutinib tagged an Orphan Drug in Europe for three indications|last=House|first=SA Editor Douglas W.|date=2016-02-25|newspaper=Seeking Alpha|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics ===\nIt was developed by Acerta Pharma.<ref>{{cite web|title=AstraZeneca to buy Acerta for blood cancer drug|url=http://www.rsc.org/chemistryworld/2015/12/astrazeneca-acerta-blood-cancer-drug|website=www.rsc.org|publisher=Chemistry World - Royal Society of Chemistry|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref> After promising results for CLL in initial clinical trials,<ref name=\"Byrd2015\" /> [[Astra Zeneca]] purchased a 55% stake in Acerta Pharma for $4 billion in December 2015, with an option to acquire the remaining 45% stake for an additional $3 billion, conditional on approval in both the US and Europe and the establishment of commercial opportunity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/astrazeneca-to-buy-stake-in-acerta-pharma-1450337812|title=AstraZeneca to Buy Stake in Acerta Pharma|last=Walker|first=Ian|date=2015-12-17|last2=Roland|first2=Denise|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nRelative to [[ibrutinib]], acalabrutinib demonstrated higher selectivity and inhibition of the targeted activity of BTK, while having a much greater IC<sub>50</sub> or otherwise virtually no inhibition on the kinase activities of ITK, EGFR, ERBB2, ERBB4, JAK3, BLK, FGR, FYN, HCK, LCK, LYN, SRC, and YES1.<ref name=Jing2016 /> In addition, in platelets treated with ibrutinib, thrombus formation was clearly inhibited while no impact to thrombus formation was  identified relative to controls for those treated with acalabrutinib.<ref name=Jing2016 /> These findings strongly suggest an improved safety profile of acalabrutinib with minimized adverse effects relative to ibrutinib.<ref name=Jing2016 /> In pre-clinical studies, it was shown to be more potent and selective than [[ibrutinib]], the first-in-class BTK inhibitor.<ref name=\"Byrd2015\" /><ref name=Jing2016 /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Jingjing|last2=Zhang|first2=Mingzhi|last3=Liu|first3=Delong|date=2016-03-09|title=Acalabrutinib (ACP-196): a selective second-generation BTK inhibitor|journal=Journal of Hematology & Oncology|language=En|volume=9|issue=1|doi=10.1186/s13045-016-0250-9|issn=1756-8722|pmc=4784459|pmid=26957112}}</ref> \n\nThe interim results of the still on-going{{when|date=March 2020}} first human phase 1/2 clinical trial (NCT02029443) with 61 patients for the treatment of relapsed [[chronic lymphocytic leukemia]] (CLL) are encouraging, with a 95% overall response rate demonstrating potential to become a best-in-class treatment for CLL.<ref name=\"Byrd2015\" /> Notably, a 100% response rate was achieved for those people which were positive for the 17p13.1 gene deletion - a subgroup that typically results in a poor response to therapy and expected outcomes.<ref name=Jing2016 />\n\nThere are plans to study the medication in [[COVID19]].<ref>{{cite news |title=AstraZeneca to Test Impact of Cancer Drug Calquence on Coronavirus Patients |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/14/world/europe/14reuters-health-coronavirus-astrazeneca.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | url = https://druginfo.nlm.nih.gov/drugportal/name/acalabrutinib | publisher = U.S. National Library of Medicine | work = Drug Information Portal | title = Acalabrutinib }}\n\n{{Portal bar | Pharmacy and pharmacology | Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Cancer treatments]]\n[[Category:Human proteins]]\n[[Category:Tyrosine kinase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:AstraZeneca brands]]\n[[Category:Alkyne derivatives]]\n[[Category:Orphan drugs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox drug\n| drug_name         = \n| INN               = \n| type              = <!-- empty -->\n| image             = Acalabrutinib.svg\n| width             = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n\n<!-- Clinical data -->\n| pronounce         = \n| tradename         = Calquence\n| Drugs.com         = {{drugs.com|monograph|acalabrutinib}}\n| MedlinePlus       = \n| licence_CA        = <!-- Health Canada may use generic or brand name (generic name preferred) -->\n| licence_EU        = <!-- EMA uses INN (or special INN_EMA) -->\n| DailyMedID        = Acalabrutinib\n| licence_US        = <!-- FDA may use generic or brand name (generic name preferred) -->\n| pregnancy_AU      = C\n| pregnancy_AU_comment = <ref name=\"Drugs.com pregnancy\">{{cite web | title=Acalabrutinib (Calquence) Use During Pregnancy | website=Drugs.com | date=23 October 2019 | url=https://www.drugs.com/pregnancy/acalabrutinib.html | access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n| pregnancy_US      = N\n| pregnancy_US_comment = <ref name=\"Drugs.com pregnancy\" />\n| pregnancy_category= \n| dependency_liability = \n| addiction_liability = \n| routes_of_administration = By mouth\n| class             = \n| ATCvet            = \n| ATC_prefix        = L01\n| ATC_suffix        = XE51\n| ATC_supplemental  = \n\n<!-- Lega