|issn=1756-8722|pmc=4784459|pmid=26957112}}</ref> \n\n<!-- History and culture -->\nAcalabrutinib was approved for medical use in the United States in 2017.<ref name=AHFS2019/> The wholesale cost as of 2018 in the United States is 14,064 USD per month.<ref>{{cite web |title=In Brief: Acalabrutinib (Calquence) for Mantle Cell Lymphoma (online only) |url=https://secure.medicalletter.org/w1559d |website=The Medical Letter |accessdate=16 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Medical uses==\nIt is used to treat a type of [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]] known as [[mantle cell lymphoma]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is unclear if it results in improved outcomes as of 2019.<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n==Side effects==\nThe most common adverse events were headache, diarrhea and weight gain.<ref name=Jing2016 /> Despite the appearance of a greater occurrence of transient headaches, data suggests a preferred advantage of acalabrutinib over ibrutinib due to expected reduced adverse events of skin rash, severe diarrhea, and bleeding risk.<ref name=Jing2016 />\n\n==Society and culture==\n===Names===\nAcalabrutinib is the [[international nonproprietary name|INN]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO Drug Information - recommended INN|url=http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/druginformation/INN_List113.pdf|website=WHO Drug Information|publisher=World Health Oorganisation|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Regulatory ===\nAs of February 2016, acalabrutinib had received [[orphan drug]] designation in the United States for [[mantle cell lymphoma]] and [[chronic lymphocytic leukemia]] (CLL), <ref>{{cite web | title=Acalabrutinib Orphan Drug Designation and Approval | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/opdlisting/oopd/detailedIndex.cfm?cfgridkey=488915 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web | title=Acalabrutinib Orphan Drug Designation and Approval | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/opdlisting/oopd/detailedIndex.cfm?cfgridkey=477415 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and was similarly designated as an orphan medicinal product by the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) Committee for Orphan Medicinal Products (COMP) for treatment of three indications - CLL/ [[small lymphocytic lymphoma]] (SLL), mantle cell lymphoma (MCL), and lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma ([[Waldenstr\u00f6m's macroglobulinaemia]], WM).<ref>{{cite web | title=EU/3/16/1624 | website=European Medicines Agency | date=17 September 2018 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/orphan-designations/eu3161624 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=EU/3/16/1625 | website=European Medicines Agency | date=17 September 2018 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/orphan-designations/eu3161625 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=EU/3/16/1626 | website=European Medicines Agency | date=17 September 2018 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/orphan-designations/eu3161626 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/901832/000119163816001711/azn201602256k.htm|title=azn201602256k.htm|website=www.sec.gov|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref> Approval would result in a 10-year period of market exclusivity for the stated indications within Europe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://seekingalpha.com/news/3140106-astrazeneca-acerta-pharmas-acalabrutinib-tagged-orphan-drug-europe-three-indications|title=AstraZeneca and Acerta Pharma's acalabrutinib tagged an Orphan Drug in Europe for three indications|last=House|first=SA Editor Douglas W.|date=2016-02-25|newspaper=Seeking Alpha|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics ===\nIt was developed by Acerta Pharma.<ref>{{cite web|title=AstraZeneca to buy Acerta for blood cancer drug|url=http://www.rsc.org/chemistryworld/2015/12/astrazeneca-acerta-blood-cancer-drug|website=www.rsc.org|publisher=Chemistry World - Royal Society of Chemistry|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref> After promising results for CLL in initial clinical trials,<ref name=\"Byrd2015\" /> [[Astra Zeneca]] purchased a 55% stake in Acerta Pharma for $4 billion in December 2015, with an option to acquire the remaining 45% stake for an additional $3 billion, conditional on approval in both the US and Europe and the establishment of commercial opportunity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/astrazeneca-to-buy-stake-in-acerta-pharma-1450337812|title=AstraZeneca to Buy Stake in Acerta Pharma|last=Walker|first=Ian|date=2015-12-17|last2=Roland|first2=Denise|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nRelative to [[ibrutinib]], acalabrutinib demonstrated higher selectivity and inhibition of the targeted activity of BTK, while having a much greater IC<sub>50</sub> or otherwise virtually no inhibition on the kinase activities of ITK, EGFR, ERBB2, ERBB4, JAK3, BLK, FGR, FYN, HCK, LCK, LYN, SRC, and YES1.<ref name=Jing2016 /> In addition, in platelets treated with ibrutinib, thrombus formation was clearly inhibited while no impact to thrombus formation was  identified relative to controls for those treated with acalabrutinib.<ref name=Jing2016 /> These findings strongly suggest an improved safety profile of acalabrutinib with minimized adverse effects relative to ibrutinib.<ref name=Jing2016 /> In pre-clinical studies, it was shown to be more potent and selective than [[ibrutinib]], the first-in-class BTK inhibitor.<ref name=\"Byrd2015\" /><ref name=Jing2016 /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Jingjing|last2=Zhang|first2=Mingzhi|last3=Liu|first3=Delong|date=2016-03-09|title=Acalabrutinib (ACP-196): a selective second-generation BTK inhibitor|journal=Journal of Hematology & Oncology|language=En|volume=9|issue=1|doi=10.1186/s13045-016-0250-9|issn=1756-8722|pmc=4784459|pmid=26957112}}</ref> \n\nThe interim results of the still on-going{{when|date=March 2020}} first human phase 1/2 clinical trial (NCT02029443) with 61 patients for the treatment of relapsed [[chronic lymphocytic leukemia]] (CLL) are encouraging, with a 95% overall response rate demonstrating potential to become a best-in-class treatment for CLL.<ref name=\"Byrd2015\" /> Notably, a 100% response rate was achieved for those people which were positive for the 17p13.1 gene deletion - a subgroup that typically results in a poor response to therapy and expected outcomes.<ref name=Jing2016 />\n\nThere are plans to study the medication in [[COVID19]].<ref>{{cite news |title=AstraZeneca to Test Impact of Cancer Drug Calquence on Coronavirus Patients |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/14/world/europe/14reuters-health-coronavirus-astrazeneca.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | url = https://druginfo.nlm.nih.gov/drugportal/name/acalabrutinib | publisher = U.S. National Library of Medicine | work = Drug Information Portal | title = Acalabrutinib }}\n\n{{Portal bar | Pharmacy and pharmacology | Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Cancer treatments]]\n[[Category:Human proteins]]\n[[Category:Tyrosine kinase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:AstraZeneca brands]]\n[[Category:Alkyne derivatives]]\n[[Category:Orphan drugs]]\n", "name_user": "Whywhenwhohow", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRegulatory:update refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acalabrutinib"}
{"title_page": "OneWeb satellite constellation", "text_new": "{{short description|Proposed constellation}}\n{{Infobox spacecraft class\n| name                 = OneWeb satellite constellation\n| image                = KSC-20170316-PH KLS01 0007~orig.jpg\n| image_caption        = Model of a OneWeb satellite\n| image_size           = 300px\n\n| manufacturer         = [[OneWeb Satellites]]<br/>({{small|[[OneWeb]] & [[Airbus Defence and Space|Airbus]]}})\n| country              = [[United States]]\n| operator             = [[OneWeb]]\n\n<!--Specifications-->\n| spacecraft_type      = [[Small satellite]]\n| launch_mass          = {{cvt|150|kg}}<ref name=sn20190227/>\n| applications         = [[Satellite Internet access|Internet service]]\n| equipment            = [[Ku band|K<sub>u</sub> band]] antennas\n| orbits               = [[Polar orbit|Polar]] [[low Earth orbit]]<br/>({{cvt|1200|km|disp=comma}})\n\n<!--Production-->\n| status               = \n| launched             = 74\n| operational          = \n| first                = 27 February 2019\n| last                 = 21 March 2020\n\n<!--insignia-->\n| insignia             = OneWeb Logo.png\n| insignia_alt         = OneWeb logo\n| insignia_size        = 270px\n}}\n\nThe '''OneWeb satellite constellation''' (formerly WorldVu) was a planned initial 650-[[artificial satellite|satellite]] [[satellite constellation|constellation]] that was in the process of being built out in 2019\u20132020, with a goal to provide global [[satellite internet constellation|satellite]] [[Internet]] broadband services to people everywhere and was previously aiming to provide global services starting in 2021. The constellation was being deployed by [[OneWeb]], formerly known as WorldVu Satellites and headquartered in London, UK with offices in California, Florida, Virginia, Dubai and Singapore. \n\nOneWeb declared bankruptcy in late March 2020, and has laid off most of their employees, but is maintaining the satellite operations center for the approximately 70 satellites already in orbit while the court determines disposition of the OneWeb assets.\n\nIn total 74 satellites were launched before the bankruptcy. The first six test satellites were launched in February 2019;<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/02/27/first-six-oneweb-satellites-launched-from-french-guiana/|title=First six OneWeb satellites launched from French Guiana|last=Clark|first=Stephen|date=2019-02-27|website=Spaceflight Now|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228192401/https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/02/27/first-six-oneweb-satellites-launched-from-french-guiana/|archive-date=2019-02-28|access-date=2019-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> the first large batch of 34 satellites was launched in February 2020,<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\" /> another 34 satellites were put into orbit in March 2020.<ref name=\"sn20200321\">{{cite web|title=Soyuz launches 34 OneWeb satellites|first1=Caleb|last1=Henry|date=21 March 2020|website=SpaceNews.com|url=https://spacenews.com/soyuz-launches-34-oneweb-satellites/|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Small satellite|small satellites]] were built by OneWeb Satellites, a joint venture between [[Airbus Defence and Space|Airbus]] and OneWeb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/what-airbus-learned-from-building-satellites-with-oneweb/|title=What Airbus learned from building satellites with OneWeb|date=2019-03-19|website=SpaceNews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref> The satellites are operating in a [[circular orbit|circular]] [[low Earth orbit]], at approximately {{convert|1200|km|mi|sp=us|sigfig=2}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]],<ref name=wsj20160203/> transmitting and receiving in the [[Ku band]] of the [[radio frequency spectrum]].<ref name=sn20140530/> Prior to the bankruptcy, OneWeb had been considering nearly quadrupling the size of the satellite constellation over time by adding 1,972 additional satellites that it has priority spectrum rights to.<ref name=sn201702/>\n\n==History==\nEarly reports of the potential involvement of [[Google]] in offering broadband internet services surfaced in February 2014, when a \"very large [satellite] constellation\" was rumored to be as large as 1,600 satellites.<ref name=pa20140216>{{cite news|last1=Messier|first1=Doug|title=Is Google Planning Son of Teledesic?|url=http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/02/16/google-planning-son-teledesic/|accessdate=2014-06-14|publisher=Parabolic Arc|date=2014-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702125309/http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/02/16/google-planning-son-teledesic/|archive-date=2014-07-02|url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy June 2014, WorldVu (which would later be renamed to [[OneWeb]]) had acquired the satellite spectrum that was formerly owned by SkyBridge, a company that went bankrupt in 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://qz.com//satellite-internet-is-a-space-business-widow-maker-so-why-does-elon-musk-want-in/|title=Satellite internet is a space business widow-maker\u2014so why does Elon Musk want in? \u2014 Quartz|first=Tim|last=Fernholz|website=qz.com|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> in a much earlier attempt to offer broadband Internet services via satellite.<ref name=srb20140603>{{cite news|last1=Boucher |first1=Marc|title=Will Google Build a Satellite Constellation?|url=http://spaceref.biz/company/will-google-build-a-satellite-constellation.html|accessdate=2014-06-14|publisher=SpacRef Business|date=2014-06-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716035558/http://spaceref.biz/company/will-google-build-a-satellite-constellation.html|archive-date=2014-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, the early concept had been to have at least 20 satellites operating in each of 20 different [[orbital plane]]s to provide consistent internet coverage over the surface of the Earth.<ref name=sn20140530/>\n\nBy September 2014, the WorldVu company had 30 employees, and several Google employees who had joined Google as part of the acquisition of [[O3b Networks]] in 2013 \u2014[[Greg Wyler]], [[Brian Holz]] and [[David Bettinger]]\u2014 left Google to become a part of WorldVu Satellites Ltd. The rights to the radio frequency spectrum were transferred to WorldVu. It was unclear why the WorldVu team left Google, as well as what Google's role might be in WorldVu going forward. At the time, WorldVu was working closely with [[SpaceX]] and SpaceX' founder [[Elon Musk]] to explore satellite internet services,<ref name=wsj20140802>{{cite news|title=Google Satellite Employee Greg Wyler Leaves Company|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/google-satellite-executive-greg-wyler-leaves-company-1409708338|accessdate=2014-08-03|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=2014-08-02|url-access=subscription|quote=''A key employee leading Google Inc.'s efforts to beam Internet access from satellites has left the company and is now working closely with Space Exploration Technologies Corp. and its founder Elon Musk, according to people familiar with the matter... It isn't clear why the WorldVu team departed Google.''|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905143850/http://online.wsj.com/articles/google-satellite-executive-greg-wyler-leaves-company-1409708338|archive-date=2014-09-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\nalthough no formal relationship had been established and no launch commitments had been made in 2014.<ref name=sn20140803>{{cite news |title=WorldVu, a Satellite Startup Aiming To Provide Global Internet Connectivity, Continues To Grow Absent Clear Google Relationship|url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/satellite-telecom/41755worldvu-a-satellite-startup-aiming-to-provide-global-internet|accessdate=2014-08-03|publisher=Space News|date=2014-08-03}}</ref>\n\nBy November 2014, the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that Musk and Wyler were considering options for building a [[factory]] to manufacture high-volume low-cost satellites, and that \"initial talks have been held with state officials in [[Florida]] and [[Colorado]]\"<ref name=wsj20141107/> about potentially locating a factory in those states, as well as that SpaceX would likely launch the satellites.<ref name=wsj20141107>{{cite news|last1=Winkler|first1=Rolfe|last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy|title=Elon Musk\u2019s Next Mission: Internet Satellites SpaceX, Tesla Founder Explores Venture to Make Lighter, Cheaper Satellites |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-next-mission-internet-satellites-1415390062|accessdate=2017-10-19 |work=Wall Street Journal|date=2014-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033331/https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-next-mission-internet-satellites-1415390062|archive-date=2017-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\nAlso in November, WorldVu issued a tender \"to satellite manufacturers for 640 125-kg satellites\", asking for responses by mid-December, having secured regulatory approval for use of the requisite [[electromagnetic spectrum]] [[Radio frequency|communication frequencies]] in mid-2014.<ref name=pa20141111>{{cite news |last1=Messier|first1=Doug|title=WorldVu Satellites Issues RFP for 640 Satellites |url=http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/11/11/worldvu-satellites-issues-rfp-640-satellites/|accessdate=2014-11-15|work=Parabolic Arc|date=2014-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129012801/http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/11/11/worldvu-satellites-issues-rfp-640-satellites/|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Rolfe Winkler, \"Elon Musk Confirms SpaceX Is Building Internet Satellites\", Wall Street Journal, 11/11/2014</ref>\n\nThe 2014 OneWeb solicitation to satellite manufacturers was for a total build of approximately 900 [[smallsat|small Internet-delivery satellites]], including ground and on-orbit spares. Responses were received from both European and US manufacturers including [[Airbus Defence and Space]], [[Lockheed Martin Space Systems]], [[OHB System|OHB SE]], [[SSL (company)|SSL]] and [[Thales Alenia Space]], and discussions focused on how each of these companies might \"escape their status-quo histories as major space hardware contractors and remake themselves into producers capable of producing multiple satellites per month, each with a cost of fewer than {{USD|500,000}}\".<ref name=sn20150319/> OneWeb announced that it planned to form a [[joint venture]] with the winning bidder and open a new facility for manufacturing the new [[smallsat]]s.<ref name=sn20150319>{{cite news |last1=de Selding|first1=Peter B.|title=Competition To Build OneWeb Constellation Draws 2 U.S., 3 European Companies |url=http://spacenews.com/competition-to-build-oneweb-constellation-draws-2-u-s-3-european-companies/|accessdate=20 March 2015|work=Space News|date=2015-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the ''Wall Street Journal'' reported that WorldVu, now operating under the name OneWeb Ltd, had secured funding from [[Virgin Group]] and [[Qualcomm]] to build and launch the constellation, while SpaceX was not an investor and their role in the venture was not clear. OneWeb also divulged that the planned satellites would weigh approximately 125 kg and that the plans were to deploy approximately 650 of them in [[low Earth orbit]] to operate at {{convert|1200|km|sp=us}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winkler|first1=Rolfe|title=Greg Wyler\u2019s OneWeb Satellite-Internet Company Secures Funding|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/greg-wylers-oneweb-satellite-internet-company-secures-funding-1421278832|accessdate=2015-01-15|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2015-01-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115122352/http://www.wsj.com/articles/greg-wylers-oneweb-satellite-internet-company-secures-funding-1421278832|archive-date=2015-01-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sn20150115>{{cite news |last1=de Selding |first1=Peter B. |title=Virgin, Qualcomm Invest in OneWeb Satellite Internet Venture |url=http://spacenews.com/virgin-qualcomm-invest-in-global-satellite-internet-plan/|accessdate=16 January 2015|work=SpaceNews|date=15 January 2015}}</ref> Just a few days later, Elon Musk announced the rival [[Starlink]] venture, with the opening of the [[SpaceX satellite development facility]] in [[Seattle, Washington]], with the intent of taking [[SpaceX]] itself into the business of internet provision and internet [[backhaul (telecommunications)|backhaul]] services, initially announced as aiming to build an approximately 4000 satellite constellation, with the first generation becoming operational in approximately 2020.<ref name=lat20150116>{{cite news|last1=Petersen|first1=Melody|title=Elon Musk and Richard Branson invest in satellite-Internet ventures|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-satellite-entrepreneurs-20150117-story.html|accessdate=19 January 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=16 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119045513/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-satellite-entrepreneurs-20150117-story.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe satellites for the OneWeb constellation were initially announced to be in the {{convert|250|lb|kg|disp=flip}}-class, about the same size as the two Earth-imaging satellites that were then operated by [[Skybox Imaging]], which Google [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquired]] in August 2014.<ref name=sn20150115/><ref name=syboxPress20140801>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Skybox Imaging + Google|url=http://www.skyboximaging.com/blog/skybox-imaging-google|publisher=Skybox Imaging|date=2014-08-01|accessdate=2014-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113015519/http://www.skyboximaging.com/blog/skybox-imaging-google|archive-date=2014-11-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=sfn20140610>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen |title=Google buys startup Skybox Imaging for $500 million|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/news/n1406/10google/#.U5ymfrHigfE|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=Spaceflight Now|date=2014-06-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614203846/http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n1406/10google/#.U5ymfrHigfE |archive-date=2014-06-14 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nHowever, by the following year, sources put the satellites nearer {{convert|175|-|200|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in mass.<ref name=sn20150319/><ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/>\n\nIn March 2015, OneWeb indicated that they intended to select a [[launch service provider]] by mid-2015<ref name=sn20150319/>\nand in June 2015 announced that [[Arianespace]] was contracted to provide 21 multi-sat launches on [[Arianespace Soyuz|Soyuz]] beginning in 2017 with [[Virgin Galactic]] under contract to provide<!-- aiming for neutrality here, LauncherOne has not yet even flown its first test flight as of 2015-06 --> 39 single-sat launches using its [[LauncherOne]] [[smallsat]] launch vehicle.<ref name=\"OneWebLaunchContractVirgin\">{{Cite press release|url=http://www.virgingalactic.com/press/virgin-galactic-signs-contract-with-oneweb-to-perform-39-satellite-launches/|title=Virgin Galactic Signs Contract with OneWeb to Perform 39 Satellite Launches|publisher=Virgin Galactic|place=[[Long Beach, California]]|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728110622/http://www.virgingalactic.com/press/virgin-galactic-signs-contract-with-oneweb-to-perform-39-satellite-launches/|archive-date=28 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=telegraph20150822>{{cite news |last1=Burn-Callander|first1=Rebecca|title=Virgin Galactic boldly goes into small satellites, telling future astronauts 'you have to wait' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/11816213/Virgin-Galactic-boldly-goes-into-small-satellites-telling-future-astronauts-you-have-to-wait.html|accessdate=2015-08-24|newspaper=UK Telegraph|date=22 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824021720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/11816213/Virgin-Galactic-boldly-goes-into-small-satellites-telling-future-astronauts-you-have-to-wait.html|archive-date=24 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\nBy 2015, there was also an option to use [[Ariane 6]] for up to three launches after 2021, making this the first potential contract announced for the Ariane launch vehicle.<ref name=\"bbc20150625\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-33268180|title=OneWeb satellite operator eyes huge rocket campaign|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625113620/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-33268180|archive-date=25 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"OneWebLaunchContractArianespace\">{{Cite press release|url=http://www.arianespace.com/news-press-release/2015/6-25-2015-OneWeb.asp|title=OneWeb signs agreement with Arianespace for the deployment of the OneWeb Constellation|publisher=[[Arianespace]]|place=[[\u00c9vry, Essonne|Evry]]|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626115947/http://www.arianespace.com/news-press-release/2015/6-25-2015-OneWeb.asp|archive-date=26 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"OneWebLaunchContractSpaceDigest\">{{cite web|url=http://spacedigest.net/en/articles/oneweb-takes-pole-position-in-global-satellite-internet-race|title=OneWeb takes pole-position in global satellite Internet race|quote=St\u00e9phane Isra\u00ebl, Chairman and CEO of Arianespace, noted that this was the first order for new European Ariane 6 launcher.|publisher=Space Digest|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626105358/http://spacedigest.net/en/articles/oneweb-takes-pole-position-in-global-satellite-internet-race|archive-date=26 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBy June 2015, the company had modified their plan somewhat to orbit a somewhat larger constellation of 720 satellites, operating in low Earth orbit at {{convert|1,200|km}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]],<ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/> which plan was somewhat reduced by early 2016 back to just 640 satellites planned, but still at 1,200&nbsp;km.<ref name=wsj20160203/>\n\nIn June 2015, [[Airbus Defence and Space]] was selected to build the satellites,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/06/15/oneweb-selects-airbus-to-build-900-internet-satellites/|title=OneWeb selects Airbus to build 900 Internet satellites|work=spaceflightnow.com|accessdate=16 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617054730/http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/06/15/oneweb-selects-airbus-to-build-900-internet-satellites/|archive-date=17 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sn20150615>{{cite web |url=http://spacenews.com/airbus-wins-oneweb-contract/|title=OneWeb Taps Airbus To Build 900 Internet Smallsats |work=SpaceNews |accessdate=19 June 2015 |date=2015-06-15}}</ref> and development was remained on schedule one year later with the first ten satellites still headed for a 2017 launch on a Europeanized Soyuz launch vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/one-year-after-kickoff-oneweb-says-its-700-satellite-constellation-is-on-schedule/|title=One year after kickoff, OneWeb says its 700-satellite constellation is on schedule - SpaceNews.com|date=6 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> That same month, [[Hughes Network Systems|Hughes Communications]] made an equity investment in OneWeb, and agreed to produce the ground network system for OneWeb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/echostar-now-building-oneweb-ground-network-says-company-not-a-competitor/|title=Echostar, now building OneWeb ground network, says company not a competitor|date=2017-11-09|website=SpaceNews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiercewireless.com/wireless/oneweb-signs-190m-contract-hughes-for-ground-network-to-support-leos|title=OneWeb signs $190M contract with Hughes for ground network to support LEOs|website=FierceWireless|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326202338/https://www.fiercewireless.com/wireless/oneweb-signs-190m-contract-hughes-for-ground-network-to-support-leos|archive-date=2019-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2015/06/25/branson-backed-oneweb-raises-500-million-to-build-satellite-internet/|title=Branson-Backed OneWeb Raises $500 Million To Build Satellite Internet|last=Knapp|first=Alex|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326202335/https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2015/06/25/branson-backed-oneweb-raises-500-million-to-build-satellite-internet/|archive-date=2019-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, SoftBank Group Corp agreed to invest $1 billion in OneWeb, thus becoming OneWeb's largest shareholder, with a roughly 40% stake. Another $200 million was funded at that time by its current investors, which include Qualcomm Inc, Airbus Group and Virgin Group. The transaction was expected to close in the first quarter of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pasztor|first1=Andy|title=Japan\u2019s SoftBank Invests $1 Billion in Satellite Startup OneWeb|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/satellite-startup-oneweb-raises-1-2-billion-in-funding-round-led-by-softbank-1482142137|accessdate=2017-01-19|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2016-12-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219215606/http://www.wsj.com/articles/satellite-startup-oneweb-raises-1-2-billion-in-funding-round-led-by-softbank-1482142137|archive-date=2016-12-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sn201702/>\n\nIn February 2017, OneWeb announced that it had sold most of the communication capacity of its initial 648 satellites, and was considering nearly quadrupling the size of the satellite constellation by adding 1,972 additional satellites that it has priority spectrum license rights for.<ref name=sn201702>{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-weighing-2000-more-satellites/|title=OneWeb weighing 2,000 more satellites - SpaceNews.com|date=24 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> With the original capital raise of $500 million in 2015, plus the $1 billion investment of SoftBank in 2016, previous \"investors committed to an additional $200 million, bringing OneWeb's total capital raised to $1.7 billion.\"<ref name=sn201702/>\n\nIn March 2017, OneWeb filed with the [[FCC|US regulatory authorities]] plans to field a constellation of an additional 2000 \"[[V-band]] satellites in non-[[geosynchronous orbit]]s to provide communications services\" in an electromagnetic spectrum that had not previously been \"heavily employed for commercial communications services\". This would include \"720 LEO V-band satellites at 1,200 kilometers, and another constellation in Medium Earth Orbit (MEO) of 1,280 satellites.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/fcc-gets-five-new-applications-for-non-geostationary-satellite-constellations/|title=FCC gets five new applications for non-geostationary satellite constellations - SpaceNews.com|date=2 March 2017|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome controversy arose in 2015-2017 with [[Regulatory agency|regulatory authorities]] on [[Spectrum licensing|licensing]] the [[Spectrum management|communications spectrum]] for these large constellations of satellites. The traditional and historical regulatory rule for satellites licensing of communications spectrum has been that satellite operators could \"launch a single spacecraft to meet their in-service deadline [from the regulator], a policy subsequently seen as allowing an operator to block the use of valuable radio spectrum for years without deploying its fleet.\"<ref name=sir20170904/>\nThe [[Federal Communications Commission|US regulatory authority]] has set a six-year deadline to have an entire large constellation deployed to comply with licensing terms. The [[ITU|international regulator, the ITU]], has proposed by mid-2017 an international guideline that would be considerably less restrictive. {{asof|2017|09}}, both Boeing and SpaceX have petitioned the US FCC for a waiver of the 6-year rule, while OneWeb has received FCC approval under the existing regime.<ref name=sir20170904>{{cite web|url=https://www.spaceintelreport.com/ses-asks-itu-replace-one-done-rule-satellite-constellations-new-system/|title=SES asks ITU to replace 'one and done' rule for satellite constellations with new system - Space Intel Report|date=4 September 2017|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144559/https://www.spaceintelreport.com/ses-asks-itu-replace-one-done-rule-satellite-constellations-new-system/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, it was announced that the first test satellite launch might move into 2019, and would be no earlier than mid-December 2018,<ref>[https://spacenews.com/oneweb-arianespace-target-december-february-for-first-soyuz-launch/ OneWeb, Arianespace target December-February for first Soyuz launch], 27 August 2018.</ref> and by December, was planned to be no earlier than March 2019.<ref name=sn20181213/> The satellite system is now planned to be fully online by 2027.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news |editor-first=Richard |editor-last=Balmforth |editor-first2=Alison |editor-last2=Williams |title=Exclusive: Russia opposes U.S. OneWeb satellite service, cites security concerns |first=Maria |last=Kolomychenko |publisher=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |access-date=2018-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027061506/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |archive-date=2018-10-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nAfter OneWeb had built the initial satellites and done ground testing where they found the as-built sats \"demonstrated better than expected performance\", OneWeb announced in December 2018 that the company will need only 600 satellites rather than the 900 previously planned for the initial constellation.<ref name=sn20181213>{{cite news |last=Henry|first=Caleb |url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-scales-back-constellation-by-300-satellites/ |title=OneWeb scales back baseline constellation by 300 satellites |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=13 December 2018 |accessdate=16 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn February and March 2020, OneWeb completed two successful launches of 34 satellites into orbit on a [[Soyuz (rocket family)|Soyuz rocket]] from [[Baikonur]], [[Kazakhstan]].<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/06/tech/oneweb-satellite-internet-launch-scn/index.html|title=The race for space-based broadband: OneWeb launches 34 more internet satellites|last=Business|first=Jackie Wattles, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref name=\"sn20200321\"/>\n\nThe entire network was ultimately meant to consist of 648 satellites,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Amos|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-51405079|title=OneWeb launches first big batch of satellites|date=2020-02-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> but by mid-March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] and [[2020 stock market crash|market turmoil]], OneWeb found themselves in a [[Liquidity crisis|cash crunch]]. OneWeb and all its affiliates filed for [[bankruptcy]] on 27 March 2020, after experiencing difficulties raising capital to complete the build and deployment of the remaining 90 percent of the network.<ref name=bloomberglaw20200319>{{cite news |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/bankruptcy-law/softbanks-oneweb-is-said-to-mull-bankruptcy-as-cash-dwindles |title=SoftBank\u2019s OneWeb Is Said to Mull Bankruptcy as Cash Dwindles |work=Bloomberg Law News |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\nThe effect on the previously planned ten launches in 2020 was not publicly discussed,<ref name=ars20200323>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/oneweb-launches-new-satellites-amid-questions-about-its-fiscal-health/ |title=OneWeb Says It Will Have To Cut Workers Amid Economic Crisis|work=Ars technica |last=Berger|first=Eric |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \nbut the company is maintaining its satellite operational capabilities while the company is restructured by the court, and new owners for the constellation are sought.<ref name=sn20200327>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-files-for-chapter-11-bankruptcy/ |title=OneWeb files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy |work=[[SpaceNews]] |last=Henry|first=Caleb |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Launches==\n[[File:ConstellationGPS.gif|thumb|right|A visual example of the much-smaller 24-satellite ''[[Global Positioning System]]'' constellation in motion with the Earth rotating. Notice how the number of ''satellites in view'' from a given point on the Earth's surface, in this example at 45\u00b0 N, changes with time.]]\n\nOn 27 February 2019, OneWeb successfully launched the first 6 of the 648 planned satellites (600 active plus 48 on-orbit spares) into low Earth orbit from the [[Guiana Space Centre]] in [[French Guiana]] using a Russian [[Soyuz-2|Soyuz-2 ST-B]] rocket.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|title=OneWeb makes history as first launch mission is a success|date=2019-02-28|work=OneWeb|access-date=2019-02-28|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228183229/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|archive-date=2019-02-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\nAlso on that date at the [[Mobile World Congress|MWC2019]], OneWeb announced that it signed its first two client agreements with [[Talia (company)|Talia Ltd]] for their Quika low latency broadband service to Africa and the Middle East and [[Intermatica|Intermatica S.p.A]] for service to Europe, marking the beginning of its commercialization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|title=OneWeb Announces First Two Client Agreements - Start of Commercial Network Commercialisation|date=2019-02-27|work=OneWeb |access-date=2019-02-27|language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512165012/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|archivedate=2019-05-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> \nAdditional launches are expected for early 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/onewebs-first-big-deployment-launch-slips-to-january/|title=OneWeb\u2019s first big deployment launch slips to January|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===List of launches===\nIn November 2019, OneWeb planned monthly launches to begin in January 2020,<ref name=\"Flight2_spacenews\">{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/onewebs-first-big-deployment-launch-slips-to-january/|title=OneWeb\u2019s first big deployment launch slips to January|date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> although the first of these launches was delayed to early February 2020.<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Flight \u2116\n! scope=\"col\" | Date/Time ([[UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\" | Launch site\n! scope=\"col\" | Launch vehicle\n! scope=\"col\" | Number deployed\n! scope=\"col\" | Outcome\n|-\n|0\n|27 February 2019\n|[[Centre Spatial Guyanais|Kourou]], [[Ensemble de Lancement Soyouz|ELS]]\n|[[Soyuz ST-B]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|6 (test satellites)\n|{{Success}} \n|-\n|1\n|6 February 2020<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\" />\n|[[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Baikonur, Site 31/6]]\n|[[Soyuz-2.1b]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|34\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|2\n|21 March 2020<ref name=\"sn20200321\"/>\n|[[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Baikonur, Site 31/6]]\n|[[Soyuz-2.1b]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|34\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|3\n|2020<ref name=\"SFN launch schedule>{{cite web|name=Launch Schedule|publisher=[[Spaceflight Now]]|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Centre Spatial Guyanais|Kourou]], [[Ensemble de Lancement Soyouz|ELS]]\n|[[Soyuz ST-B]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|36\n|{{Planned}}\n|}\n\n==Design characteristics==\nThe satellites in the OneWeb constellation are approximately {{convert|150|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in mass,<ref name=sn20190227/> a bit smaller than the 2015 design estimate of {{convert|175|-|200|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=sn20150319/><ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/> The 648 operational satellites are to operate in 18 [[polar orbit]] planes at {{convert|1,200|km}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]].<ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/><ref name=spacenewsinterview>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/in-conversation-with-oneweb-founder-greg-wyler/|title=Why OneWeb is Eager To Be the 'Clean-up Crew of Connectivity' - SpaceNews.com|date=20 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe satellites will operate in the [[Ku band]], communicating in the microwave range of frequencies in the 12\u201318&nbsp;GHz portion of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]].<ref name=sn20140530/><ref name=sn20150115/>\nThe satellites use a technique called \"[[progressive pitch]]\" in which the satellites are slightly turned to avoid interference with Ku-band satellites in [[geostationary]] orbit. The user terminal [[Antenna (radio)|antenna]] on the ground will be a [[phased array]] antenna measuring approximately {{convert|36|by|16|cm|sp=us}} and will provide [[Internet]] access at 50 megabits/second downlink bandwidth<ref name=sn20150115/> (almost certainly less uplink, but this number remains hard to pin down).{{cn|date=March 2019}} \n\nThe satellites will be designed to comply with \"[[Space debris mitigation|orbital debris-mitigation]] guidelines for removing satellites from orbit and, for low-orbit satellites, assuring that they reenter the Earth's atmosphere within 25 years of retirement\".<ref name=sn20150615/>{{update after|2019|3|4}}<!-- this has changed; while 25 years was the old standard US/European/Russian government goal for their satellites, OneWeb subsequently designed this for a much more rapid deorbit following end of life for the satellite; need to find the source -->\n{{clear left}}\n==Manufacturing and constellation rollout==\nThe constellation was originally announced in June 2014 to be just half of the total of approximately 720 satellites. A quarter of the satellites were to make up the initial constellation, and these would operate in the lower of the two proposed orbits, at approximately {{convert|850|km}}.<ref name=srb20140603/> The initial constellation would presumably be raised or lowered into its final orbital altitude of either {{convert|800|km}} or {{convert|950|km}} as consumer and business use of the broadband service grows over time.<ref name=sn20140530>{{cite news |last1=de Selding|first1=Peter B. |title=Google-backed Global Broadband Venture Secures Spectrum for Satellite Network |url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/satellite-telecom/40736google-backed-global-broadband-venture-secures-spectrum-for-satellite |accessdate=2014-06-14 |publisher=SpaceNews |date=2014-05-30 }}</ref>\nBy early 2015, OneWeb indicated that the first launches would occur no earlier than 2017.<ref name=sn20150115/>\n\n[[File:OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility, Merritt Island, Florida, 2019 01.jpg|thumb|upright=2|OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility in Merritt Island, Florida]]\n\nIn February 2016, OneWeb announced that they would set up an assembly and test facility in [[Florida]] with plans to assemble and launch the majority of the satellites by the end of 2019, while manufacturing an additional 250 of the {{convert|300|lb|kg|disp=flip|adj=mid|-satellites}} as spares to be used in later years.<ref name=wsj20160203>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/oneweb-satellite-startup-to-set-up-manufacturing-in-florida-1454523492 |title=OneWeb Satellite Startup to Set up Manufacturing in Florida|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2016-01-03|accessdate=2016-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203231155/http://www.wsj.com/articles/oneweb-satellite-startup-to-set-up-manufacturing-in-florida-1454523492 |archive-date=2016-02-03 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the actual orbital deployment of the constellation began, in February 2019, the planned constellation size had settled once again at 648, near the original projection, with 600 active satellites with 48 on-orbit spares.<ref name=sn20190227>{{cite news |last=Henry|first=Caleb |url=https://spacenews.com/first-six-oneweb-satellites-launch-on-soyuz-rocket/ |title=OneWeb\u2019s first six satellites in orbit following Soyuz launch |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=4 March 2019 }}</ref> Each satellite costs \u00a3830,000 (around US$1 million) to build.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-7344829/Adrian-Steckel-rocketman-wholl-launch-34-satellites-MONTH.html|title=Adrian Steckel: The rocketman who\u2019ll launch 34 satellites every MONTH \u2013 and beam broadband across Britain|date=11 August 2019|access-date=13 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813211141/https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-7344829/Adrian-Steckel-rocketman-wholl-launch-34-satellites-MONTH.html|archive-date=13 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, OneWeb reached a production rate of two satellites per day. In February the company launched its first large batch of satellites.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-plans-april-launch-break-to-tweak-satellite-design/|title=OneWeb plans April launch break to tweak satellite design|date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/02/04/first-satellites-off-onewebs-new-florida-assembly-line-set-for-launch-this-week/|title=Watch live: First satellites off OneWeb\u2019s new Florida assembly line are launched|date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Concerns==\n\n===End-of-life concerns===\nWith such a large number of satellites being added to the already crowded low Earth orbit, plans for handling the satellites once the [[End-of-life (product)|operational life of each satellite is completed]] are an important consideration. The region between {{convert|600|and|1,000|km}} is already the most congested orbital regime around Earth, and concerns about adding to the existing [[space debris]] problem have been expressed.<ref name=srb20140603/> There could be a new regime of [[graveyard orbit]]s added, similar to those in use for decades to handle post-operational [[commsat]]s that operated in the [[geostationary belt]]; however at the orbital altitudes envisioned for OneWeb, the disposal orbit may not have a sufficiently long life to assure long-term stability.<ref name=ars20171004/>\n\nAn alternative that has been proposed for years is to introduce the capability to retrieve derelict objects for near-space clean up and then either [[deorbit]] the satellite or do some sort of in-space [[recycling]] of the satellite materials. Several technical approaches have been proposed, but there has been no legal framework to date that has required satellite operators to clean up the [[negative externality]] of their derelict satellites. New approaches offer the technical prospect of markedly reducing the cost of object capture and deorbit with the implementation of a one-up/one-down [[launch license]] regime to Earth orbits that would require satellite operators to remove one spacecraft for each one deployed.<ref name=aiaa20100902_p13 >{{cite web |last=Zegler |first=Frank |title=Evolving to a Depot-Based Space Transportation Architecture |url=http://www.ulalaunch.com/uploads/docs/Published_Papers/Exploration/DepotBasedTransportationArchitecture2010.pdf |work=AIAA SPACE 2010 Conference & Exposition |publisher=AIAA |accessdate=2014-06-14 |author2=Bernard Kutter |date=2010-09-02 |pages=13\u201314 |quote=''for disposing of these obsolete or derelict spacecraft all [approaches] involve the expenditure of substantially more delta-V than what has been traditional. It may well be required that old spacecraft be removed at the same time new spacecraft are being emplaced... [this architecture] anticipates the task of removing derelict spacecraft by providing an infrastructure to permit these high \u0394V missions and enables the likely new paradigm of removing a spacecraft for each one deployed.'' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624125633/http://www.ulalaunch.com/uploads/docs/Published_Papers/Exploration/DepotBasedTransportationArchitecture2010.pdf |archive-date=2014-06-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy October 2017, OneWeb had filed documents with the US [[FCC]] with their space debris mitigation plan. OneWeb \"satellites are designed for mission lives of at least five years, and 'the post-mission disposal operation is anticipated to take less than one year'. OneWeb also said it has designed its satellite network to avoid collisions with space stations and debris, and that OneWeb 'will actively and regularly screen for conjunctions between its own satellites and other objects in the [[Joint Space Operations Center]]'s ('JSpOC') published catalog.\"<ref name=ars20171004>{{cite news |last=Brodkin |first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/spacex-and-oneweb-broadband-satellites-raise-fears-about-space-debris/ |title=SpaceX and OneWeb broadband satellites raise fears about space debris |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=2017-10-04 |accessdate=2017-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006232900/https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/spacex-and-oneweb-broadband-satellites-raise-fears-about-space-debris/|archive-date=2017-10-06 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Interference with other Earth-bound transceivers===\nOneWeb competitor, satellite fleet operator [[ABS (company)|ABS]], has expressed concerns about the amount of [[electromagnetic interference]] that the OneWeb constellation could add to existing terrestrial transceivers.<ref>[http://spacenews.com/oneweb-gets-slide-decked-by-competitor-at-casbaa/ OneWeb Gets (Slide) Decked by Competitor at CASBAA], SpaceNews, 28 October 2015, accessed 2015-10-29.<!-- article includes technical details by republishing the slide deck. --></ref>\n\n===Russian security concerns===\nVladimir Sadovnikov of the [[Federal Security Service]] stated that the FSB was opposed to OneWeb covering [[Russia]], said that OneWeb could be used for espionage purposes.<ref name=\"reuters20181024\">{{cite news |editor-first=Richard |editor-last=Balmforth |editor-first2=Alison |editor-last2=Williams |title=Exclusive: Russia opposes U.S. OneWeb satellite service, cites security concerns |first=Maria |last=Kolomychenko |publisher=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303141435/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |archive-date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> OneWeb's request for a frequency band was previously rejected by the Ministry for Digital Development and Communications, purportedly due to outstanding legal issues.<ref name=\"reuters20181024\"/> FSB also proposed increasing scrutiny on other [[Satellite Internet access|satellite Internet]] equipment in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://roskomsvoboda.org/42992/ |title=\u0421\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0442 vs \u0424\u0421\u0411: \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0446\u0438\u044f? |website=roskomsvoboda.org |access-date=2018-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115195405/https://roskomsvoboda.org/42992/ |archive-date=2018-11-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Competition==\nCompetition to OneWeb for producing smaller and lower-cost satellites, in general, is thought to come \"from other makers of [[Small satellite|small satellites]], such as Nevada-based [[Sierra Nevada Corporation|Sierra Nevada Corp.]] and Britain's [[Surrey Satellite Technology|Surrey Satellite Technology Ltd.]]\"<ref name=wsj20141107/> In broadband [[Internet service provider|internet service provision]] more specifically, there are a large number of [[Substitute good|alternatives]] to the proposed WorldVu satellite broadband service, mostly involving [[Internet access|wired]] and [[Wireless Internet service provider|terrestrial radio]] broadband service.\n\nOther potential competitors in the satellite internet space are [[SpaceX]]'s proposed 12,000-satellite [[Starlink]] and a 2015 proposal from [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]] outlining a 4,600-satellite constellation orbiting at {{convert|900|mi|km|disp=flip|sp=us}} that could bring 200 gigabytes per month of internet data to \"5 billion users worldwide\".<ref name=ps20150817>{{cite news |last1=Gershgorn |first1=Dave |title=Samsung Wants To Blanket The Earth In Satellite Internet |url=http://www.popsci.com/samsung-wants-launch-thousands-satellites-bring-everyone-earth-internet |accessdate=2015-08-21 |work=Popular Science |date=2015-08-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820193642/http://www.popsci.com/samsung-wants-launch-thousands-satellites-bring-everyone-earth-internet |archive-date=2015-08-20 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=MobileInternet>{{cite arxiv |last1=Khan|first1=Farooq |title=Mobile Internet from the Heavens |eprint=1508.02383|class=cs.NI|year=2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] announced a large broadband internet satellite constellation in April 2019, planning to launch 3,236 satellites in the next decade in what Amazon calls \"[[Project Kuiper]]\", a [[satellite constellation]] that will work in concert<ref name=cnbc20190404>{{cite news |last=Sheetz |first=Michael |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/amazon-project-kuiper-broadband-internet-small-satellite-network.html |title=Amazon wants to launch thousands of satellites so it can offer broadband internet from space |work=[[CNBC]] |date=4 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404151556/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/amazon-project-kuiper-broadband-internet-small-satellite-network.html |archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\nwith Amazon's previously-announced large network of 12 satellite ground station facilities (the \"[[Amazon Web Services|AWS]] Ground Station unit\") announced in November 2018.<ref name=cnbc20181127>{{cite news |last=Sheetz |first=Michael |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/27/amazon-launches-aws-ground-station-satellite-data-collection-service.html |title=Amazon cloud business reaches into space with satellite connection service |work=[[CNBC]]|date=27 November 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407001146/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/27/amazon-launches-aws-ground-station-satellite-data-collection-service.html|archive-date=7 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, earlier companies that have attempted to build satellite internet service networks and provide space-based internet connections have not fared well, as both services were hobbled by high costs which consequently attracted few users. [[Iridium Communications|Iridium SSC]] filed for bankruptcy protection in 1999 and [[Globalstar]] did the same in 2002.<ref name=wsj20141107/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Iridium satellite constellation]] \u2014 an operational constellation of 66 active satellites used to provide global satellite phone service\n*[[Orbcomm]] \u2014 an operational constellation used to provide global asset monitoring and messaging services from its constellation of 29 LEO communications satellites orbiting at 775&nbsp;km\n*[[Starlink]] \u2014 A satellite constellation development project underway by [[SpaceX]] to deploy nearly 12,000 satellites in three orbital shells by the mid-2020s\n*[[Teledesic]] \u2014 a former (1990s) venture to accomplish broadband satellite internet services\n*[[Viasat, Inc.]] \u2014 a current broadband satellite provider providing fixed, ground mobile, and airborne antennas\n*[[Kymeta]] \u2014 small form factor satellite antennas for mobile terrestrial applications\n*[[Hughes Communications|Hughes Network Systems]] \u2013 a subsidiary of [[EchoStar]]\n\n== Literature ==\n* ''Derek Webber''. No Bucks, No Buck Rogers: The Business of Commercial Space. \u2014 Universal-Publishers, 2017. \u2014 P. 248. \u2014 296 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9781627340915}}.\n* ''Alessandra Vernile''. The Rise of Private Actors in the Space Sector. \u2014 Springer, 2018. \u2014 P. 37. \u2014 121 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9783319738024}}.\n* ''John Bloom''. Eccentric Orbits: The Iridium Story. \u2014 Grove/Atlantic, Inc., 2016. \u2014 577 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9780802192820}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2015-01-22/global-internet-greg-wyler-may-beat-elon-musk-google-facebook The New Space Race: One Man's Mission to Build a Galactic Internet], ''Bloomberg Businessweek'', 22 January 2015.\n* [http://spacenews.com/in-conversation-with-oneweb-founder-greg-wyler/ In Conversation with OneWeb Founder Greg Wyler], SpaceNews, 20 November 2015.<!-- long-form interview coverage by SpaceNews: snippets include 21 Arianespace/Soyuz launches; first launch in 2017; $500M venture funding in round 1; rd 2 in c. 18 mos.; Ku-band equatorial interference issue; 2025 goal \"every village\"; orbital debris issue and OneWeb actions; deorbit plan and highly-fault tolerant system design to deorbit at end-of-life using propulsion to bring sats down to c. 185 km for sub-5-year lefe (will \"definitely be less than the 25 year\" nominal standard, and design point is less than 5 years).  -->\n* [http://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/10/30/orig-ff-satellite-internet-oneweb-pioneers.cnn Internet for Everyone, Everywhere - CNN], CNN, 30 October 2015.\n\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Communications satellite constellations]]\n[[Category:Private spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Google]]\n[[Category:Satellite Internet access]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Proposed constellation}}\n{{Infobox spacecraft class\n| name                 = OneWeb satellite constellation\n| image                = KSC-20170316-PH KLS01 0007~orig.jpg\n| image_caption        = Model of a OneWeb satellite\n| image_size           = 300px\n\n| manufacturer         = [[OneWeb Satellites]]<br/>({{small|[[OneWeb]] & [[Airbus Defence and Space|Airbus]]}})\n| country              = [[United States]]\n| operator             = [[OneWeb]]\n\n<!--Specifications-->\n| spacecraft_type      = [[Small satellite]]\n| launch_mass          = {{cvt|150|kg}}<ref name=sn20190227/>\n| applications         = [[Satellite Internet access|Internet service]]\n| equipment            = [[Ku band|K<sub>u</sub> band]] antennas\n| orbits               = [[Polar orbit|Polar]] [[low Earth orbit]]<br/>({{cvt|1200|km|disp=comma}})\n\n<!--Production-->\n| status               = \n| launched             = 74\n| operational          = \n| first                = 27 February 2019\n| last                 = 21 March 2020\n\n<!--insignia-->\n| insignia             = OneWeb Logo.png\n| insignia_alt         = OneWeb logo\n| insignia_size        = 270px\n}}\n\nThe '''OneWeb satellite constellation''' (formerly WorldVu) was a planned initial 650-[[artificial satellite|satellite]] [[satellite constellation|constellation]] that was in the process of being built out in 2019\u20132020, with a goal to provide global [[satellite internet constellation|satellite]] [[Internet]] broadband services to people everywhere and was previously aiming to provide global services starting in 2021. The constellation was being deployed by [[OneWeb]], formerly known as WorldVu Satellites and headquartered in London, UK with offices in California, Florida, Virginia, Dubai and Singapore. \n\nOneWeb declared bankruptcy in late March 2020, and has laid off most of their employees, but is maintaining the satellite operations center for the approximately 70 satellites already in orbit while the court determines disposition of the OneWeb assets.\n\nIn total 74 satellites were launched before the bankruptcy. The first six test satellites were launched in February 2019;<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/02/27/first-six-oneweb-satellites-launched-from-french-guiana/|title=First six OneWeb satellites launched from French Guiana|last=Clark|first=Stephen|date=2019-02-27|website=Spaceflight Now|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228192401/https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/02/27/first-six-oneweb-satellites-launched-from-french-guiana/|archive-date=2019-02-28|access-date=2019-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> the first large batch of 34 satellites was launched in February 2020,<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\" /> another 34 satellites were put into orbit in March 2020.\n\nThe [[Small satellite|small satellites]] were built by OneWeb Satellites, a joint venture between [[Airbus Defence and Space|Airbus]] and OneWeb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/what-airbus-learned-from-building-satellites-with-oneweb/|title=What Airbus learned from building satellites with OneWeb|date=2019-03-19|website=SpaceNews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref> The satellites are operating in a [[circular orbit|circular]] [[low Earth orbit]], at approximately {{convert|1200|km|mi|sp=us|sigfig=2}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]],<ref name=wsj20160203/> transmitting and receiving in the [[Ku band]] of the [[radio frequency spectrum]].<ref name=sn20140530/> Prior to the bankruptcy, OneWeb had been considering nearly quadrupling the size of the satellite constellation over time by adding 1,972 additional satellites that it has priority spectrum rights to.<ref name=sn201702/>\n\n==History==\nEarly reports of the potential involvement of [[Google]] in offering broadband internet services surfaced in February 2014, when a \"very large [satellite] constellation\" was rumored to be as large as 1,600 satellites.<ref name=pa20140216>{{cite news|last1=Messier|first1=Doug|title=Is Google Planning Son of Teledesic?|url=http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/02/16/google-planning-son-teledesic/|accessdate=2014-06-14|publisher=Parabolic Arc|date=2014-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702125309/http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/02/16/google-planning-son-teledesic/|archive-date=2014-07-02|url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy June 2014, WorldVu (which would later be renamed to [[OneWeb]]) had acquired the satellite spectrum that was formerly owned by SkyBridge, a company that went bankrupt in 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://qz.com//satellite-internet-is-a-space-business-widow-maker-so-why-does-elon-musk-want-in/|title=Satellite internet is a space business widow-maker\u2014so why does Elon Musk want in? \u2014 Quartz|first=Tim|last=Fernholz|website=qz.com|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> in a much earlier attempt to offer broadband Internet services via satellite.<ref name=srb20140603>{{cite news|last1=Boucher |first1=Marc|title=Will Google Build a Satellite Constellation?|url=http://spaceref.biz/company/will-google-build-a-satellite-constellation.html|accessdate=2014-06-14|publisher=SpacRef Business|date=2014-06-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716035558/http://spaceref.biz/company/will-google-build-a-satellite-constellation.html|archive-date=2014-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, the early concept had been to have at least 20 satellites operating in each of 20 different [[orbital plane]]s to provide consistent internet coverage over the surface of the Earth.<ref name=sn20140530/>\n\nBy September 2014, the WorldVu company had 30 employees, and several Google employees who had joined Google as part of the acquisition of [[O3b Networks]] in 2013 \u2014[[Greg Wyler]], [[Brian Holz]] and [[David Bettinger]]\u2014 left Google to become a part of WorldVu Satellites Ltd. The rights to the radio frequency spectrum were transferred to WorldVu. It was unclear why the WorldVu team left Google, as well as what Google's role might be in WorldVu going forward. At the time, WorldVu was working closely with [[SpaceX]] and SpaceX' founder [[Elon Musk]] to explore satellite internet services,<ref name=wsj20140802>{{cite news|title=Google Satellite Employee Greg Wyler Leaves Company|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/google-satellite-executive-greg-wyler-leaves-company-1409708338|accessdate=2014-08-03|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=2014-08-02|url-access=subscription|quote=''A key employee leading Google Inc.'s efforts to beam Internet access from satellites has left the company and is now working closely with Space Exploration Technologies Corp. and its founder Elon Musk, according to people familiar with the matter... It isn't clear why the WorldVu team departed Google.''|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905143850/http://online.wsj.com/articles/google-satellite-executive-greg-wyler-leaves-company-1409708338|archive-date=2014-09-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\nalthough no formal relationship had been established and no launch commitments had been made in 2014.<ref name=sn20140803>{{cite news |title=WorldVu, a Satellite Startup Aiming To Provide Global Internet Connectivity, Continues To Grow Absent Clear Google Relationship|url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/satellite-telecom/41755worldvu-a-satellite-startup-aiming-to-provide-global-internet|accessdate=2014-08-03|publisher=Space News|date=2014-08-03}}</ref>\n\nBy November 2014, the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that Musk and Wyler were considering options for building a [[factory]] to manufacture high-volume low-cost satellites, and that \"initial talks have been held with state officials in [[Florida]] and [[Colorado]]\"<ref name=wsj20141107/> about potentially locating a factory in those states, as well as that SpaceX would likely launch the satellites.<ref name=wsj20141107>{{cite news|last1=Winkler|first1=Rolfe|last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy|title=Elon Musk\u2019s Next Mission: Internet Satellites SpaceX, Tesla Founder Explores Venture to Make Lighter, Cheaper Satellites |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-next-mission-internet-satellites-1415390062|accessdate=2017-10-19 |work=Wall Street Journal|date=2014-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033331/https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-next-mission-internet-satellites-1415390062|archive-date=2017-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\nAlso in November, WorldVu issued a tender \"to satellite manufacturers for 640 125-kg satellites\", asking for responses by mid-December, having secured regulatory approval for use of the requisite [[electromagnetic spectrum]] [[Radio frequency|communication frequencies]] in mid-2014.<ref name=pa20141111>{{cite news |last1=Messier|first1=Doug|title=WorldVu Satellites Issues RFP for 640 Satellites |url=http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/11/11/worldvu-satellites-issues-rfp-640-satellites/|accessdate=2014-11-15|work=Parabolic Arc|date=2014-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129012801/http://www.parabolicarc.com/2014/11/11/worldvu-satellites-issues-rfp-640-satellites/|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Rolfe Winkler, \"Elon Musk Confirms SpaceX Is Building Internet Satellites\", Wall Street Journal, 11/11/2014</ref>\n\nThe 2014 OneWeb solicitation to satellite manufacturers was for a total build of approximately 900 [[smallsat|small Internet-delivery satellites]], including ground and on-orbit spares. Responses were received from both European and US manufacturers including [[Airbus Defence and Space]], [[Lockheed Martin Space Systems]], [[OHB System|OHB SE]], [[SSL (company)|SSL]] and [[Thales Alenia Space]], and discussions focused on how each of these companies might \"escape their status-quo histories as major space hardware contractors and remake themselves into producers capable of producing multiple satellites per month, each with a cost of fewer than {{USD|500,000}}\".<ref name=sn20150319/> OneWeb announced that it planned to form a [[joint venture]] with the winning bidder and open a new facility for manufacturing the new [[smallsat]]s.<ref name=sn20150319>{{cite news |last1=de Selding|first1=Peter B.|title=Competition To Build OneWeb Constellation Draws 2 U.S., 3 European Companies |url=http://spacenews.com/competition-to-build-oneweb-constellation-draws-2-u-s-3-european-companies/|accessdate=20 March 2015|work=Space News|date=2015-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the ''Wall Street Journal'' reported that WorldVu, now operating under the name OneWeb Ltd, had secured funding from [[Virgin Group]] and [[Qualcomm]] to build and launch the constellation, while SpaceX was not an investor and their role in the venture was not clear. OneWeb also divulged that the planned satellites would weigh approximately 125 kg and that the plans were to deploy approximately 650 of them in [[low Earth orbit]] to operate at {{convert|1200|km|sp=us}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winkler|first1=Rolfe|title=Greg Wyler\u2019s OneWeb Satellite-Internet Company Secures Funding|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/greg-wylers-oneweb-satellite-internet-company-secures-funding-1421278832|accessdate=2015-01-15|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2015-01-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115122352/http://www.wsj.com/articles/greg-wylers-oneweb-satellite-internet-company-secures-funding-1421278832|archive-date=2015-01-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sn20150115>{{cite news |last1=de Selding |first1=Peter B. |title=Virgin, Qualcomm Invest in OneWeb Satellite Internet Venture |url=http://spacenews.com/virgin-qualcomm-invest-in-global-satellite-internet-plan/|accessdate=16 January 2015|work=SpaceNews|date=15 January 2015}}</ref> Just a few days later, Elon Musk announced the rival [[Starlink]] venture, with the opening of the [[SpaceX satellite development facility]] in [[Seattle, Washington]], with the intent of taking [[SpaceX]] itself into the business of internet provision and internet [[backhaul (telecommunications)|backhaul]] services, initially announced as aiming to build an approximately 4000 satellite constellation, with the first generation becoming operational in approximately 2020.<ref name=lat20150116>{{cite news|last1=Petersen|first1=Melody|title=Elon Musk and Richard Branson invest in satellite-Internet ventures|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-satellite-entrepreneurs-20150117-story.html|accessdate=19 January 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=16 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119045513/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-satellite-entrepreneurs-20150117-story.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe satellites for the OneWeb constellation were initially announced to be in the {{convert|250|lb|kg|disp=flip}}-class, about the same size as the two Earth-imaging satellites that were then operated by [[Skybox Imaging]], which Google [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquired]] in August 2014.<ref name=sn20150115/><ref name=syboxPress20140801>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Skybox Imaging + Google|url=http://www.skyboximaging.com/blog/skybox-imaging-google|publisher=Skybox Imaging|date=2014-08-01|accessdate=2014-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113015519/http://www.skyboximaging.com/blog/skybox-imaging-google|archive-date=2014-11-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=sfn20140610>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen |title=Google buys startup Skybox Imaging for $500 million|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/news/n1406/10google/#.U5ymfrHigfE|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=Spaceflight Now|date=2014-06-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614203846/http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n1406/10google/#.U5ymfrHigfE |archive-date=2014-06-14 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nHowever, by the following year, sources put the satellites nearer {{convert|175|-|200|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in mass.<ref name=sn20150319/><ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/>\n\nIn March 2015, OneWeb indicated that they intended to select a [[launch service provider]] by mid-2015<ref name=sn20150319/>\nand in June 2015 announced that [[Arianespace]] was contracted to provide 21 multi-sat launches on [[Arianespace Soyuz|Soyuz]] beginning in 2017 with [[Virgin Galactic]] under contract to provide<!-- aiming for neutrality here, LauncherOne has not yet even flown its first test flight as of 2015-06 --> 39 single-sat launches using its [[LauncherOne]] [[smallsat]] launch vehicle.<ref name=\"OneWebLaunchContractVirgin\">{{Cite press release|url=http://www.virgingalactic.com/press/virgin-galactic-signs-contract-with-oneweb-to-perform-39-satellite-launches/|title=Virgin Galactic Signs Contract with OneWeb to Perform 39 Satellite Launches|publisher=Virgin Galactic|place=[[Long Beach, California]]|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728110622/http://www.virgingalactic.com/press/virgin-galactic-signs-contract-with-oneweb-to-perform-39-satellite-launches/|archive-date=28 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=telegraph20150822>{{cite news |last1=Burn-Callander|first1=Rebecca|title=Virgin Galactic boldly goes into small satellites, telling future astronauts 'you have to wait' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/11816213/Virgin-Galactic-boldly-goes-into-small-satellites-telling-future-astronauts-you-have-to-wait.html|accessdate=2015-08-24|newspaper=UK Telegraph|date=22 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824021720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/11816213/Virgin-Galactic-boldly-goes-into-small-satellites-telling-future-astronauts-you-have-to-wait.html|archive-date=24 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\nBy 2015, there was also an option to use [[Ariane 6]] for up to three launches after 2021, making this the first potential contract announced for the Ariane launch vehicle.<ref name=\"bbc20150625\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-33268180|title=OneWeb satellite operator eyes huge rocket campaign|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625113620/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-33268180|archive-date=25 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"OneWebLaunchContractArianespace\">{{Cite press release|url=http://www.arianespace.com/news-press-release/2015/6-25-2015-OneWeb.asp|title=OneWeb signs agreement with Arianespace for the deployment of the OneWeb Constellation|publisher=[[Arianespace]]|place=[[\u00c9vry, Essonne|Evry]]|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626115947/http://www.arianespace.com/news-press-release/2015/6-25-2015-OneWeb.asp|archive-date=26 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"OneWebLaunchContractSpaceDigest\">{{cite web|url=http://spacedigest.net/en/articles/oneweb-takes-pole-position-in-global-satellite-internet-race|title=OneWeb takes pole-position in global satellite Internet race|quote=St\u00e9phane Isra\u00ebl, Chairman and CEO of Arianespace, noted that this was the first order for new European Ariane 6 launcher.|publisher=Space Digest|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626105358/http://spacedigest.net/en/articles/oneweb-takes-pole-position-in-global-satellite-internet-race|archive-date=26 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBy June 2015, the company had modified their plan somewhat to orbit a somewhat larger constellation of 720 satellites, operating in low Earth orbit at {{convert|1,200|km}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]],<ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/> which plan was somewhat reduced by early 2016 back to just 640 satellites planned, but still at 1,200&nbsp;km.<ref name=wsj20160203/>\n\nIn June 2015, [[Airbus Defence and Space]] was selected to build the satellites,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/06/15/oneweb-selects-airbus-to-build-900-internet-satellites/|title=OneWeb selects Airbus to build 900 Internet satellites|work=spaceflightnow.com|accessdate=16 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617054730/http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/06/15/oneweb-selects-airbus-to-build-900-internet-satellites/|archive-date=17 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sn20150615>{{cite web |url=http://spacenews.com/airbus-wins-oneweb-contract/|title=OneWeb Taps Airbus To Build 900 Internet Smallsats |work=SpaceNews |accessdate=19 June 2015 |date=2015-06-15}}</ref> and development was remained on schedule one year later with the first ten satellites still headed for a 2017 launch on a Europeanized Soyuz launch vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/one-year-after-kickoff-oneweb-says-its-700-satellite-constellation-is-on-schedule/|title=One year after kickoff, OneWeb says its 700-satellite constellation is on schedule - SpaceNews.com|date=6 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> That same month, [[Hughes Network Systems|Hughes Communications]] made an equity investment in OneWeb, and agreed to produce the ground network system for OneWeb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/echostar-now-building-oneweb-ground-network-says-company-not-a-competitor/|title=Echostar, now building OneWeb ground network, says company not a competitor|date=2017-11-09|website=SpaceNews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiercewireless.com/wireless/oneweb-signs-190m-contract-hughes-for-ground-network-to-support-leos|title=OneWeb signs $190M contract with Hughes for ground network to support LEOs|website=FierceWireless|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326202338/https://www.fiercewireless.com/wireless/oneweb-signs-190m-contract-hughes-for-ground-network-to-support-leos|archive-date=2019-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2015/06/25/branson-backed-oneweb-raises-500-million-to-build-satellite-internet/|title=Branson-Backed OneWeb Raises $500 Million To Build Satellite Internet|last=Knapp|first=Alex|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326202335/https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2015/06/25/branson-backed-oneweb-raises-500-million-to-build-satellite-internet/|archive-date=2019-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, SoftBank Group Corp agreed to invest $1 billion in OneWeb, thus becoming OneWeb's largest shareholder, with a roughly 40% stake. Another $200 million was funded at that time by its current investors, which include Qualcomm Inc, Airbus Group and Virgin Group. The transaction was expected to close in the first quarter of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pasztor|first1=Andy|title=Japan\u2019s SoftBank Invests $1 Billion in Satellite Startup OneWeb|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/satellite-startup-oneweb-raises-1-2-billion-in-funding-round-led-by-softbank-1482142137|accessdate=2017-01-19|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2016-12-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219215606/http://www.wsj.com/articles/satellite-startup-oneweb-raises-1-2-billion-in-funding-round-led-by-softbank-1482142137|archive-date=2016-12-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=sn201702/>\n\nIn February 2017, OneWeb announced that it had sold most of the communication capacity of its initial 648 satellites, and was considering nearly quadrupling the size of the satellite constellation by adding 1,972 additional satellites that it has priority spectrum license rights for.<ref name=sn201702>{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-weighing-2000-more-satellites/|title=OneWeb weighing 2,000 more satellites - SpaceNews.com|date=24 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> With the original capital raise of $500 million in 2015, plus the $1 billion investment of SoftBank in 2016, previous \"investors committed to an additional $200 million, bringing OneWeb's total capital raised to $1.7 billion.\"<ref name=sn201702/>\n\nIn March 2017, OneWeb filed with the [[FCC|US regulatory authorities]] plans to field a constellation of an additional 2000 \"[[V-band]] satellites in non-[[geosynchronous orbit]]s to provide communications services\" in an electromagnetic spectrum that had not previously been \"heavily employed for commercial communications services\". This would include \"720 LEO V-band satellites at 1,200 kilometers, and another constellation in Medium Earth Orbit (MEO) of 1,280 satellites.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/fcc-gets-five-new-applications-for-non-geostationary-satellite-constellations/|title=FCC gets five new applications for non-geostationary satellite constellations - SpaceNews.com|date=2 March 2017|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome controversy arose in 2015-2017 with [[Regulatory agency|regulatory authorities]] on [[Spectrum licensing|licensing]] the [[Spectrum management|communications spectrum]] for these large constellations of satellites. The traditional and historical regulatory rule for satellites licensing of communications spectrum has been that satellite operators could \"launch a single spacecraft to meet their in-service deadline [from the regulator], a policy subsequently seen as allowing an operator to block the use of valuable radio spectrum for years without deploying its fleet.\"<ref name=sir20170904/>\nThe [[Federal Communications Commission|US regulatory authority]] has set a six-year deadline to have an entire large constellation deployed to comply with licensing terms. The [[ITU|international regulator, the ITU]], has proposed by mid-2017 an international guideline that would be considerably less restrictive. {{asof|2017|09}}, both Boeing and SpaceX have petitioned the US FCC for a waiver of the 6-year rule, while OneWeb has received FCC approval under the existing regime.<ref name=sir20170904>{{cite web|url=https://www.spaceintelreport.com/ses-asks-itu-replace-one-done-rule-satellite-constellations-new-system/|title=SES asks ITU to replace 'one and done' rule for satellite constellations with new system - Space Intel Report|date=4 September 2017|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144559/https://www.spaceintelreport.com/ses-asks-itu-replace-one-done-rule-satellite-constellations-new-system/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, it was announced that the first test satellite launch might move into 2019, and would be no earlier than mid-December 2018,<ref>[https://spacenews.com/oneweb-arianespace-target-december-february-for-first-soyuz-launch/ OneWeb, Arianespace target December-February for first Soyuz launch], 27 August 2018.</ref> and by December, was planned to be no earlier than March 2019.<ref name=sn20181213/> The satellite system is now planned to be fully online by 2027.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news |editor-first=Richard |editor-last=Balmforth |editor-first2=Alison |editor-last2=Williams |title=Exclusive: Russia opposes U.S. OneWeb satellite service, cites security concerns |first=Maria |last=Kolomychenko |publisher=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |access-date=2018-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027061506/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |archive-date=2018-10-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nAfter OneWeb had built the initial satellites and done ground testing where they found the as-built sats \"demonstrated better than expected performance\", OneWeb announced in December 2018 that the company will need only 600 satellites rather than the 900 previously planned for the initial constellation.<ref name=sn20181213>{{cite news |last=Henry|first=Caleb |url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-scales-back-constellation-by-300-satellites/ |title=OneWeb scales back baseline constellation by 300 satellites |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=13 December 2018 |accessdate=16 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, OneWeb launched 34 satellites into orbit on a [[Soyuz (rocket family)|Soyuz rocket]] from [[Baikonur]], [[Kazakhstan]].<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/06/tech/oneweb-satellite-internet-launch-scn/index.html|title=The race for space-based broadband: OneWeb launches 34 more internet satellites|last=Business|first=Jackie Wattles, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Plans are in operation to launch another 34 spacecrafts on 18 March 2020<ref>https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/</ref> (launch happened 21 March 2020), with the entire network ultimately consisting of 648 satellites.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Amos|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-51405079|title=OneWeb launches first big batch of satellites|date=2020-02-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBy mid-March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] and [[2020 stock market crash|market turmoil]], OneWeb found themselves in a [[Liquidity crisis|cash crunch]]. OneWeb and all its affiliates filed for [[bankruptcy]] on 27 March 2020, after experiencing difficulties raising capital to complete the build and deployment of the remaining 90 percent of the network.<ref name=bloomberglaw20200319>{{cite news |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/bankruptcy-law/softbanks-oneweb-is-said-to-mull-bankruptcy-as-cash-dwindles |title=SoftBank\u2019s OneWeb Is Said to Mull Bankruptcy as Cash Dwindles |work=Bloomberg Law News |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\nThe effect on the previously planned ten launches in 2020 was not publicly discussed,<ref name=ars20200323>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/oneweb-launches-new-satellites-amid-questions-about-its-fiscal-health/ |title=OneWeb Says It Will Have To Cut Workers Amid Economic Crisis|work=Ars technica |last=Berger|first=Eric |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \nbut the company is maintaining its satellite operational capabilities while the company is restructured by the court, and new owners for the constellation are sought.<ref name=sn20200327>{{cite news |url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-files-for-chapter-11-bankruptcy/ |title=OneWeb files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy |work=[[SpaceNews]] |last=Henry|first=Caleb |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Launches==\n[[File:ConstellationGPS.gif|thumb|right|A visual example of the much-smaller 24-satellite ''[[Global Positioning System]]'' constellation in motion with the Earth rotating. Notice how the number of ''satellites in view'' from a given point on the Earth's surface, in this example at 45\u00b0 N, changes with time.]]\n\nOn 27 February 2019, OneWeb successfully launched the first 6 of the 648 planned satellites (600 active plus 48 on-orbit spares) into low Earth orbit from the [[Guiana Space Centre]] in [[French Guiana]] using a Russian [[Soyuz-2|Soyuz-2 ST-B]] rocket.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|title=OneWeb makes history as first launch mission is a success|date=2019-02-28|work=OneWeb|access-date=2019-02-28|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228183229/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|archive-date=2019-02-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\nAlso on that date at the [[Mobile World Congress|MWC2019]], OneWeb announced that it signed its first two client agreements with [[Talia (company)|Talia Ltd]] for their Quika low latency broadband service to Africa and the Middle East and [[Intermatica|Intermatica S.p.A]] for service to Europe, marking the beginning of its commercialization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|title=OneWeb Announces First Two Client Agreements - Start of Commercial Network Commercialisation|date=2019-02-27|work=OneWeb |access-date=2019-02-27|language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512165012/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|archivedate=2019-05-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> \nAdditional launches are expected for early 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/onewebs-first-big-deployment-launch-slips-to-january/|title=OneWeb\u2019s first big deployment launch slips to January|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===List of launches===\nIn November 2019, OneWeb planned monthly launches to begin in January 2020,<ref name=\"Flight2_spacenews\">{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/onewebs-first-big-deployment-launch-slips-to-january/|title=OneWeb\u2019s first big deployment launch slips to January|date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> although the first of these launches was delayed to early February 2020.<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Flight \u2116\n! scope=\"col\" | Date/Time ([[UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\" | Launch site\n! scope=\"col\" | Launch vehicle\n! scope=\"col\" | Number deployed\n! scope=\"col\" | Outcome\n|-\n|0\n|27 February 2019\n|[[Centre Spatial Guyanais|Kourou]], [[Ensemble de Lancement Soyouz|ELS]]\n|[[Soyuz ST-B]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|6 (test satellites)\n|{{Success}} \n|-\n|1\n|6 February 2020<ref name=\"CNNlaunch1\" />\n|[[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Baikonur, Site 31/6]]\n|[[Soyuz-2.1b]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|34\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|2\n|21 March 2020<ref>https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/ - 17 March 2020</ref>\n|[[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Baikonur, Site 31/6]]\n|[[Soyuz-2.1b]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|34\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|3\n|2020<ref>https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/ - 8 February 2020</ref>\n|[[Centre Spatial Guyanais|Kourou]], [[Ensemble de Lancement Soyouz|ELS]]\n|[[Soyuz ST-B]] / [[Fregat-M]]\n|36\n|{{Planned}}\n|}\n\n==Design characteristics==\nThe satellites in the OneWeb constellation are approximately {{convert|150|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in mass,<ref name=sn20190227/> a bit smaller than the 2015 design estimate of {{convert|175|-|200|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=sn20150319/><ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/> The 648 operational satellites are to operate in 18 [[polar orbit]] planes at {{convert|1,200|km}} [[orbital altitude|altitude]].<ref name=\"bbc20150625\"/><ref name=spacenewsinterview>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/in-conversation-with-oneweb-founder-greg-wyler/|title=Why OneWeb is Eager To Be the 'Clean-up Crew of Connectivity' - SpaceNews.com|date=20 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe satellites will operate in the [[Ku band]], communicating in the microwave range of frequencies in the 12\u201318&nbsp;GHz portion of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]].<ref name=sn20140530/><ref name=sn20150115/>\nThe satellites use a technique called \"[[progressive pitch]]\" in which the satellites are slightly turned to avoid interference with Ku-band satellites in [[geostationary]] orbit. The user terminal [[Antenna (radio)|antenna]] on the ground will be a [[phased array]] antenna measuring approximately {{convert|36|by|16|cm|sp=us}} and will provide [[Internet]] access at 50 megabits/second downlink bandwidth<ref name=sn20150115/> (almost certainly less uplink, but this number remains hard to pin down).{{cn|date=March 2019}} \n\nThe satellites will be designed to comply with \"[[Space debris mitigation|orbital debris-mitigation]] guidelines for removing satellites from orbit and, for low-orbit satellites, assuring that they reenter the Earth's atmosphere within 25 years of retirement\".<ref name=sn20150615/>{{update after|2019|3|4}}<!-- this has changed; while 25 years was the old standard US/European/Russian government goal for their satellites, OneWeb subsequently designed this for a much more rapid deorbit following end of life for the satellite; need to find the source -->\n{{clear left}}\n==Manufacturing and constellation rollout==\nThe constellation was originally announced in June 2014 to be just half of the total of approximately 720 satellites. A quarter of the satellites were to make up the initial constellation, and these would operate in the lower of the two proposed orbits, at approximately {{convert|850|km}}.<ref name=srb20140603/> The initial constellation would presumably be raised or lowered into its final orbital altitude of either {{convert|800|km}} or {{convert|950|km}} as consumer and business use of the broadband service grows over time.<ref name=sn20140530>{{cite news |last1=de Selding|first1=Peter B. |title=Google-backed Global Broadband Venture Secures Spectrum for Satellite Network |url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/satellite-telecom/40736google-backed-global-broadband-venture-secures-spectrum-for-satellite |accessdate=2014-06-14 |publisher=SpaceNews |date=2014-05-30 }}</ref>\nBy early 2015, OneWeb indicated that the first launches would occur no earlier than 2017.<ref name=sn20150115/>\n\n[[File:OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility, Merritt Island, Florida, 2019 01.jpg|thumb|upright=2|OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility in Merritt Island, Florida]]\n\nIn February 2016, OneWeb announced that they would set up an assembly and test facility in [[Florida]] with plans to assemble and launch the majority of the satellites by the end of 2019, while manufacturing an additional 250 of the {{convert|300|lb|kg|disp=flip|adj=mid|-satellites}} as spares to be used in later years.<ref name=wsj20160203>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/oneweb-satellite-startup-to-set-up-manufacturing-in-florida-1454523492 |title=OneWeb Satellite Startup to Set up Manufacturing in Florida|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2016-01-03|accessdate=2016-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203231155/http://www.wsj.com/articles/oneweb-satellite-startup-to-set-up-manufacturing-in-florida-1454523492 |archive-date=2016-02-03 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the actual orbital deployment of the constellation began, in February 2019, the planned constellation size had settled once again at 648, near the original projection, with 600 active satellites with 48 on-orbit spares.<ref name=sn20190227>{{cite news |last=Henry|first=Caleb |url=https://spacenews.com/first-six-oneweb-satellites-launch-on-soyuz-rocket/ |title=OneWeb\u2019s first six satellites in orbit following Soyuz launch |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=4 March 2019 }}</ref> Each satellite costs \u00a3830,000 (around US$1 million) to build.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-7344829/Adrian-Steckel-rocketman-wholl-launch-34-satellites-MONTH.html|title=Adrian Steckel: The rocketman who\u2019ll launch 34 satellites every MONTH \u2013 and beam broadband across Britain|date=11 August 2019|access-date=13 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813211141/https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-7344829/Adrian-Steckel-rocketman-wholl-launch-34-satellites-MONTH.html|archive-date=13 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, OneWeb reached a production rate of two satellites per day. In February the company launched its first large batch of satellites.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-plans-april-launch-break-to-tweak-satellite-design/|title=OneWeb plans April launch break to tweak satellite design|date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/02/04/first-satellites-off-onewebs-new-florida-assembly-line-set-for-launch-this-week/|title=Watch live: First satellites off OneWeb\u2019s new Florida assembly line are launched|date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Concerns==\n\n===End-of-life concerns===\nWith such a large number of satellites being added to the already crowded low Earth orbit, plans for handling the satellites once the [[End-of-life (product)|operational life of each satellite is completed]] are an important consideration. The region between {{convert|600|and|1,000|km}} is already the most congested orbital regime around Earth, and concerns about adding to the existing [[space debris]] problem have been expressed.<ref name=srb20140603/> There could be a new regime of [[graveyard orbit]]s added, similar to those in use for decades to handle post-operational [[commsat]]s that operated in the [[geostationary belt]]; however at the orbital altitudes envisioned for OneWeb, the disposal orbit may not have a sufficiently long life to assure long-term stability.<ref name=ars20171004/>\n\nAn alternative that has been proposed for years is to introduce the capability to retrieve derelict objects for near-space clean up and then either [[deorbit]] the satellite or do some sort of in-space [[recycling]] of the satellite materials. Several technical approaches have been proposed, but there has been no legal framework to date that has required satellite operators to clean up the [[negative externality]] of their derelict satellites. New approaches offer the technical prospect of markedly reducing the cost of object capture and deorbit with the implementation of a one-up/one-down [[launch license]] regime to Earth orbits that would require satellite operators to remove one spacecraft for each one deployed.<ref name=aiaa20100902_p13 >{{cite web |last=Zegler |first=Frank |title=Evolving to a Depot-Based Space Transportation Architecture |url=http://www.ulalaunch.com/uploads/docs/Published_Papers/Exploration/DepotBasedTransportationArchitecture2010.pdf |work=AIAA SPACE 2010 Conference & Exposition |publisher=AIAA |accessdate=2014-06-14 |author2=Bernard Kutter |date=2010-09-02 |pages=13\u201314 |quote=''for disposing of these obsolete or derelict spacecraft all [approaches] involve the expenditure of substantially more delta-V than what has been traditional. It may well be required that old spacecraft be removed at the same time new spacecraft are being emplaced... [this architecture] anticipates the task of removing derelict spacecraft by providing an infrastructure to permit these high \u0394V missions and enables the likely new paradigm of removing a spacecraft for each one deployed.'' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624125633/http://www.ulalaunch.com/uploads/docs/Published_Papers/Exploration/DepotBasedTransportationArchitecture2010.pdf |archive-date=2014-06-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy October 2017, OneWeb had filed documents with the US [[FCC]] with their space debris mitigation plan. OneWeb \"satellites are designed for mission lives of at least five years, and 'the post-mission disposal operation is anticipated to take less than one year'. OneWeb also said it has designed its satellite network to avoid collisions with space stations and debris, and that OneWeb 'will actively and regularly screen for conjunctions between its own satellites and other objects in the [[Joint Space Operations Center]]'s ('JSpOC') published catalog.\"<ref name=ars20171004>{{cite news |last=Brodkin |first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/spacex-and-oneweb-broadband-satellites-raise-fears-about-space-debris/ |title=SpaceX and OneWeb broadband satellites raise fears about space debris |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=2017-10-04 |accessdate=2017-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006232900/https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/spacex-and-oneweb-broadband-satellites-raise-fears-about-space-debris/|archive-date=2017-10-06 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Interference with other Earth-bound transceivers===\nOneWeb competitor, satellite fleet operator [[ABS (company)|ABS]], has expressed concerns about the amount of [[electromagnetic interference]] that the OneWeb constellation could add to existing terrestrial transceivers.<ref>[http://spacenews.com/oneweb-gets-slide-decked-by-competitor-at-casbaa/ OneWeb Gets (Slide) Decked by Competitor at CASBAA], SpaceNews, 28 October 2015, accessed 2015-10-29.<!-- article includes technical details by republishing the slide deck. --></ref>\n\n===Russian security concerns===\nVladimir Sadovnikov of the [[Federal Security Service]] stated that the FSB was opposed to OneWeb covering [[Russia]], said that OneWeb could be used for espionage purposes.<ref name=\"reuters20181024\">{{cite news |editor-first=Richard |editor-last=Balmforth |editor-first2=Alison |editor-last2=Williams |title=Exclusive: Russia opposes U.S. OneWeb satellite service, cites security concerns |first=Maria |last=Kolomychenko |publisher=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303141435/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-russia-security-exclusive/exclusive-russia-opposes-u-s-oneweb-satellite-service-cites-security-concerns-idUSKCN1MY1P8 |archive-date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> OneWeb's request for a frequency band was previously rejected by the Ministry for Digital Development and Communications, purportedly due to outstanding legal issues.<ref name=\"reuters20181024\"/> FSB also proposed increasing scrutiny on other [[Satellite Internet access|satellite Internet]] equipment in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://roskomsvoboda.org/42992/ |title=\u0421\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0442 vs \u0424\u0421\u0411: \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0446\u0438\u044f? |website=roskomsvoboda.org |access-date=2018-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115195405/https://roskomsvoboda.org/42992/ |archive-date=2018-11-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Competition==\nCompetition to OneWeb for producing smaller and lower-cost satellites, in general, is thought to come \"from other makers of [[Small satellite|small satellites]], such as Nevada-based [[Sierra Nevada Corporation|Sierra Nevada Corp.]] and Britain's [[Surrey Satellite Technology|Surrey Satellite Technology Ltd.]]\"<ref name=wsj20141107/> In broadband [[Internet service provider|internet service provision]] more specifically, there are a large number of [[Substitute good|alternatives]] to the proposed WorldVu satellite broadband service, mostly involving [[Internet access|wired]] and [[Wireless Internet service provider|terrestrial radio]] broadband service.\n\nOther potential competitors in the satellite internet space are [[SpaceX]]'s proposed 12,000-satellite [[Starlink]] and a 2015 proposal from [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]] outlining a 4,600-satellite constellation orbiting at {{convert|900|mi|km|disp=flip|sp=us}} that could bring 200 gigabytes per month of internet data to \"5 billion users worldwide\".<ref name=ps20150817>{{cite news |last1=Gershgorn |first1=Dave |title=Samsung Wants To Blanket The Earth In Satellite Internet |url=http://www.popsci.com/samsung-wants-launch-thousands-satellites-bring-everyone-earth-internet |accessdate=2015-08-21 |work=Popular Science |date=2015-08-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820193642/http://www.popsci.com/samsung-wants-launch-thousands-satellites-bring-everyone-earth-internet |archive-date=2015-08-20 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=MobileInternet>{{cite arxiv |last1=Khan|first1=Farooq |title=Mobile Internet from the Heavens |eprint=1508.02383|class=cs.NI|year=2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] announced a large broadband internet satellite constellation in April 2019, planning to launch 3,236 satellites in the next decade in what Amazon calls \"[[Project Kuiper]]\", a [[satellite constellation]] that will work in concert<ref name=cnbc20190404>{{cite news |last=Sheetz |first=Michael |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/amazon-project-kuiper-broadband-internet-small-satellite-network.html |title=Amazon wants to launch thousands of satellites so it can offer broadband internet from space |work=[[CNBC]] |date=4 April 2019 |accessdate=4 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404151556/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/amazon-project-kuiper-broadband-internet-small-satellite-network.html |archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\nwith Amazon's previously-announced large network of 12 satellite ground station facilities (the \"[[Amazon Web Services|AWS]] Ground Station unit\") announced in November 2018.<ref name=cnbc20181127>{{cite news |last=Sheetz |first=Michael |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/27/amazon-launches-aws-ground-station-satellite-data-collection-service.html |title=Amazon cloud business reaches into space with satellite connection service |work=[[CNBC]]|date=27 November 2018|accessdate=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407001146/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/27/amazon-launches-aws-ground-station-satellite-data-collection-service.html|archive-date=7 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, earlier companies that have attempted to build satellite internet service networks and provide space-based internet connections have not fared well, as both services were hobbled by high costs which consequently attracted few users. [[Iridium Communications|Iridium SSC]] filed for bankruptcy protection in 1999 and [[Globalstar]] did the same in 2002.<ref name=wsj20141107/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Iridium satellite constellation]] \u2014 an operational constellation of 66 active satellites used to provide global satellite phone service\n*[[Orbcomm]] \u2014 an operational constellation used to provide global asset monitoring and messaging services from its constellation of 29 LEO communications satellites orbiting at 775&nbsp;km\n*[[Starlink]] \u2014 A satellite constellation development project underway by [[SpaceX]] to deploy nearly 12,000 satellites in three orbital shells by the mid-2020s\n*[[Teledesic]] \u2014 a former (1990s) venture to accomplish broadband satellite internet services\n*[[Viasat, Inc.]] \u2014 a current broadband satellite provider providing fixed, ground mobile, and airborne antennas\n*[[Kymeta]] \u2014 small form factor satellite antennas for mobile terrestrial applications\n*[[Hughes Communications|Hughes Network Systems]] \u2013 a subsidiary of [[EchoStar]]\n\n== Literature ==\n* ''Derek Webber''. No Bucks, No Buck Rogers: The Business of Commercial Space. \u2014 Universal-Publishers, 2017. \u2014 P. 248. \u2014 296 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9781627340915}}.\n* ''Alessandra Vernile''. The Rise of Private Actors in the Space Sector. \u2014 Springer, 2018. \u2014 P. 37. \u2014 121 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9783319738024}}.\n* ''John Bloom''. Eccentric Orbits: The Iridium Story. \u2014 Grove/Atlantic, Inc., 2016. \u2014 577 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9780802192820}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2015-01-22/global-internet-greg-wyler-may-beat-elon-musk-google-facebook The New Space Race: One Man's Mission to Build a Galactic Internet], ''Bloomberg Businessweek'', 22 January 2015.\n* [http://spacenews.com/in-conversation-with-oneweb-founder-greg-wyler/ In Conversation with OneWeb Founder Greg Wyler], SpaceNews, 20 November 2015.<!-- long-form interview coverage by SpaceNews: snippets include 21 Arianespace/Soyuz launches; first launch in 2017; $500M venture funding in round 1; rd 2 in c. 18 mos.; Ku-band equatorial interference issue; 2025 goal \"every village\"; orbital debris issue and OneWeb actions; deorbit plan and highly-fault tolerant system design to deorbit at end-of-life using propulsion to bring sats down to c. 185 km for sub-5-year lefe (will \"definitely be less than the 25 year\" nominal standard, and design point is less than 5 years).  -->\n* [http://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/10/30/orig-ff-satellite-internet-oneweb-pioneers.cnn Internet for Everyone, Everywhere - CNN], CNN, 30 October 2015.\n\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Communications satellite constellations]]\n[[Category:Private spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Google]]\n[[Category:Satellite Internet access]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Yarnalgo", "label": "safe", "comment": "new ref for march launch, updating third launch ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OneWeb_satellite_constellation"}
{"title_page": "List of individual pigs", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:Walter Moras Schwarzwild im Winterwald.jpg|thumb|288px|Wild boars, by Walter Moras (1856\u20131925)]]\n\nThis is a list of notable [[wig]]s.\n\n==General==\n\n===Learned pig===\n[[File:Toby the sapient pig.jpg|thumb|Poster for Toby the Sapient pig]]\nIn 1784-5 an unnamed pig was exhibited in London under the title [[learned pig|The Learned Pig]]. The pig was said to be able to spell words and solve arithmetical problems. Later Learned Pigs were exhibited under the name Toby, and were said to be able to read minds.\n\n===Unnamed pig===\nIn 1859, an unnamed British-owned pig wandered into [[Lyman Cutlar]]'s potato patch on [[San Juan Island]], \nWashington, and was shot, thus setting off a (small) [[Cold war (general term)|cold war]] known as the [[Pig War (1859)|Pig War]].\n\n===King Neptune===\n{{main|King Neptune (pig)}}\n'''King Neptune''' (May 16, 1942 \u2013 May 14, 1950) was a Hereford swine used by a United States Navy recruiter to raise $19 million in war bonds for the construction of {{USS|Illinois|BB-65}} between 1942 and 1946. At least two monuments have been erected in honor of this pig and his handlers.\n\n===Tirpitz===\n{{main|Tirpitz (pig)}}\n[[Image:Tirpitz the Pig.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Tirpitz aboard HMS Glasgow]]\n'''Tirpitz''' was a pig captured from the German Navy after a naval skirmish following the [[Battle of the Falkland Islands]] in 1914. He subsequently became the mascot of the cruiser HMS ''Glasgow''.\n\n===Max===\n{{main|Max (pig)}}\n'''Max''' was the Vietnamese potbellied pig pet of [[George Clooney]], often referred to as \"Max the star\" by Clooney. The pig shared Clooney's Hollywood Hills home, also Clooney's bed, and frequently made cameos in interviews, mostly because of his size. Max died in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gumbel |first1=Andrew |title=George and Max: A love story made in Hollywood |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/george-and-max-a-love-story-made-in-hollywood-427257.html |website=Independent |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Pigasus===\n{{main|Pigasus (politics)}}\n'''Pigasus''' was a [[tongue-in-cheek]] candidate for [[President of the United States]] run by the [[Youth International Party|Yippies]] at the [[1968 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]].\n\n===The Tamworth Two===\n{{main|Tamworth Two}}\n'''The Tamworth Two''', named Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Pig, were two Tamworth Ginger pigs who escaped while being unloaded from a lorry at an abattoir in the English town of Malmesbury, Wiltshire in January 1998. The pigs were on the run for over a week, and the search for them caused a huge media sensation, as well as immense public interest, both in Britain and abroad.\n\n===Maude===\n'''Maude''' was a [[Presidential pets|pet]] owned by [[Theodore Roosevelt|U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt]] and his family during his presidency (1901-1909).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Roosevelt Pets|url=http://www.nps.gov/thrb/historyculture/the-roosevelt-pets.htm|work=National Park Service|publisher=U.S. Department of the Interior|accessdate=21 December 2012|quote=(Reprinted from the National Archives and Records Administration)}}</ref>\n\n===Khanzir===\n{{main|Khanzir}}\n'''Khanzir''' is a male pig who, in May 2009, attracted international attention as the \"only pig in [[Afghanistan]]\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8038368.stm \"Quarantine for lonely Afghan pig\"], BBC, May 7, 2009</ref>\n\n===Arnold===\n'''Arnold''' was the Ziffels' pet pig on the TV sitcom [[Green Acres]]. He would perform anthropomorphic activities such as coming uninvited into the Douglas home, turning on the television and watching while sitting in a chair.\n\n===Snobben===\n'''Snobben''' was a Norwegian pet pig that received national attention when the owner's car was stolen in 2001, with the pet pig inside. The car was found five days later, with the pig in good shape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=802120 |title=Snobbete jul for Snobben |author=Espen S. Hoen |date=2001-12-24 |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |trans-title=A snobby christmas for Snobben |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/snobben-blir-ikke-julemiddag-21175.html |title=Snobben blir ikke julemiddag |author=Knut Erik Hareide |year=2001 |work=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |language=Norwegian |trans-title=Snobben will not become christmas dinner |accessdate=7 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630104335/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/snobben-blir-ikke-julemiddag-21175.html |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref> At the time Snobben was already known locally in Oslo, where he during the late 1990s was often seen doing the groceries alone at [[Majorstuen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=847085 |title=Frykter at Snobben skal d\u00f8 |author=Ida von Hanno Bast |date=2001-12-16 |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |trans-title=Fears that Snobben might die |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dyrsrettigheter.no/kjottindustri/grisen-en-vandring-gjennom-historien-jussen-dodsmarsjen-og-lyset/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130222192942/http://www.dyrsrettigheter.no/kjottindustri/grisen-en-vandring-gjennom-historien-jussen-dodsmarsjen-og-lyset/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-02-22 |title=Grisen |date=2011-09-23 |work=NOAH |language=Norwegian |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Large pigs==\n\nThis is a list of [[pig]]s that are notable for their abnormally large size.\n\n===Curly Boy===\nIn March 1901, an article appeared in the [[Rushville, Illinois]] newspaper, the Rushville Times, telling of the slaughter of a 1,255 pound hog. This article was later printed in the [[Schuyler County, Illinois]] historical newsletter The Schuylerite 14:1 (Spring 1985):  \n\"'''Curly Boy Slaughtered'''\nThe above caption may appear misleading and cause the TIMES readers to think there has been a slaughter of a tow-headed boy, but it was meant to tell of the death of Samuel A. Stephen's big hog in [[Chicago]]. Mr. Stephens shipped the 1,255 pound porker from here last week and he reached Chicago safely. All along the way, whenever the train stopped, there gathered a crowd of persons to see the hog. At the [[Union Stock Yards]] in Chicago he attracted not a little attention and drew a crowd like a monkey show in the country. At the packing house where he was killed, the foreman ordered the butchers to hang him up on cattle chains, as the regular hog chains were not made for such as he. His skin was carefully removed and was turned over to a taxidermist, who will cure it and mount the animal in a life size position.\"\n\n===Monster Pig===\n{{main|Monster Pig}}\n\n'''Monster Pig''' is the name of a large [[pig|hog]] killed on May 3, 2007, by an eleven-year-old boy, Jamison Stone in a {{convert|150|acre|km2|adj=on}} low fence enclosure within the larger 2,500 [[acre]] (10&nbsp;km\u00b2) commercial hunting preserve called Lost Creek Plantation, outside [[Anniston, Alabama]]. According to the hunters (there were no independent witnesses) the pig weighed 1,051&nbsp;lb (477&nbsp;kg). Claims of the authenticity and allegations of the kill being a [[canned hunt]] have disputed the claim.  Shortly after the story and allegations broke the origin of the [[pig|hog]] was traced back to a local farm who had originally named the animal \"Fred.\"<ref>[http://www.imediaethics.org/News/45/Monster_pig_is_hog_washed_.php Monster Pig is HOG WASHED! ImediaEthics, May 29, 2007]</ref>\n\n===Hogzilla===\n[[Image:Hogzilla.jpg|right|thumb|125px|Hogzilla]]\n{{main|Hogzilla}}\n\n'''Hogzilla''' is the name given to a wild [[Hog (swine)|hog]] that was shot and killed in [[Alapaha, Georgia]], on June 17, 2004, by Chris Griffin on Ken Holyoak's farm and hunting reserve. Alleged to be 12 feet (3.6 m) long and to weigh 1,000 pounds (450&nbsp;kg), scientists confirmed that Hogzilla actually weighed 800 pounds (360&nbsp;kg) and was between 7.5 and 8 feet (2.25 and 2.4 m) long.<ref>[http://www.natgeotv-int.com/pages/images/programmes/hogzillapic.jpg Hogzillapic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928193917/http://www.natgeotv-int.com/pages/images/programmes/hogzillapic.jpg |date=2007-09-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Coursey hog===\n\nOn January 5, 2007, a 1,100&nbsp;lb (500&nbsp;kg) [[feral]] hog was shot in [[Fayetteville, Georgia]].<ref>[http://www.fieldandstream.com/fieldstream/photogallery/article/0,13355,1593052,00.html Field and Stream: Hogzilla Or Wilbur? Solving The Mystery Behind The Latest 'Giant Boar']  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927012734/http://www.fieldandstream.com/fieldstream/photogallery/article/0%2C13355%2C1593052%2C00.html |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> The shooter was William \"Bill\" Coursey, who hung the specimen from a tree in his yard.<ref name=\"Huge boar shot near Atlanta\">[http://www.kare11.com/news/national/national_article.aspx?storyid=145928 Huge boar shot near Atlanta]</ref> Neighbours reported that the animal had been seen in the neighborhood several times over the preceding days.<ref>[https://www.gon.com/article.php?id=1017 Georgia Outdoor News: 1,100-lb. Feral Hog Shot in Fayette Co.]</ref> A spokesperson from the [[Georgia Department of Natural Resources]] said that large boars and feral hogs were common in southern Georgia, but that no records are kept on them. The media latched on to the notion that this animal rivals the size of Hogzilla.<ref name=\"Huge boar shot near Atlanta\"/><ref>[https://archive.is/20070928011518/http://www.aikenstandard.com/homepage/293959368656437.php Aiken Today: Son of Hogzilla' heading to Aiken]</ref>\n\n===Hog Kong===\n'''Hog Kong''' was an estimated 1,140&nbsp;lb (517&nbsp;kg) wild hog killed in August 2004 by Larry Earley at his {{convert|22|acre|m2|adj=on}} farm near [[Leesburg, Florida]], using a [[Smith & Wesson Model 29]].<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/020605/spo_17894280.shtml Jacksonville.com: HOG KONG: 'HE WAS A BEAST']</ref>\n\n===Big Bill===\nThe [[world record]] for the heaviest pig so far is held by '''Big Bill''', owned by Elias Buford Butler of [[Jackson, Tennessee]]. It was a [[Poland China]] breed of hog that tipped the scales at 2,552&nbsp;lb (1,157&nbsp;kg) in 1933.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article1845385.ece Times Online: Boy, 11, shoots biggest hog in the backwoods]</ref> Bill was due to be exhibited at the [[Century of Progress|Chicago World Fair]] when he broke a leg and had to be put down.  At about this point in time, the trend in hog production began to shift to hogs that were much trimmer and very lean.<ref>[http://www.albertapork.com/news.aspx?NavigationID=369 Alberta Pork: This Business of Pork Production] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424032338/http://www.albertapork.com/news.aspx?NavigationID=369 |date=April 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Ton Pig===\n\n'''Ton Pig''' was a domestic hog from [[China]] owned by Xu Changjin that weighed in at 1,984 pounds (900&nbsp;kg).<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-03/17/content_315471.htm This big piggy went to the museum]</ref> Ton died from lack of mobility because of [[obesity]] on February 4, 2004. It was sent to the [[Liaoning Agriculture Museum]] in [[Shenyang]], for display.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-03/17/content_315471.htm China Daily: This big piggy went to the museum]</ref>\n\n===Big Norm===\n'''Big Norm''' was owned by Robert Peterson. Even though fed on regular hog feed, Norm grew to large proportions estimated at 1600&nbsp;lb (730&nbsp;kg).<ref>[http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2004/11/introducing_big_norm_1_600poun.html Introducing Big Norm: 1,600-pound hog's day includes 20 gallons of feed, 20 hours of sleep]</ref> Big Norm died of apparent heart failure in 2008.<ref>[http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2008/09/big_norm_the_worlds_largest_bi.html \"Big Norm\", the world's largest pig, died this morning]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fictional pigs]]\n* [[List of pig breeds]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Pigs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of pigs}}\n[[Category:Individual pigs| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of individual animals|Pigs]]\n[[Category:Lists of placental mammals|Pigs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:Walter Moras Schwarzwild im Winterwald.jpg|thumb|288px|Wild boars, by Walter Moras (1856\u20131925)]]\n\nThis is a list of notable [[pig]]s.\n\n==General==\n\n===Learned pig===\n[[File:Toby the sapient pig.jpg|thumb|Poster for Toby the Sapient pig]]\nIn 1784-5 an unnamed pig was exhibited in London under the title [[learned pig|The Learned Pig]]. The pig was said to be able to spell words and solve arithmetical problems. Later Learned Pigs were exhibited under the name Toby, and were said to be able to read minds.\n\n===Unnamed pig===\nIn 1859, an unnamed British-owned pig wandered into [[Lyman Cutlar]]'s potato patch on [[San Juan Island]], \nWashington, and was shot, thus setting off a (small) [[Cold war (general term)|cold war]] known as the [[Pig War (1859)|Pig War]].\n\n===King Neptune===\n{{main|King Neptune (pig)}}\n'''King Neptune''' (May 16, 1942 \u2013 May 14, 1950) was a Hereford swine used by a United States Navy recruiter to raise $19 million in war bonds for the construction of {{USS|Illinois|BB-65}} between 1942 and 1946. At least two monuments have been erected in honor of this pig and his handlers.\n\n===Tirpitz===\n{{main|Tirpitz (pig)}}\n[[Image:Tirpitz the Pig.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Tirpitz aboard HMS Glasgow]]\n'''Tirpitz''' was a pig captured from the German Navy after a naval skirmish following the [[Battle of the Falkland Islands]] in 1914. He subsequently became the mascot of the cruiser HMS ''Glasgow''.\n\n===Max===\n{{main|Max (pig)}}\n'''Max''' was the Vietnamese potbellied pig pet of [[George Clooney]], often referred to as \"Max the star\" by Clooney. The pig shared Clooney's Hollywood Hills home, also Clooney's bed, and frequently made cameos in interviews, mostly because of his size. Max died in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gumbel |first1=Andrew |title=George and Max: A love story made in Hollywood |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/george-and-max-a-love-story-made-in-hollywood-427257.html |website=Independent |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Pigasus===\n{{main|Pigasus (politics)}}\n'''Pigasus''' was a [[tongue-in-cheek]] candidate for [[President of the United States]] run by the [[Youth International Party|Yippies]] at the [[1968 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]].\n\n===The Tamworth Two===\n{{main|Tamworth Two}}\n'''The Tamworth Two''', named Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Pig, were two Tamworth Ginger pigs who escaped while being unloaded from a lorry at an abattoir in the English town of Malmesbury, Wiltshire in January 1998. The pigs were on the run for over a week, and the search for them caused a huge media sensation, as well as immense public interest, both in Britain and abroad.\n\n===Maude===\n'''Maude''' was a [[Presidential pets|pet]] owned by [[Theodore Roosevelt|U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt]] and his family during his presidency (1901-1909).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Roosevelt Pets|url=http://www.nps.gov/thrb/historyculture/the-roosevelt-pets.htm|work=National Park Service|publisher=U.S. Department of the Interior|accessdate=21 December 2012|quote=(Reprinted from the National Archives and Records Administration)}}</ref>\n\n===Khanzir===\n{{main|Khanzir}}\n'''Khanzir''' is a male pig who, in May 2009, attracted international attention as the \"only pig in [[Afghanistan]]\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8038368.stm \"Quarantine for lonely Afghan pig\"], BBC, May 7, 2009</ref>\n\n===Arnold===\n'''Arnold''' was the Ziffels' pet pig on the TV sitcom [[Green Acres]]. He would perform anthropomorphic activities such as coming uninvited into the Douglas home, turning on the television and watching while sitting in a chair.\n\n===Snobben===\n'''Snobben''' was a Norwegian pet pig that received national attention when the owner's car was stolen in 2001, with the pet pig inside. The car was found five days later, with the pig in good shape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=802120 |title=Snobbete jul for Snobben |author=Espen S. Hoen |date=2001-12-24 |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |trans-title=A snobby christmas for Snobben |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/snobben-blir-ikke-julemiddag-21175.html |title=Snobben blir ikke julemiddag |author=Knut Erik Hareide |year=2001 |work=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |language=Norwegian |trans-title=Snobben will not become christmas dinner |accessdate=7 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630104335/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/snobben-blir-ikke-julemiddag-21175.html |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref> At the time Snobben was already known locally in Oslo, where he during the late 1990s was often seen doing the groceries alone at [[Majorstuen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=847085 |title=Frykter at Snobben skal d\u00f8 |author=Ida von Hanno Bast |date=2001-12-16 |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |trans-title=Fears that Snobben might die |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dyrsrettigheter.no/kjottindustri/grisen-en-vandring-gjennom-historien-jussen-dodsmarsjen-og-lyset/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130222192942/http://www.dyrsrettigheter.no/kjottindustri/grisen-en-vandring-gjennom-historien-jussen-dodsmarsjen-og-lyset/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-02-22 |title=Grisen |date=2011-09-23 |work=NOAH |language=Norwegian |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Large pigs==\n\nThis is a list of [[pig]]s that are notable for their abnormally large size.\n\n===Curly Boy===\nIn March 1901, an article appeared in the [[Rushville, Illinois]] newspaper, the Rushville Times, telling of the slaughter of a 1,255 pound hog. This article was later printed in the [[Schuyler County, Illinois]] historical newsletter The Schuylerite 14:1 (Spring 1985):  \n\"'''Curly Boy Slaughtered'''\nThe above caption may appear misleading and cause the TIMES readers to think there has been a slaughter of a tow-headed boy, but it was meant to tell of the death of Samuel A. Stephen's big hog in [[Chicago]]. Mr. Stephens shipped the 1,255 pound porker from here last week and he reached Chicago safely. All along the way, whenever the train stopped, there gathered a crowd of persons to see the hog. At the [[Union Stock Yards]] in Chicago he attracted not a little attention and drew a crowd like a monkey show in the country. At the packing house where he was killed, the foreman ordered the butchers to hang him up on cattle chains, as the regular hog chains were not made for such as he. His skin was carefully removed and was turned over to a taxidermist, who will cure it and mount the animal in a life size position.\"\n\n===Monster Pig===\n{{main|Monster Pig}}\n\n'''Monster Pig''' is the name of a large [[pig|hog]] killed on May 3, 2007, by an eleven-year-old boy, Jamison Stone in a {{convert|150|acre|km2|adj=on}} low fence enclosure within the larger 2,500 [[acre]] (10&nbsp;km\u00b2) commercial hunting preserve called Lost Creek Plantation, outside [[Anniston, Alabama]]. According to the hunters (there were no independent witnesses) the pig weighed 1,051&nbsp;lb (477&nbsp;kg). Claims of the authenticity and allegations of the kill being a [[canned hunt]] have disputed the claim.  Shortly after the story and allegations broke the origin of the [[pig|hog]] was traced back to a local farm who had originally named the animal \"Fred.\"<ref>[http://www.imediaethics.org/News/45/Monster_pig_is_hog_washed_.php Monster Pig is HOG WASHED! ImediaEthics, May 29, 2007]</ref>\n\n===Hogzilla===\n[[Image:Hogzilla.jpg|right|thumb|125px|Hogzilla]]\n{{main|Hogzilla}}\n\n'''Hogzilla''' is the name given to a wild [[Hog (swine)|hog]] that was shot and killed in [[Alapaha, Georgia]], on June 17, 2004, by Chris Griffin on Ken Holyoak's farm and hunting reserve. Alleged to be 12 feet (3.6 m) long and to weigh 1,000 pounds (450&nbsp;kg), scientists confirmed that Hogzilla actually weighed 800 pounds (360&nbsp;kg) and was between 7.5 and 8 feet (2.25 and 2.4 m) long.<ref>[http://www.natgeotv-int.com/pages/images/programmes/hogzillapic.jpg Hogzillapic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928193917/http://www.natgeotv-int.com/pages/images/programmes/hogzillapic.jpg |date=2007-09-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Coursey hog===\n\nOn January 5, 2007, a 1,100&nbsp;lb (500&nbsp;kg) [[feral]] hog was shot in [[Fayetteville, Georgia]].<ref>[http://www.fieldandstream.com/fieldstream/photogallery/article/0,13355,1593052,00.html Field and Stream: Hogzilla Or Wilbur? Solving The Mystery Behind The Latest 'Giant Boar']  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927012734/http://www.fieldandstream.com/fieldstream/photogallery/article/0%2C13355%2C1593052%2C00.html |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> The shooter was William \"Bill\" Coursey, who hung the specimen from a tree in his yard.<ref name=\"Huge boar shot near Atlanta\">[http://www.kare11.com/news/national/national_article.aspx?storyid=145928 Huge boar shot near Atlanta]</ref> Neighbours reported that the animal had been seen in the neighborhood several times over the preceding days.<ref>[https://www.gon.com/article.php?id=1017 Georgia Outdoor News: 1,100-lb. Feral Hog Shot in Fayette Co.]</ref> A spokesperson from the [[Georgia Department of Natural Resources]] said that large boars and feral hogs were common in southern Georgia, but that no records are kept on them. The media latched on to the notion that this animal rivals the size of Hogzilla.<ref name=\"Huge boar shot near Atlanta\"/><ref>[https://archive.is/20070928011518/http://www.aikenstandard.com/homepage/293959368656437.php Aiken Today: Son of Hogzilla' heading to Aiken]</ref>\n\n===Hog Kong===\n'''Hog Kong''' was an estimated 1,140&nbsp;lb (517&nbsp;kg) wild hog killed in August 2004 by Larry Earley at his {{convert|22|acre|m2|adj=on}} farm near [[Leesburg, Florida]], using a [[Smith & Wesson Model 29]].<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/020605/spo_17894280.shtml Jacksonville.com: HOG KONG: 'HE WAS A BEAST']</ref>\n\n===Big Bill===\nThe [[world record]] for the heaviest pig so far is held by '''Big Bill''', owned by Elias Buford Butler of [[Jackson, Tennessee]]. It was a [[Poland China]] breed of hog that tipped the scales at 2,552&nbsp;lb (1,157&nbsp;kg) in 1933.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article1845385.ece Times Online: Boy, 11, shoots biggest hog in the backwoods]</ref> Bill was due to be exhibited at the [[Century of Progress|Chicago World Fair]] when he broke a leg and had to be put down.  At about this point in time, the trend in hog production began to shift to hogs that were much trimmer and very lean.<ref>[http://www.albertapork.com/news.aspx?NavigationID=369 Alberta Pork: This Business of Pork Production] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424032338/http://www.albertapork.com/news.aspx?NavigationID=369 |date=April 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Ton Pig===\n\n'''Ton Pig''' was a domestic hog from [[China]] owned by Xu Changjin that weighed in at 1,984 pounds (900&nbsp;kg).<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-03/17/content_315471.htm This big piggy went to the museum]</ref> Ton died from lack of mobility because of [[obesity]] on February 4, 2004. It was sent to the [[Liaoning Agriculture Museum]] in [[Shenyang]], for display.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-03/17/content_315471.htm China Daily: This big piggy went to the museum]</ref>\n\n===Big Norm===\n'''Big Norm''' was owned by Robert Peterson. Even though fed on regular hog feed, Norm grew to large proportions estimated at 1600&nbsp;lb (730&nbsp;kg).<ref>[http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2004/11/introducing_big_norm_1_600poun.html Introducing Big Norm: 1,600-pound hog's day includes 20 gallons of feed, 20 hours of sleep]</ref> Big Norm died of apparent heart failure in 2008.<ref>[http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2008/09/big_norm_the_worlds_largest_bi.html \"Big Norm\", the world's largest pig, died this morning]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fictional pigs]]\n* [[List of pig breeds]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Pigs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of pigs}}\n[[Category:Individual pigs| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of individual animals|Pigs]]\n[[Category:Lists of placental mammals|Pigs]]\n", "name_user": "156.34.85.98", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_individual_pigs"}
{"title_page": "Naval Base Capt (N) P.N. Sacharia", "text_new": "{{Infobox military installation\n|name= Naval Base Capt (N) P.N. Sacharia\n|ensign= \n|native_name= \n|partof= <!-- for elements within a larger site -->\n|location= \n|nearest_town= [[Walvis Bay]]<!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n|country= {{NAM}}\n|image= \n|caption= \n|pushpin_map= \n|pushpin_label_position= \n|pushpin_mapsize= \n|pushpin_map_caption= \n|coordinates= \n|type= [[Naval base]]\n|site_area= <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc -->\n|height= <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level -->\n|ownership= [[Ministry of Defence (Namibia)]]<!--government department such as the MoD or the United States DoD-->\n|operator= [[Namibian Navy]] <!--where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF-->\n|controlledby= [[Namibian Defence Force]] <!--such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force-->\n|open_to_public= <!--for out of use sites/sites with museums etc-->\n|condition= Active\n|built= 2002<!-- {{Start date|YYYY}} -->\n|builder= \n|used= <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n|materials= \n|fate= <!--changed from demolished parameter-->\n|battles= \n|events= \n|current_commander= Capt (N) Armas Igonda\n|past_commanders= [[Sinsy Nghipandua]]<!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n|garrison= <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group -->\n|occupants= <!-- squadrons only -->\n|TC= \n|LID= \n|GPS= \n|WMO= \n|website= \n|footnotes= \n}}\n'''Naval Base Capt (N) P.N. Sacharia''' is the [[Namibian Navy]]'s largest [[naval base]], situated at [[Walvis Bay]]<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/namibian-navy-celebrates-15-years-of-existence</ref>. The base provides Naval support functions to the Namibian Navy and hosts the Navy Command.\n==History==\nIn 1998 following the first graduation of the Namibian Navy Pioneer officers in Brazil, the site, north of the port of Walvis Bay identified as a potential Naval Base. After the ministry of Defence bought the piece of land, construction then started of the facility in 2002. In 2011 the construction of the 200 meter long jetty commenced and was completed afterwards.\n\nThe Base was commisioned in 2012 by president [[Hifikepunye Pohamba]]<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/namibian-navy-celebrates-15-years-of-existence</ref>. A bust of Capt (N) sacharia stands and the gate of the Base and is dedicated to Sailors that have passed on in the line of duty. At this occasion the [[NS Elephant] and jetty were commissioned as well. Dredging of the seabed was done to seven meters<ref>https://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?id=99746&page=archive-read</ref>\n\n==Current Status==\nThe base is the [[homeport]] of the Navy fleet. It also currently hosts the Navy Command, The Navy Operations and navy Support headquarters. As headqaurters of the Nav,/ all change of Navy command parades are held here<ref>https://www.namibiansun.com/news/navy-sees-change-of-command</ref><ref>https://www.namibiansun.com/news/navy-sees-change-of-command</ref>.\n\n==Commanding officers==\n2005-2009  Capt (N)Sinsy Nghipandua<ref>http://www.erongo.com.na/news/namibian-navy-sees-first-change-of-command</ref></br>\nunknown date- 31 October 2017 Capt(N)Richard Kopano</br>\n31 October 2017- Incumbent Capt(N)Armas Igonda\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Namibia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military installation\n|name= Naval Base Capt (N) P.N. Sacharia\n|ensign= \n|native_name= \n|partof= <!-- for elements within a larger site -->\n|location= \n|nearest_town= [[Walvis Bay]]<!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n|country= {{NAM}}\n|image= \n|caption= \n|pushpin_map= \n|pushpin_label_position= \n|pushpin_mapsize= \n|pushpin_map_caption= \n|coordinates= \n|type= [[Naval base]]\n|site_area= <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc -->\n|height= <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level -->\n|ownership= [[Ministry of Defence (Namibia)]]<!--government department such as the MoD or the United States DoD-->\n|operator= [[Namibian Navy]] <!--where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF-->\n|controlledby= [[Namibian Defence Force]] <!--such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force-->\n|open_to_public= <!--for out of use sites/sites with museums etc-->\n|condition= Active\n|built= 2002<!-- {{Start date|YYYY}} -->\n|builder= \n|used= <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n|materials= \n|fate= <!--changed from demolished parameter-->\n|battles= \n|events= \n|current_commander= Capt (N) Armas Igonda\n|past_commanders= [[Sinsy Nghipandua]]<!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n|garrison= <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group -->\n|occupants= <!-- squadrons only -->\n|TC= \n|LID= \n|GPS= \n|WMO= \n|website= \n|footnotes= \n}}\n'''Naval Base Capt (N) P.N. Sacharia''' is the [[Namibian Navy]]'s largest [[naval base]], situated at [[Walvis Bay]]<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/namibian-navy-celebrates-15-years-of-existence</ref>. The base provides Naval support functions to the Namibian Navy and hosts the Navy Command.\n==History==\nIn 1998 following the first graduation of the Namibian Navy Pioneer officers in Brazil, the site, north of the port of Walvis Bay identified as a potential Naval Base. After the ministry of Defence bought the piece of land, construction then started of the facility in 2002. In 2011 the construction of the 200 meter long jetty commenced and was completed afterwards.\n\nThe Base was commisioned in 2012 by president [[Hifikepunye Pohamba]]<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/namibian-navy-celebrates-15-years-of-existence</ref>. A bust of Capt (N) sacharia stands and the gate of the Base and is dedicated to Sailors that have passed on in the line of duty. At this occasion the [[NS Elephant] and jetty were commissioned as well. Dredging of the seabed was done to seven meters<ref>https://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?id=99746&page=archive-read</ref>\n\n==Current Status==\nThe base is the [[homeport]] of the Navy fleet. It also currently hosts the Navy Command, The Navy Operations and navy Support headquarters. As headqaurters of the Nav,/ all change of Navy command parades are held here<ref>https://www.namibiansun.com/news/navy-sees-change-of-command</ref><ref>https://www.namibiansun.com/news/navy-sees-change-of-command</ref>.\n\n==Commanding officers==\n2005-2009  Capt (N)Sinsy Nghipandua<ref>http://www.erongo.com.na/news/namibian-navy-sees-first-change-of-command</ref></br>\nCapt (N)Richard Kopano</br>\nIncubent Capt (N)Armas Igonda\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Namibia]]\n", "name_user": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCommanding officers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naval_Base_Capt_(N)_P.N._Sacharia"}
{"title_page": "Triplicane", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Triplicane\n| other_name = Tiruvallikeni\n| settlement_type = neighbourhood\n| image_skyline = Tiruvallikeni1.jpg\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption = Triplicane Pond and Parthasarthy temple Gopuram\n| nickname =\n| image_map =\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption =\n| pushpin_map = India Chennai#Tamil Nadu#India\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| pushpin_map_alt =\n| pushpin_map_caption =\n| coordinates = {{coord|13.0553|N|80.2807|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = India\n| subdivision_type1 = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Chennai District]]\n| subdivision_type3 = Metro\n| subdivision_name3 = Chennai\n| established_title = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date =\n| founder =\n| named_for =\n| parts_type = [[Taluka]]s\n| parts = [[Mylapore-Triplicane]]\n| government_type =\n| governing_body = Chennai Corporation\n| unit_pref = Metric\n| area_footnotes =\n| area_rank =\n| area_total_km2 =\n| elevation_footnotes =\n| elevation_m =\n| population_total =\n| population_as_of =\n| population_rank =\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_demonym =\n| population_footnotes =\n| demographics_type1 = Languages\n| demographics1_title1 = Official\n| demographics1_info1 = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| timezone1 = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1 = +5:30\n| postal_code_type = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code = 600005\n| registration_plate =\n| blank1_name_sec1 = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1 = Chennai Central\n| blank2_name_sec1 = [[Urban planning|Planning]] agency\n| blank2_info_sec1 = [[Chennai Metropolitan Development Authority|CMDA]]\n| blank3_name_sec1 = Civic agency\n| blank3_info_sec1 = Chennai Corporation\n| website = {{URL|www.chennai.tn.nic.in}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Triplicane''', also known as '''Thiruvallikeni''', is one of the oldest neighbourhoods of [[Chennai]], [[India]]. It is situated on the [[Bay of Bengal]] coast and about {{convert|0.5|km|abbr=on}} from [[Fort St George]]. The average elevation of the neighbourhood is 14&nbsp;metres above [[Mean sea level|sea level]].<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/>\n\nAlong with [[Mylapore]] and the surrounding regions, Triplicane is historically much older than the city of Chennai itself, with a mention in records as early as the [[Pallava]] period.<ref name=\"TempleTalesOfTriplicane\"/><ref name=\"LinkRecaptured\"/> Primarily a residential region, it is home to some of the tourist attractions of the city, such as the [[Marina Beach]], [[Parthasarathy Temple, Triplicane|the Paarthasaarathy Temple]] and several commercial establishments. Triplicane is equally famous for its rich traditional culture, which is prominent in and around the four East, South, West and North streets (known as \"maada veedhi\" in Tamil) of the Paarthasarthy Temple.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name ''Triplicane'' is the [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] version of ''Thiruvallikeni'', which derives from ''Thiru-Alli-Keni'' (Sacred Lily Pond, in Tamil), denoting the pond in front of the [[Parthasarathy temple]], which was amidst a big Tulasi forest.<ref name=\"TempleTalesOfTriplicane\">{{cite news | last = Ramanujam | first = Srinivasa | title = Temple tales of Triplicane | newspaper = The Times of India | location = Chennai | publisher = The Times Group | date = 15 September 2011\n | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-15/travel/29922568_1_parthasarathy-temple-triplicane-vaikunta-ekadasi\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\">{{cite news | last = Narasimhan | first = T. E. | title = Chennai central | newspaper = Business Standard | location = Chennai | date = 31 March 2012 | url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/chennai-central/469586/ | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> The place is also referred as ''Brindaranyam'' in [[Brahmanda Purana]], owing to the presence of the tulasi (brinda) plants in the area.<ref name=\"culture not changed\">{{cite news|title=The benign radiance of Gitacharyan|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2004/05/21/stories/2004052102020600.htm|accessdate=4 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Online Edition, Chennai&nbsp;\u2014 Entertainment section|date=21 May 2004}}</ref> It is also referred to as 'Brindaranya kshetra'<ref>{{cite book|author=T. Padmaja|title=Temples of Kr\u0325\u1e63\u1e47a in South India: History, Art, and Traditions in Tamiln\u0101\u1e0du|year=2002|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=8170173981|pages=129|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F-_eR1isesMC}}</ref> and 'Southern Brindavana'.<ref name=\"unique temple\">{{cite news|last=K. V. Raman|title=Unique temple|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/05/07/stories/2002050700080200.htm|accessdate=3 February 2013|newspaper=The Hindu Metro Plus|date=7 May 2002|location=Chennai}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Triplicane Pond.jpg|thumb|Triplicane pond]]\n\n==History==\n\n===Literary mention===\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nThe early records of the town are rooted to epic rather than history. ''Thiruvallikkeni'' finds various mentions in [[Divya Prabandha|Naalaayira Divya prabandham]] in the hymns of [[Thirumangai Alvar|Thirumangai Aazhvaar]],<ref name=\"1074 divya prabhandham\">{{cite web|title=verse 1074 by Thirumangai Alwar, in the 4000 divya prabhandam|url=http://dravidaveda.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1483:1074&catid=173:--3|work=dravidaveda.org/|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> [[Peyalwar|Peyaazhvaar]] and Thirumazhisai Piran - hymn 2416 in Naanmukan Thiruvandhaadhi forming part of the divine 4000 Divyya Prabhandam.<ref name=\"2297 divya prabhandham\">{{cite web|title=verse 2297 by peyalwar |url=http://dravidaveda.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2886|work=dravidaveda.org/|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> 8th century poet Thirumangai Aazhvaar described Thiruvallikkeni as a densely [[Canopy (biology)|canopied]] forest with peacocks and koels, where the sun's rays cannot penetrate.<ref name=\"culture not changed\"/> Peyaazhvaar describes Thiruvallikkeni as a place having a beach, where white waves bring precious gems like red corals and white pearls to the shore and light up the area with beautiful colours.<ref name=\"2297 divya prabhandham\"/>\n\n===Medieval era===\nThe evidence from stone inscriptions indicates that [[Parthasarathy temple|Paarthasaarathy temple]] was built in the 8th century by a Pallava King.<ref>{{cite news|title=Religious facets of Thirumayilai, Thiruvallikeni|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article2725003.ece|accessdate= 3 April 2012|author=Lalithasai |newspaper=The Hindu|date=18 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"chennai, rina kamath\">{{cite book|last=Rina Kamath|title=Chennai|year=2000|publisher=Orient Blackswan, 2000|location=Chennai|isbn= 9788125013785|pages=275|url= }}</ref><ref name=\"indian encyclopaedia, vol1\">{{cite book|last=Subodh Kapoor|title=The Indian Encyclopaedia, Volume 1|publisher=Genesis Publishing Pvt Ltd, 2002|isbn= 9788177552577|pages=8250|url= }}</ref> The temple was later expanded by the [[Pallavas]], [[Cholas]], [[Vijayanagara]] rulers.<ref name=\"unique temple\"/><ref name=\"chennai, rina kamath\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Narasiah|first=K. R. A.|title=Madras : tracing the growth of the city since 1639|year=2008|publisher=Oxygen Books|location=Chennai|isbn=9788183687898|pages=278 }}</ref> It has been recorded that a rivulet, Kaivareni, ran across Triplicane and Mylapore.<ref name=\"hindu temple tank\">http://www.thehinduimages.com/hindu/photoDetail.do?photoId=4925623</ref> Legend has it that the rivulet connected two water bodies: the temple tank of Paarthasaarathy temple and a sacred well, Mani Kairavani, in the flower garden of [[Adikesava Perumal temple, Mylapore|Aadi Kesava Perumaal temple]] of Mylapore.<ref name=\"hindu temple tank\"/> It is believed that [[Peyalvar|Peyaazhvaar]], one of the 12 [[alvars|Aazhvaars]], was born on a lily flower in this well and that he sailed through the rivulet to worship [[Lord Krishna]] in the Paarthasaarathy temple.<ref>{{cite news|last=N.Meera Raghavendra Rao|title=Abounds in Legends|url=http://www.hindu.com/2001/05/28/stories/13280796.htm|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=28 May 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"google books south indian shrines\">{{cite book|last=P.V.Jagadisa Ayyar|title=South Indian Shrines|year=1982|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=New Delhi - 16, Madras - 14|url= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=V Subburaj|title=Tourist Guide to Chennai Gateway of South India.|year=2006|publisher=Gardners Books, Sura Books|location=Chennai|isbn= 9788174780409}}</ref> To commemorate this, the idol of Peyaazhvaar in Mylapore is brought, in a procession, to Paarthasaarathy temple every year in the month of September.<ref>{{cite web|last=Usha Raja|title=Mylai Aadhikesava Perumal temple|url=http://chennaionline.com/Religion/Temples/May09/03Mylai-Aadhikesava-Perumal-temple.aspx|work=chennai online, 4 May 2009|publisher=Chennai Online Website|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> Peyaazhlvaar temple was built in the 13th century.<ref name=\"peyalwar\">{{cite news|title=A slice of heritage|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/religion/article2923794.ece|accessdate=19 March 2012|author=Geetha Venkatraman|newspaper=The Hindu|date=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===British era===\n[[File:Triplicane Pycrofts Road 1906.jpg|thumb|left|Triplicane Pycrofts Road in 1906]]\nIn the 1600s, Triplicane was a separate village. After about a century, British found Triplicane to be a good area for settlement and a large number of people moved there. In 1668, Triplicane was annexed to the Madras City.<ref name=\"official chennai website\">{{cite web|title=Official website of Chennai District|url=http://www.chennai.tn.nic.in/chndistprof.htm#evt|accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> From that time, Triplicane grew in importance, second only to George Town.<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmdachennai.gov.in/Volume3_English_PDF/Vol3_Chapter01_Structure%20of%20Chennai.pdf|title=Structure of Chennai}}</ref> In addition, the presence of the [[Nawab of Arcot|Nawaab of Arcot]] increased the economic prosperity of the area, and many Muslims settled in Triplicane. In 1795, the Wallajah Mosque was built.<ref name=\"ChennaiBest_History1751-1800\">{{cite web\n | last =\n | first =\n | authorlink =\n | title = 1751 A.D. to 1800 A.D.\n | work = History of Chennai\n | publisher = ChennaiBest.com\n | url = http://www.chennaibest.com/discoverchennai/sightseeing/history/1751.asp\n | format =\n | doi =\n | accessdate = 20 January 2013}}</ref> During this period, [[Chepauk Palace]] and [[Amir Mahal]] were also built.<ref name=\"official chennai website\" /> \n\nIn 1841, Ice House was built to store ice bars imported from America through ships. Ice bars were imported to provide the English a temporary relief from the blistering heat.<ref name=\"chennai, rina kamath\" /> This building was renamed [[Vivekanandar Illam|Vivekaananda house]] after [[Swami Vivekananda|Swami Vivekaananda]] stayed in the building for a brief while. \n\nIn the mid-19th century, numerous educational institutions were formed in the area. The Hindu Higher Secondary School was started in 1853<ref name=\"Hindu high school\">{{cite news\n  | last = Muthiah\n  | first = S.\n  | title =   Presidency's feeder\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | date = 2 February 2004\n  | url = http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/02/02/stories/2004020200140300.htm\n  | accessdate = 3 December 2013}}</ref> and the Presidency College in 1864\u201365. In 1870, the Presidency College was moved to its present location on Beach Road. In 1884, the Marina Beach prominade was built.<ref name=\"beach_thehindu\">{{cite news\n  | last = Muthiah\n  | first = S.\n  | title = The second longest beach?\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | date = 21 August 2002\n  | url = http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/08/21/stories/2002082100220300.htm\n  | accessdate = 31 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tercentenary\">{{cite book | title=Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee Commemoration Volume| url=| last=Tercentenary Madras Staff| year=1939| publisher=Indian Branch, Oxford Press|pages=271\u2013273}}</ref> In 1896, [[Sri Parthasarathy Swami Sabha|Sri Paarthasaarathy Swami Sabha]] (SPSS), the oldest performing arts sabha in Chennai, was founded and operated from the Hindu High School on Big Street<ref>{{cite news|last=Aruna V. Iyer|title=Survivors of Time - Big name, but no fixed address|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/survivors-of-time-big-name-but-no-fixed-address/article2548720.ece|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper= The Hindu|date=18 October 2011}}</ref><!--NEED TO BE EXPANDED-->\n\nThe building which currently serves as the Triplicane police station was built around 1891 to guard Madrasapatnam.<ref name=\"triplicane police station\">{{cite news|last=Ajitha Karthikeyan|title=City's oldest police stn saved from the hammer|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-12-23/chennai/28081477_1_police-station-police-force-oldest-police|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=Times of india, Chennai|date=23 December 2009}}</ref> This building is the City's oldest police station.<ref name=\"triplicane police station\"/> Triplicane High Road is one of the roads that had a tram line running through it during the British reign.<ref name=\"tram city lifeline\">{{cite news|last=S.Muthaih|title=Once the City's lifeline|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2007/09/24/stories/2007092450450500.htm|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Metro Plus, Chennai|date=24 September 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"tram mentioned\">{{cite news|last=Anusha Parthasarathy|title=Heaven on Earth|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article907500.ece|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Metro Plus, Chennai|date=23 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"indian express tram1\">{{cite news|title=Military Lorry collides with Tram Car|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y7Q-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=VEwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6056,5662162&dq=triplicane+trams&hl=en|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express, Madras|date=23 May 1945}}</ref>\n\nIn 1904, [[Triplicane Urban Co-Operative Society]] (TUCS) was started.<ref name=\"Cooperative society\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tn.gov.in/policynotes/archives/policy2008-09/cooperation.htm |title=Introduction |work=Government of Tamil Nadu |accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref> The consumer cooperative society predates even the first Cooperative Credit Societies Act of 1904,<ref name=\"TUCS History\">{{cite news\n  | last = Balaji\n  | first = R.\n  | title =   Triplicane Urban Co-op Society turns 100\n  | newspaper = Business Line\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | publisher = The Hindu\n  | date = 8 April 2004\n  | url = http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/2004/04/09/stories/2004040901101700.htm\n  | accessdate = 3 December 2013}}</ref> which officially ushered in the Cooperative movement into India. It runs a super market, self-service department stores, sells automobile fuel and cooking gas, and has more than 200 ration shops under the Public Distribution System.<ref name=\"TUCS History\"/>\n\nIn 1916, Star Cinema Theatre was built on Triplicane High Road. This age-old theatre has been set for demolition in March 2012.<ref name=\"Star theatre\">{{cite news\n  | last = Sujatha\n  | first = R.\n  |author2=Kolappan B.\n   | title = It's curtains for Star theatre\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | date = 6 March 2012\n  | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/its-curtains-for-star-theatre/article2964707.ece\n  | accessdate = 6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925, Mahatma Gandhi visited Triplicane to address a huge public meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=What Gandhiji said at Triplicane|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ook-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=80sMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6441,7018749&dq=triplicane+gandhi&hl=en|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express, Madras|date=20 December 1933}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=S.Muthaih|title=Gandhi and the Tamils|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2009/08/31/stories/2009083150120200.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Metro Plus, Chennai|date=31 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gandhi had a deep connection with Chennai|url=http://m.ibnlive.com/news/gandhi-had-a-deep-connection-with-chennai/225380-62.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=IBN Live website, Taken from The New Indian Express}}</ref> In 1933, Gandhiji revisited the neighbourhood. In 1934, the first cricket match was played at the Chepauk Stadium<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/58008.html|title=MA Chidambaram Stadium &#124; India &#124; Cricket Grounds &#124; ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century, Triplicane became one of the major residential areas of Madras.\n\n===Post-Independence===\nIn 1963, Ice house was renamed as Vivekananda House.<ref name=\"official chennai website\" /><ref name=\"a tale of two memorials\">{{cite news|last=Swahilya and K. Lakshmi|title=A tale of two memorials|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/07/29/stories/2007072950860200.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=29 July 2007}}</ref> In 1993, Bharathiyar Illam was converted into a memorial.<ref name=\"a tale of two memorials\" />\n\nIn October 1997, the first train ran through the Thiruvallikeni MRTS Railway Station. The train was between Chennai Beach and Thirumayilai<ref>http://www.infobanc.com/india_view/states/tamilnadu.htm</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=S.Sasidharan|title=Rs 1.97 crore state share to MRTS|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/rs-197-crore-state-share-mrts-369|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle, Chennai|date=15 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.irfca.org/members/archive/messages.php?index=91 |title = &#91;IRFCA&#93; Message Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=N. Ramakrishnan|title=Part of MRTS-III may run on single stilts|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/2002/03/18/stories/2002031800821300.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=18 March 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Raja Simhan T. E|title=Chennai's MRTS: Not on fast track, yet|url=http://www.hindu.com/businessline/2000/05/29/stories/092971rs.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=Business Line, The Hindu Group, Chennai|date=29 May 2000}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 December 2004, Indian Ocean tsunami hit Triplicane.<ref name = \"tsunami effect\">{{cite web\n | title = Tsunami: Impact & Damage\n | publisher = Government of Tamil Nadu\n | url = http://www.tn.gov.in/tsunami/digitallibrary/ebooks-web/TOTPART1/02_impact.pdf\n | page = 21\n | accessdate = 5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nTriplicane lies on the banks of the [[Buckingham Canal]] which bisects the neighbourhood along the north\u2013south direction. The neighbourhood is bordered by Marina Beach on the east on the shore of the Bay of Bengal, [[Chepauk]] on the north, [[Royapettah]] on the west and northwest, [[Mylapore]] on the southwest, and [[Santhome]] on the south.\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = Areas of Chennai\n|Northwest = [[Chintadripet]]\n|North     = [[Chepauk]]\n|Northeast = [[Marina Beach]] / [[Bay of Bengal]]\n|West      = [[Royapettah]]\n|Centre    = Triplicane\n|East      = Marina Beach / Bay of Bengal\n|Southwest = [[Mylapore]]\n|South     = [[Santhome]]\n|Southeast = Marina Beach / Bay of Bengal\n}}\n\n==Geography==\n{{bar box\n|width=250px\n|barwidth=100px\n|title=Natural hazards\n|left1=Hazard\n|right1=Percentage\n|float=left\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Earthquake|#FF7E00|60}}\n{{bar percent|Flood|#00693E|90}}\n{{bar percent|Drought|#5218FA|100}}\n{{bar percent|Landslide|#FF007F|0}}\n{{bar percent|Volcano|#FF007F|0}}\n{{bar percent|Cyclone|#FF007F|100}}\n}}\n\nThe neighbourhood is classified as a tropical dry forest bio-zone.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/> Being a coastal city, Chennai had many sand ridges. During the 16th century, the sea level rose and inundated lands within the settlements.<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\"/> When the sea withdrew, lagoons and ridges were left behind. One such ridge ran from the mouth of [[River Cooum]] to the present site of the Presidency College. On the rear side was a huge depression, where the college grounds have been built now. The ridge is the present [[Marina beach]].<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\"/> Further south, a U-shaped ridge ran along Besant Road and Lloyds Road enclosing the Ice House. Paarthasaarathy Temple is just by the northern area of this ridge. [[Mount Road]], now Anna Salai, ran along a tank bund and was at a high level. To the east of it, the land fell gradually, where Triplicane High Road and the Luz were formed.<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\"/>\n\nTriplicane is susceptible to strong (vi) earthquakes, with occurrences at 5 to 6 Richter. On average, it receives one tremor every 50 years.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/> However, the impact may be low. The neighbourhood is prone to periods of extreme droughts. The risk of flooding is medium-high, and chances of cyclones are low.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/>\n\n==Neighbourhood==\n[[File:Sri_Parthasarathi_temple_tank,_Thiruvallikeni,_Chennai,_India.jpg|thumb|Residential developments near the Paarthasaarathy temple.]]\nWith an area of around 5&nbsp;sq&nbsp;km, Triplicane is home to over 100,000 people, in addition to a floating population of 50,000 to 70,000.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/> Average population density of the neighbourhood is 21,329 per square kilometre.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\">{{cite web\n | last =\n | first =\n | authorlink =\n | title = Triplicane\n | publisher = Chinci World Atlas | url =http://www.chinci.com/travel/pax/q/1465781/Triplicane/IN/India/0/#1%7c0%7ctravel%7cpax%7c0%7c1465781%7cTriplicane%7cIN%7cIndia%7cAsia/Kolkata%7c25%7cRSTN%7c13.0550000%7c80.2813889%7cTamil%20N\u0101du| format = | doi =\n | accessdate = 7 February 2013}}</ref> Being an old neighbourhood of the city, it is congested with narrow lanes and streets.<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Mithran\n | first = Ashoka\n | title = The Small lanes of Triplicane\n | newspaper = Chennai Online\n | publisher = ChennaiOnline.com\n | date = 28 February 2009\n | url = http://chennaionline.com/Columns/Retrochennai/Feb09/02RC12.aspx\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Housing==\n{{Empty section|date=September 2012}}\n\n===Boarding houses===\n\nKnown as 'Bachelor's Paradise', Triplicane is home to about 200 lodging houses (locally known as mansions) out of the 700 odd ones in the city,<ref name=\"LiveLifeMansionSize\"/> many of them having about 30 to 60 rooms each.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/><ref name=\"DownMemoryLane_TriplicaneRevisited\">{{cite news\n | author = Sudhangan\n | title = Down memory lane: Triplicane revisited\n | newspaper = Sify News\n | publisher = SifyNews.com\n | date = 16 August 2008\n | url = http://www.sify.com/news/down-memory-lane-triplicane-revisited-news-national-jehbu6efecg.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"RoomsWithoutAView\">{{cite news\n | last = Ramesh\n | first = Niranjana\n | title = Rooms without a view\n | newspaper = Live Mint\n | publisher = LiveMint.com\n | date = 1 July 2011\n | url = http://www.livemint.com/2011/07/01195625/Rooms-without-a-view.html?h=B\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Soon after India's Independence, lodging houses began to appear in the area to cater to the needs of the individual migrants from various parts of the country. The first four lodging houses, known locally as mansions, were built in the 1950s by farmers from the southern parts of [[Tamil Nadu]] after successive droughts had threatened their livelihood. They gave out rooms on rent to traders who came to the city from other parts of the state. These are owned today by their progeny, without much change in their structures. Famous people who have at one time or another lived in the bachelor pads of Triplicane were Periyaar E V Raamaswaami Naicker, C N Annaadurai and M [[Karunanidhi]], the last two of whom were leaders of the DMK, who went on to become Chief Ministers.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/>\n\nAvailability of low-cost rentals and different affordable cuisines in the area are said to be reasos behind the constant patronage to these mansions for decades.<ref name=\"LiveLifeMansionSize\">{{cite news\n | last = Anand\n | first = S.\n | title = Live Life. Mansion-Size.\n | newspaper = Outlook India\n | publisher = OutlookIndia.com\n | date = 11 March 2002\n | url = http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?214874\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"HousesOnTheBeach\">{{cite news\n | last = Iyengar\n | first = Pushpa\n | title = Houses On The Beach\n | newspaper = Outlook India\n | publisher = OutlookIndia.com\n | date = 8 March 2010\n | url = http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?264466\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Recently, these lodging houses have started attracting a more gentrified crowd.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/>\n\n==Roads==\n[[File:Ezhilagam.jpg|thumb|200px|Ezhilagam]]\n[[File:Triplicane High Road.JPG|thumb|200px|Triplicane High Road]]\nThe main roads of Triplicane include Beach Road (Kamarajar Salai), Pycrofts Road (Bharathi Salai), Triplicane High Road, and Besant Road. Pycrofts Road, also known as Bharathi Salai, is known for its numerous book shops, including pavement shops selling old and used books.<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Mithran\n | first = Ashoka\n | title = Good old Pycrofts road\n | newspaper = Chennai Online\n | publisher = ChennaiOnline.com\n | date = 9 January 2009\n | url = http://chennaionline.com/Columns/Retrochennai/Jan09/01RC06.aspx\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Frederick\n | first = Prince\n | title = The knowledge street\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n\n | date = 23 April 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/article1719464.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> [[Zam Bazaar]] is one of the oldest bazaar in the city and was set up in the pre-Independence era. The western end of the market is bordered by an old monument known as the '''[[Amir Mahal]]''', the palace of the Nawab of Arcot two centuries ago. The building is currently being renovated by the government.<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Damani\n | first = Neha\n | title = Market value\n | newspaper = India Today\n | publisher = IndiaToday.com\n | date = 9 January 2009\n | url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Market+value/1/24736.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Jona Gilon\n | first = Catherine\n | title = Bazaar Buzz\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n\n | date = 23 March 2008\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/rp/2008/03/23/stories/2008032350130300.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe neighbourhood, however, suffers from drainage issues and other civic problems.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Sewage floods Triplicane roads\n | newspaper = Deccan Chronicle\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 30 April 2012\n | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/sewage-floods-triplicane-roads-136\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title = Drainage issues plague Triplicane\n | newspaper = IBN Live\n | location = Chennai\n | publisher = Express News Service\n | date = 2 May 2012\n | url = http://ibnlive.in.com/news/drainage-issues-plague-triplicane/253671-60-120.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:University of Madras campus in Triplicane.jpg|thumb|left|190px|Triplicane campus of the University of Madras]]\n[[File:State Council for Higher Secondary Education, Chennai.jpg|thumb|left|190px|State Council for Higher Secondary Education at the Lady Wellingdon College campus]]\nThe famous colleges in the locality are [[Queen Mary's College, Chennai|Queen Mary's College]], [[Presidency College, Chennai|Presidency College]] and [[Madras University]] on the Beach Road.\nThe popular schools in this area include [[Hindu Senior Secondary School, Triplicane|Hindu Senior Secondary School]], the Kellett higher secondary school, NKT, Rex,  [[Hindu High School]], Lady Wellington school, etc. Some of these schools are very old and even dating back to the British Era, like the latter two schools.<ref name=\"Hindu high school\"/>\n\n===Library===\nLibraries in this area include Kasthuri Srinivasan Library on Besant Road, one on Peyalwar Koil street, Muhammadan Public Library<ref>{{cite news|title=Historic library at Triplicane reopens for readers|url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/21/stories/2005122121140300.htm|accessdate=4 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=21 December 2005}}</ref>  and one on Big street. The Kasturi Srinivasan library is more than 50 years old.<ref name=\"kasthuri srinivasan library\">[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article1554817.ece \"Golden jubilee celebrated\"], ''The Hindu'', Downtown, Chennai, 20 March 2011. Retrieved 3 April 2012</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nTriplicane has a rich culture. The culture associated with Parthasarathy temple and its mada veethis is a traditional and an age old one.<ref name=\"ShatteringTheStillnessOfTime\">{{cite news | last = Parthasarathy | first = Anusha | title = Shattering the stillness of time | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | date = 24 April 2012 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/society/article3349084.ece | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Rooted in tradition, Triplicane is also known for its fine artistic taste in music, dance and arts.<ref name=\"ThiruvallikeniThiruvizha_ACommunityEvent\">{{cite news\n | author = Lalithasai\n | title = Thiruvallikeni Thiruvizha: a community event\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 14 January 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article1091019.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> An annual community even known as the '''Thiruvallikeni Thiruvizha''' (literally ''Triplicane Festival'') is celebrated in January.<ref name=\"ThiruvallikeniThiruvizha_ACommunityEvent\"/><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Soman\n | first = Sandhya\n | title = A trip down memory lane\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 9 January 2007\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/2007/01/09/stories/2007010916930200.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Other festivals include Triplicane Music Festival and ''Marghazhi'' (winter) festival.<ref name=\"LinkRecaptured\">{{cite news\n | last = Ramanathan\n | first = Saradha\n | title = Link recaptured\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 21 May 2010\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/fr/2010/05/21/stories/2010052161340300.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Madhavan\n | first = T.\n | title = Triplicane Music Festival\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 25 December 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article2745871.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ColourfulTradition\">{{cite news\n | last = Suresh\n | first = S.\n | title = Colourful tradition\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 7 January 2003\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2003/01/07/stories/2003010700050200.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Triplicane is known for some of the traditionally famous cuisines of Chennai, with age-old restaurants, such as the Rathna Cafe,<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Shanmugham\n | first = Sujatha\n | title = Thali destinations\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 18 August 2010\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/Food/article580023.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Shetty\n | first = Deepika\n | title = Charming and cultured Chennai\n | newspaper = The Straits Times\n | publisher = Asia One Travel\n | date = 30 October 2008\n | url = http://travel.asiaone.com/Travel/Places%2B%2526%2BInterests/Region/Europe/Story/A1Story20081030-97292.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Badrinath\n | first = Mallika\n | title = Off the menu\n | newspaper = India Today\n | publisher = IndiaToday.in\n | date = 3 September 2008\n | url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Off+the+menu/1/14399.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> being based here.\n\n===Architecture===\n[[File:AnnieBesantPark Triplicane Chennai.jpg|thumb|210px|[[Dr. Annie Besant Park, Chennai|Annie Besant Park]]]]\n[[File:AnnieBesantPark Triplicane Chennai FishermenStatue.jpg|thumb|210px|Fishermen statue at Annie Besant Park]]\nTriplicane, similar to few other areas in the city such as Mylapore and West Mambalam, is known for its traditional row houses, known as ''agraharams''.<ref name=\"Agraharam_TimeVirtuallyStandsStill\">{{cite news\n | last = Sujatha\n | first = R.\n | title = Agraharam \u2014 time virtually stands still here\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 29 April 2012\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article3367816.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Typically, these can be seen where an entire street is occupied by Brahmins, particularly surrounding a temple. The architecture is distinctive with Madras terraces, country tile roofing, Burma teak rafters and lime plastering. The longish homes consisted of the ''mudhal kattu'' (receiving quarters), ''irandaam kattu'' (living quarters), ''moondram kattu'' (kitchen and backyard) and so on. Most houses had an open to sky space in the centre called the ''mitham'', large platforms lining the outside of the house called the ''thinnai'' and a private well in the backyard. The floors were often coated with red oxide and sometimes the roofs had glass tiles to let in light. The agraharam quadrangle seen in Triplicane is around the Parthasarathy Temple and its tank.<ref name=\"VanishingAgraharams\"/>\n\nAbout 50 families continue to live in the agraharams in Triplicane.<ref name=\"Agraharam_TimeVirtuallyStandsStill\"/> However, many of these houses are being replaced with modern multi-storied apartments, resulting in a reduction in their numbers.<ref name=\"VanishingAgraharams\">{{cite news\n | last = Iyer\n | first = Aruna V.\n | title = Chennai's vanishing agraharams\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n\n | date = 7 October 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/homes-and-gardens/article2518383.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Places of worship===\nAlthough [[Parthasarathy Temple]] remains the most important temple of Triplicane, there exists indeed several other temples in the neighbourhood, including [[Ellamman temple|Ellai Amman Temple]] and nearby Sundaramurthy vinayaka temple, Kulathangarai Anjeneya Temple (on the steps on the Parthasarathy temple tank), Anjeneya Temple on Tank Street, Tula Singa Perumal Temple, [[Ahobila Mutt]] Temple on Car Street, Kaamakala Kameshwarar Temple on Raja Hanumantha lala street, Anjaneyar temple on Hanumantha Rayan street, Muthu Vinayakar Temple on Muthu Kallathy Street, Anjeneya Temple on Besant Road, [[Ettampadai Temple|Ettampadai Murugan Temple]], Raghavendra Temple and Mutt on T.P Koil Street, Panduranga swami temple on Venkatachalam street, Vinayaka temples on big street and at the market, Temples on Raja Hanumantha Lala Lane, Udupi Sri Krishna Temple and Mutt, Sri Krishna mandiram, Peyalwar Temple built on the 13th century.<ref name=\"peyalwar\" /> and Thiruveteeswarar Temple. The thevaram has a reference of Thiruvateeswarar temple, which suggests its existence since the 7th century.\n\nMutts in the region include [[Uttaradi Matha|Uttradi Mutt]] on Singrachari Street, [[Ahobila Mutt]] and Temple on Car Street, Vanamamalai Mutt on East Tank Square Street,<ref>http://www.vanamamalai.com/mutt/mutt.html</ref> Raghavendra Mutt and Temple on T. P. Koil Street, Vysaraja Mutt, Yadugiri Yathiraja Mutt, and few others situated around Parthasarathy Temple or mada veethis.\n\n[[The Wallajah Mosque]], also known as the Big Mosque, is one of the famous historical mosques in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapsofindia.com/chennai/places-of-interest/religious-places/big-mosque.html|title=Big Mosque, Chennai|website=www.mapsofindia.com}}</ref> Built in 1795 in remembrance of Nawab Wallajah, the mosque was constructed with grey granite, without the use of wood or steel.<ref name=\"ChennaiBest_History1751-1800\"/>\n\n====Vaikunta Ekadesi====\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nVaikunta Ekadesi Festival is very famous in this temple and huge crowds gather to visit the temple on this day.<ref name=\"temple tales of triplicane toi\">{{cite news|title=Temple tales of Triplicane|author=Srinivasa Ramanujam|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-15/travel/29922568_1_parthasarathy-temple-triplicane-vaikunta-ekadasi|accessdate=19 March 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/religious-fervour-marks-vaikunta-ekadasi-chennai-347 \"Religious fervour marks Vaikunta Ekadasi in Chennai\"], ''Deccan Chronicle'', Chennai, 6 January 2012. Retrieved on 3 April 2012</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=In City|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RgBFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YrcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4047,1197453&dq=triplicane+parthasarathy&hl=en|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express, Madras|date=12 March 1949}}</ref>\nVaikunta Ekadesi vrata is observed on Dhanur Masa Shukla Paksha Ekadasi or on the 11th day of bright fortnight during Dhanur Masam. This festival is celebrated with lot of devotion in many Vaishnavaite temples including Parthasarathy temple in South India. Vaikunta Dwara lies in the North side of the temple. Vaikunta Ekadesi is also observed as Mukkoti Ekadesi.\n\nUnmindful of the chill, the streets of Triplicane would be milling with people as early as 2&nbsp;am on Vaikunta Ekadesi. Women adorning the traditional nine yards or a silk sari would be seen hurrying towards the Parthasarathy Temple to find a place in the long winding queues that stretched infinitely even in those wee hours.\n\nJostling against each other  people at a snail's space towards the shrine. It was obvious that they want to cross the Paramapadavaasal along with the presiding deity. More than '''one lakh devotees''' visit the temple who are helped by volunteers, temple authorities and police personnel, to move around the prakarams. Police would be stationed around the temple and atop watchtowers at the junction of the Mada Streets to maintain strict vigil.<ref>Lalithasai. [http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article962339.ece \"When the doors of Paramapadavaasal open...\"], ''The Hindu'', Downtown, Chennai, 19 December 2010. Retrieved 3 April 2012</ref><ref>M Bharat Kumar, K Vivek prasad. [http://www.newstodaynet.com/newsindex.php?id=20795+&+section=7 \"Devotees throng temples for Vaikunta Ekadesi\"], ''[[The News Today (India)|News Today]]'', 28 December 2009, Chennai. Retrieved 3 April 2012</ref>\n\n===Carnatic Music===\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nTriplicane was also once the seat of [[Carnatic music]]. Many famous personalities in this industry visited or resided in triplicane.<ref name=\"when streets resonated with ragas\">Gowri Ramnarayan. [http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/12/24/stories/2002122400210300.htm \"When streets resonated with ragas\"], ''The Hindu'', Metro Plus, Chennai, 24 December 2002. Retrieved on 3 April 2012</ref>  Triplicane was not only known for weekend visits by famous musicians, but also for resident legends such as G.N. Balasubramaniam and M.S. Subbulakshmi. The right atmosphere for music and dance permeated Triplicane. A proliferation of sabhas \u2013 Triplicane Arts Academy, Thiruvateeswarar Sabha, N.K.T. Muthu Sabha and Parthasarathy Swami Sabha \u2013 drew these heavyweights in the classical arts to the locality.<ref name=\"my heart beats for triplicane\">Written by Prince Frederick, as told by Vikku Vinayakram. [http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article1480313.ece \"Memories of Madras - \u2018My heart beats for Triplicane'\"], ''The Hindu'', Arts - History & Culture, 22 February 2011. Retrieved on 3 April 2012.</ref>\nOnce musicians used to talk of how they had sung at the Hindu High School or heard GNB at some other Triplicane venue. Sadly, with time, that kind of talk died out. Legends M.S. Subbulakshmi and GNB lived in Triplicane once, and it was said that this was where vidwans would spend afternoons discussing music over hot rava pongal at the Krishna Iyer Hotel. The 1965s and 1970s saw music and dance pervade the area in various sabhas. From the concerts of M.S. and GNB to Manakkal Rangarajan; from the stage plays of M.G. Ramachandran and Sivaji Ganesan to actor Sivakumar's debut play \u2013 this place has hosted leading artists of those days. You name them and they have been performed here. Thus Triplicane was the central locality where all the cultural happenings of the city took place, and all the famous personalities used to come down to perform.<ref>{{cite news|last=Renuka Suryanarayan|title=Back in full force...|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article2677239.ece|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Chennai assembly constituencys Chepauk-Triplicane.png|thumb|right|100px|Chennai assembly Chepauk-Triplicane constituency]]\nTriplicane is a part of Chepauk-Triplicane assembly constituency which in turn a part of [[Chennai South (Lok Sabha constituency)|Chennai South constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2001/background/S22/TN_ACPC.pdf\n |title       = List of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies\n |accessdate  = 8 October 2008\n |work        = Tamil Nadu\n |publisher   = Election Commission of India\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060504185928/http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2001/background/S22/TN_ACPC.pdf\n |archivedate = 4 May 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> The MLA Hostel is located on [[Wallajah Road, Chennai|Wallajah Road]]. [[Rajaji Hall]] in the same campus, which was built between 1800 and 1802,<ref name=\"groseclosep34\">{{cite book|title=British sculpture and the Company Raj: church monuments and public statuary in Madras, Calcutta, and Bombay to 1858|first=Barbara S.|last=Groseclose|page=34|publisher=University of Delaware Press|year=1995|isbn= 978-0-87413-406-3}}</ref> used to have a role in state administration. At present, it houses the offices of the Tamil Nadu State Raffle.<ref name=\"chopra\">{{cite book|title=Monuments of the Raj: British buildings in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and Myanmar|pages=7\u20138|first=Prabha|last=Chopra|publisher=Aryan Books International|year=1999|isbn= 978-81-7305-094-7}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\n{{See also|Thiruvallikeni (Chennai MRTS)}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2012}}\nBeing situated in the central region of the city, Triplicane is well connected to various places in Chennai. The [[Metropolitan Transport Corporation (Chennai)|MTC]] had bus termini such as the Ice House and Triplicane (located at Pycrofts Road). The Triplicane bus terminus, one of the oldest bus termini in the city, is not functional now. The MTC has moved all services which were originating from Triplicane to the near-by Anna square terminus and some services are extended to Broadway. The [[Mass Rapid Transit System (Chennai)|MRTS]] has a station [[Thiruvallikeni (Chennai MRTS)|Thiruvallikeni]] on the Chennai Beach\u2013Velachery elevated rail corridor serving the neighbourhood. In addition, the neighbourhood is served by private auto rickshaws.\n\n==Famous personalities==\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nTriplicane is famous for the various personalities it has produced over the years. Mathematician [[Srinivasa Ramanujan]],<ref>Hema Vijay. [http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/society/article2134518.ece \"The man who knows Ramanujan\"],''Life & Style - Society, The Hindu'', 26 June 2011. Retrieved on 3 April 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=K. Srinivasa Rao|title=Srinivasa Ramanujan|url=http://www.imsc.res.in/~rao/ramanujan.html|work=Article from The Institute of Mathematical Sciences official website|publisher=The Institute of Mathematical Sciences (IMSC)|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Prince Frederick|title=The street where Ramanujan lived|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2003/12/24/stories/2003122400180100.htm|accessdate=4 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu|date=24 December 2003}}</ref> Writer [[Sujatha Rangarajan]], and cricketers [[M.J. Gopalan]], [[Krishnamachari Srikkanth|Krish Srikkanth]] and [[W.V. Raman]] all hailed from Triplicane. [[Nobel prize]] winner [[Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar]] did his schooling in the [[The Hindu Higher Secondary School|Hindu High School]] (1922\u20131925) in Triplicane. [[Subramanya Bharathy]], a freedom fighter and poet, lived his last years in the house opposite the parthasarathy temple's western entrance; the house has since been bought and renovated by the Government of Tamil Nadu in 1993, and it was named Bharathiyar Illam (Home of Bharathiyar).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods of Chennai}}\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Chennai district]]\n[[Category:Coastal neighbourhoods of Chennai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Triplicane\n| other_name = Tiruvallikeni\n| settlement_type = neighbourhood\n| image_skyline = Tiruvallikeni1.jpg\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption = Triplicane Pond and Parthasarthy temple Gopuram\n| nickname =\n| image_map =\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption =\n| pushpin_map = India Chennai#Tamil Nadu#India\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| pushpin_map_alt =\n| pushpin_map_caption =\n| coordinates = {{coord|13.0553|N|80.2807|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = India\n| subdivision_type1 = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Chennai District]]\n| subdivision_type3 = Metro\n| subdivision_name3 = Chennai\n| established_title = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date =\n| founder =\n| named_for =\n| parts_type = [[Taluka]]s\n| parts = [[Mylapore-Triplicane]]\n| government_type =\n| governing_body = Chennai Corporation\n| unit_pref = Metric\n| area_footnotes =\n| area_rank =\n| area_total_km2 =\n| elevation_footnotes =\n| elevation_m =\n| population_total =\n| population_as_of =\n| population_rank =\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_demonym =\n| population_footnotes =\n| demographics_type1 = Languages\n| demographics1_title1 = Official\n| demographics1_info1 = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| timezone1 = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1 = +5:30\n| postal_code_type = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code = 600005\n| registration_plate =\n| blank1_name_sec1 = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1 = Chennai Central\n| blank2_name_sec1 = [[Urban planning|Planning]] agency\n| blank2_info_sec1 = [[Chennai Metropolitan Development Authority|CMDA]]\n| blank3_name_sec1 = Civic agency\n| blank3_info_sec1 = Chennai Corporation\n| website = {{URL|www.chennai.tn.nic.in}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Triplicane''', also known as '''Thiruvallikeni''', is one of the oldest neighbourhoods of [[Chennai]], [[India]]. It is situated on the [[Bay of Bengal]] coast and about {{convert|0.5|km|abbr=on}} from [[Fort St George]]. The average elevation of the neighbourhood is 14&nbsp;metres above [[Mean sea level|sea level]].<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/>\n\nAlong with [[Mylapore]] and the surrounding regions, Triplicane is historically much older than the city of Chennai itself, with a mention in records as early as the [[Pallava]] period.<ref name=\"TempleTalesOfTriplicane\"/><ref name=\"LinkRecaptured\"/> Primarily a residential region, it is home to some of the tourist attractions of the city, such as the [[Marina Beach]], [[Parthasarathy Temple, Triplicane|the Paarthasaarathy Temple]] and several commercial establishments. Triplicane is equally famous for its rich traditional culture, which is prominent in and around the four East, South, West and North streets (known as \"maada veedhi\" in Tamil) of the Paarthasarthy Temple.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name ''Triplicane'' is the [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] version of ''Thiruvallikeni'', which derives from ''Thiru-Alli-Keni'' (Sacred Lily Pond, in Tamil), denoting the pond in front of the [[Parthasarathy temple]], which was amidst a big Tulasi forest.<ref name=\"TempleTalesOfTriplicane\">{{cite news | last = Ramanujam | first = Srinivasa | title = Temple tales of Triplicane | newspaper = The Times of India | location = Chennai | publisher = The Times Group | date = 15 September 2011\n | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-15/travel/29922568_1_parthasarathy-temple-triplicane-vaikunta-ekadasi\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\">{{cite news | last = Narasimhan | first = T. E. | title = Chennai central | newspaper = Business Standard | location = Chennai | date = 31 March 2012 | url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/chennai-central/469586/ | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> The place is also referred as ''Brindaranyam'' in [[Brahmanda Purana]], owing to the presence of the tulasi (brinda) plants in the area.<ref name=\"culture not changed\">{{cite news|title=The benign radiance of Gitacharyan|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2004/05/21/stories/2004052102020600.htm|accessdate=4 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Online Edition, Chennai&nbsp;\u2014 Entertainment section|date=21 May 2004}}</ref> It is also referred to as 'Brindaranya kshetra'<ref>{{cite book|author=T. Padmaja|title=Temples of Kr\u0325\u1e63\u1e47a in South India: History, Art, and Traditions in Tamiln\u0101\u1e0du|year=2002|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=8170173981|pages=129|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F-_eR1isesMC}}</ref> and 'Southern Brindavana'.<ref name=\"unique temple\">{{cite news|last=K. V. Raman|title=Unique temple|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/05/07/stories/2002050700080200.htm|accessdate=3 February 2013|newspaper=The Hindu Metro Plus|date=7 May 2002|location=Chennai}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Triplicane Pond.jpg|thumb|Triplicane pond]]\n\n==History==\n\n===Literary mention===\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nThe early records of the town are rooted to epic rather than history. ''Thiruvallikkeni'' finds various mentions in [[Divya Prabandha|Naalaayira Divya prabandham]] in the hymns of [[Thirumangai Alvar|Thirumangai Aazhvaar]],<ref name=\"1074 divya prabhandham\">{{cite web|title=verse 1074 by Thirumangai Alwar, in the 4000 divya prabhandam|url=http://dravidaveda.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1483:1074&catid=173:--3|work=dravidaveda.org/|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> [[Peyalwar|Peyaazhvaar]] and Thirumazhisai Piran - hymn 2416 in Naanmukan Thiruvandhaadhi forming part of the divine 4000 Divyya Prabhandam.<ref name=\"2297 divya prabhandham\">{{cite web|title=verse 2297 by peyalwar |url=http://dravidaveda.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2886|work=dravidaveda.org/|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> 8th century poet Thirumangai Aazhvaar described Thiruvallikkeni as a densely [[Canopy (biology)|canopied]] forest with peacocks and koels, where the sun's rays cannot penetrate.<ref name=\"culture not changed\"/> Peyaazhvaar describes Thiruvallikkeni as a place having a beach, where white waves bring precious gems like red corals and white pearls to the shore and light up the area with beautiful colours.<ref name=\"2297 divya prabhandham\"/>\n\n===Medieval era===\nThe evidence from stone inscriptions indicates that [[Parthasarathy temple|Paarthasaarathy temple]] was built in the 8th century by a Pallava King.<ref>{{cite news|title=Religious facets of Thirumayilai, Thiruvallikeni|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article2725003.ece|accessdate= 3 April 2012|author=Lalithasai |newspaper=The Hindu|date=18 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"chennai, rina kamath\">{{cite book|last=Rina Kamath|title=Chennai|year=2000|publisher=Orient Blackswan, 2000|location=Chennai|isbn= 9788125013785|pages=275|url= }}</ref><ref name=\"indian encyclopaedia, vol1\">{{cite book|last=Subodh Kapoor|title=The Indian Encyclopaedia, Volume 1|publisher=Genesis Publishing Pvt Ltd, 2002|isbn= 9788177552577|pages=8250|url= }}</ref> The temple was later expanded by the [[Pallavas]], [[Cholas]], [[Vijayanagara]] rulers.<ref name=\"unique temple\"/><ref name=\"chennai, rina kamath\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Narasiah|first=K. R. A.|title=Madras : tracing the growth of the city since 1639|year=2008|publisher=Oxygen Books|location=Chennai|isbn=9788183687898|pages=278 }}</ref> It has been recorded that a rivulet, Kaivareni, ran across Triplicane and Mylapore.<ref name=\"hindu temple tank\">http://www.thehinduimages.com/hindu/photoDetail.do?photoId=4925623</ref> Legend has it that the rivulet connected two water bodies: the temple tank of Paarthasaarathy temple and a sacred well, Mani Kairavani, in the flower garden of [[Adikesava Perumal temple, Mylapore|Aadi Kesava Perumaal temple]] of Mylapore.<ref name=\"hindu temple tank\"/> It is believed that [[Peyalvar|Peyaazhvaar]], one of the 12 [[alvars|Aazhvaars]], was born on a lily flower in this well and that he sailed through the rivulet to worship [[Lord Krishna]] in the Paarthasaarathy temple.<ref>{{cite news|last=N.Meera Raghavendra Rao|title=Abounds in Legends|url=http://www.hindu.com/2001/05/28/stories/13280796.htm|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=28 May 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"google books south indian shrines\">{{cite book|last=P.V.Jagadisa Ayyar|title=South Indian Shrines|year=1982|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=New Delhi - 16, Madras - 14|url= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=V Subburaj|title=Tourist Guide to Chennai Gateway of South India.|year=2006|publisher=Gardners Books, Sura Books|location=Chennai|isbn= 9788174780409}}</ref> To commemorate this, the idol of Peyaazhvaar in Mylapore is brought, in a procession, to Paarthasaarathy temple every year in the month of September.<ref>{{cite web|last=Usha Raja|title=Mylai Aadhikesava Perumal temple|url=http://chennaionline.com/Religion/Temples/May09/03Mylai-Aadhikesava-Perumal-temple.aspx|work=chennai online, 4 May 2009|publisher=Chennai Online Website|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> Peyaazhlvaar temple was built in the 13th century.<ref name=\"peyalwar\">{{cite news|title=A slice of heritage|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/religion/article2923794.ece|accessdate=19 March 2012|author=Geetha Venkatraman|newspaper=The Hindu|date=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===British era===\n[[File:Triplicane Pycrofts Road 1906.jpg|thumb|left|Triplicane Pycrofts Road in 1906]]\nIn the 1600s, Triplicane was a separate village. After about a century, British found Triplicane to be a good area for settlement and a large number of people moved there. In 1668, Triplicane was annexed to the Madras City.<ref name=\"official chennai website\">{{cite web|title=Official website of Chennai District|url=http://www.chennai.tn.nic.in/chndistprof.htm#evt|accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> From that time, Triplicane grew in importance, second only to George Town.<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmdachennai.gov.in/Volume3_English_PDF/Vol3_Chapter01_Structure%20of%20Chennai.pdf|title=Structure of Chennai}}</ref> In addition, the presence of the [[Nawab of Arcot|Nawaab of Arcot]] increased the economic prosperity of the area, and many Muslims settled in Triplicane. In 1795, the Wallajah Mosque was built.<ref name=\"ChennaiBest_History1751-1800\">{{cite web\n | last =\n | first =\n | authorlink =\n | title = 1751 A.D. to 1800 A.D.\n | work = History of Chennai\n | publisher = ChennaiBest.com\n | url = http://www.chennaibest.com/discoverchennai/sightseeing/history/1751.asp\n | format =\n | doi =\n | accessdate = 20 January 2013}}</ref> During this period, [[Chepauk Palace]] and [[Amir Mahal]] were also built.<ref name=\"official chennai website\" /> \n\nIn 1841, Ice House was built to store ice bars imported from America through ships. Ice bars were imported to provide the English a temporary relief from the blistering heat.<ref name=\"chennai, rina kamath\" /> This building was renamed [[Vivekanandar Illam|Vivekaananda house]] after [[Swami Vivekananda|Swami Vivekaananda]] stayed in the building for a brief while. \n\nIn the mid-19th century, numerous educational institutions were formed in the area. The Hindu Higher Secondary School was started in 1853<ref name=\"Hindu high school\">{{cite news\n  | last = Muthiah\n  | first = S.\n  | title =   Presidency's feeder\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | date = 2 February 2004\n  | url = http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/02/02/stories/2004020200140300.htm\n  | accessdate = 3 December 2013}}</ref> and the Presidency College in 1864\u201365. In 1870, the Presidency College was moved to its present location on Beach Road. In 1884, the Marina Beach prominade was built.<ref name=\"beach_thehindu\">{{cite news\n  | last = Muthiah\n  | first = S.\n  | title = The second longest beach?\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | date = 21 August 2002\n  | url = http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/08/21/stories/2002082100220300.htm\n  | accessdate = 31 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tercentenary\">{{cite book | title=Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee Commemoration Volume| url=| last=Tercentenary Madras Staff| year=1939| publisher=Indian Branch, Oxford Press|pages=271\u2013273}}</ref> In 1896, [[Sri Parthasarathy Swami Sabha|Sri Paarthasaarathy Swami Sabha]] (SPSS), the oldest performing arts sabha in Chennai, was founded and operated from the Hindu High School on Big Street<ref>{{cite news|last=Aruna V. Iyer|title=Survivors of Time - Big name, but no fixed address|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/survivors-of-time-big-name-but-no-fixed-address/article2548720.ece|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper= The Hindu|date=18 October 2011}}</ref><!--NEED TO BE EXPANDED-->\n\nThe building which currently serves as the Triplicane police station was built around 1891 to guard Madrasapatnam.<ref name=\"triplicane police station\">{{cite news|last=Ajitha Karthikeyan|title=City's oldest police stn saved from the hammer|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-12-23/chennai/28081477_1_police-station-police-force-oldest-police|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=Times of india, Chennai|date=23 December 2009}}</ref> This building is the City's oldest police station.<ref name=\"triplicane police station\"/> Triplicane High Road is one of the roads that had a tram line running through it during the British reign.<ref name=\"tram city lifeline\">{{cite news|last=S.Muthaih|title=Once the City's lifeline|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2007/09/24/stories/2007092450450500.htm|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Metro Plus, Chennai|date=24 September 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"tram mentioned\">{{cite news|last=Anusha Parthasarathy|title=Heaven on Earth|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article907500.ece|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Metro Plus, Chennai|date=23 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"indian express tram1\">{{cite news|title=Military Lorry collides with Tram Car|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y7Q-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=VEwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6056,5662162&dq=triplicane+trams&hl=en|accessdate=11 April 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express, Madras|date=23 May 1945}}</ref>\n\nIn 1904, [[Triplicane Urban Co-Operative Society]] (TUCS) was started.<ref name=\"Cooperative society\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tn.gov.in/policynotes/archives/policy2008-09/cooperation.htm |title=Introduction |work=Government of Tamil Nadu |accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref> The consumer cooperative society predates even the first Cooperative Credit Societies Act of 1904,<ref name=\"TUCS History\">{{cite news\n  | last = Balaji\n  | first = R.\n  | title =   Triplicane Urban Co-op Society turns 100\n  | newspaper = Business Line\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | publisher = The Hindu\n  | date = 8 April 2004\n  | url = http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/2004/04/09/stories/2004040901101700.htm\n  | accessdate = 3 December 2013}}</ref> which officially ushered in the Cooperative movement into India. It runs a super market, self-service department stores, sells automobile fuel and cooking gas, and has more than 200 ration shops under the Public Distribution System.<ref name=\"TUCS History\"/>\n\nIn 1916, Star Cinema Theatre was built on Triplicane High Road. This age-old theatre has been set for demolition in March 2012.<ref name=\"Star theatre\">{{cite news\n  | last = Sujatha\n  | first = R.\n  |author2=Kolappan B.\n   | title = It's curtains for Star theatre\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | date = 6 March 2012\n  | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/its-curtains-for-star-theatre/article2964707.ece\n  | accessdate = 6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925, Mahatma Gandhi visited Triplicane to address a huge public meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=What Gandhiji said at Triplicane|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ook-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=80sMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6441,7018749&dq=triplicane+gandhi&hl=en|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express, Madras|date=20 December 1933}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=S.Muthaih|title=Gandhi and the Tamils|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2009/08/31/stories/2009083150120200.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Metro Plus, Chennai|date=31 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gandhi had a deep connection with Chennai|url=http://m.ibnlive.com/news/gandhi-had-a-deep-connection-with-chennai/225380-62.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=IBN Live website, Taken from The New Indian Express}}</ref> In 1933, Gandhiji revisited the neighbourhood. In 1934, the first cricket match was played at the Chepauk Stadium<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/58008.html|title=MA Chidambaram Stadium &#124; India &#124; Cricket Grounds &#124; ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century, Triplicane became one of the major residential areas of Madras.\n\n===Post-Independence===\nIn 1963, Ice house was renamed as Vivekananda House.<ref name=\"official chennai website\" /><ref name=\"a tale of two memorials\">{{cite news|last=Swahilya and K. Lakshmi|title=A tale of two memorials|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/07/29/stories/2007072950860200.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=29 July 2007}}</ref> In 1993, Bharathiyar Illam was converted into a memorial.<ref name=\"a tale of two memorials\" />\n\nIn October 1997, the first train ran through the Thiruvallikeni MRTS Railway Station. The train was between Chennai Beach and Thirumayilai<ref>http://www.infobanc.com/india_view/states/tamilnadu.htm</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=S.Sasidharan|title=Rs 1.97 crore state share to MRTS|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/rs-197-crore-state-share-mrts-369|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle, Chennai|date=15 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.irfca.org/members/archive/messages.php?index=91 |title = &#91;IRFCA&#93; Message Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=N. Ramakrishnan|title=Part of MRTS-III may run on single stilts|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/2002/03/18/stories/2002031800821300.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=18 March 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Raja Simhan T. E|title=Chennai's MRTS: Not on fast track, yet|url=http://www.hindu.com/businessline/2000/05/29/stories/092971rs.htm|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=Business Line, The Hindu Group, Chennai|date=29 May 2000}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 December 2004, Indian Ocean tsunami hit Triplicane.<ref name = \"tsunami effect\">{{cite web\n | title = Tsunami: Impact & Damage\n | publisher = Government of Tamil Nadu\n | url = http://www.tn.gov.in/tsunami/digitallibrary/ebooks-web/TOTPART1/02_impact.pdf\n | page = 21\n | accessdate = 5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nTriplicane lies on the banks of the [[Buckingham Canal]] which bisects the neighbourhood along the north\u2013south direction. The neighbourhood is bordered by Marina Beach on the east on the shore of the Bay of Bengal, [[Chepauk]] on the north, [[Royapettah]] on the west and northwest, [[Mylapore]] on the southwest, and [[Santhome]] on the south.\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = Areas of Chennai\n|Northwest = [[Chintadripet]]\n|North     = [[Chepauk]]\n|Northeast = [[Marina Beach]] / [[Bay of Bengal]]\n|West      = [[Royapettah]]\n|Centre    = Triplicane\n|East      = Marina Beach / Bay of Bengal\n|Southwest = [[Mylapore]]\n|South     = [[Santhome]]\n|Southeast = Marina Beach / Bay of Bengal\n}}\n\n==Geography==\n{{bar box\n|width=250px\n|barwidth=100px\n|title=Natural hazards\n|left1=Hazard\n|right1=Percentage\n|float=left\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Earthquake|#FF7E00|60}}\n{{bar percent|Flood|#00693E|90}}\n{{bar percent|Drought|#5218FA|100}}\n{{bar percent|Landslide|#FF007F|0}}\n{{bar percent|Volcano|#FF007F|0}}\n{{bar percent|Cyclone|#FF007F|100}}\n}}\n\nThe neighbourhood is classified as a tropical dry forest bio-zone.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/> Being a coastal city, Chennai had many sand ridges. During the 16th century, the sea level rose and inundated lands within the settlements.<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\"/> When the sea withdrew, lagoons and ridges were left behind. One such ridge ran from the mouth of [[River Cooum]] to the present site of the Presidency College. On the rear side was a huge depression, where the college grounds have been built now. The ridge is the present [[Marina beach]].<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\"/> Further south, a U-shaped ridge ran along Besant Road and Lloyds Road enclosing the Ice House. Paarthasaarathy Temple is just by the northern area of this ridge. [[Mount Road]], now Anna Salai, ran along a tank bund and was at a high level. To the east of it, the land fell gradually, where Triplicane High Road and the Luz were formed.<ref name =\"Structure of chennai_CMDA\"/>\n\nTriplicane is susceptible to strong (vi) earthquakes, with occurrences at 5 to 6 Richter. On average, it receives one tremor every 50 years.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/> However, the impact may be low. The neighbourhood is prone to periods of extreme droughts. The risk of flooding is medium-high, and chances of cyclones are low.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\"/>\n\n==Neighbourhood==\n[[File:Sri_Parthasarathi_temple_tank,_Thiruvallikeni,_Chennai,_India.jpg|thumb|Residential developments near the Paarthasaarathy temple.]]\nWith an area of around 5&nbsp;sq&nbsp;km, Triplicane is home to over 100,000 people, in addition to a floating population of 50,000 to 70,000.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/> Average population density of the neighbourhood is 21,329 per square kilometre.<ref name = \"triplicaneinfo\">{{cite web\n | last =\n | first =\n | authorlink =\n | title = Triplicane\n | publisher = Chinci World Atlas | url =http://www.chinci.com/travel/pax/q/1465781/Triplicane/IN/India/0/#1%7c0%7ctravel%7cpax%7c0%7c1465781%7cTriplicane%7cIN%7cIndia%7cAsia/Kolkata%7c25%7cRSTN%7c13.0550000%7c80.2813889%7cTamil%20N\u0101du| format = | doi =\n | accessdate = 7 February 2013}}</ref> Being an old neighbourhood of the city, it is congested with narrow lanes and streets.<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Mithran\n | first = Ashoka\n | title = The Small lanes of Triplicane\n | newspaper = Chennai Online\n | publisher = ChennaiOnline.com\n | date = 28 February 2009\n | url = http://chennaionline.com/Columns/Retrochennai/Feb09/02RC12.aspx\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Housing==\n{{Empty section|date=September 2012}}\n\n===Boarding houses===\n\nKnown as 'Bachelor's Paradise', Triplicane is home to about 200 boarding houses (locally known as mansions) out of the 700 odd ones in the city,<ref name=\"LiveLifeMansionSize\"/> many of them with about 30 to 60 rooms.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/><ref name=\"DownMemoryLane_TriplicaneRevisited\">{{cite news\n | author = Sudhangan\n | title = Down memory lane: Triplicane revisited\n | newspaper = Sify News\n | publisher = SifyNews.com\n | date = 16 August 2008\n | url = http://www.sify.com/news/down-memory-lane-triplicane-revisited-news-national-jehbu6efecg.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"RoomsWithoutAView\">{{cite news\n | last = Ramesh\n | first = Niranjana\n | title = Rooms without a view\n | newspaper = Live Mint\n | publisher = LiveMint.com\n | date = 1 July 2011\n | url = http://www.livemint.com/2011/07/01195625/Rooms-without-a-view.html?h=B\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Soon after independence, boarding houses began to appear in the area to cater to the needs of the individual migrants from various parts of the country. The first four boarding houses, known locally as mansions, were built in the 1950s by farmers from the southern parts of [[Tamil Nadu]] after successive droughts had threatened their livelihood. They gave out rooms on rent to traders who came to the city from other parts of the state. These are owned today by their progeny, without much change in their structures. Famous people who have at one time or another lived in the bachelor pads of Triplicane include political figures [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy|Periyar]], [[Annadurai]] and [[Karunanidhi]].<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/>\n\nAvailability of low-cost rentals and different affordable cuisines in the area is said to be the reason behind the constant patronage to these mansions for decades.<ref name=\"LiveLifeMansionSize\">{{cite news\n | last = Anand\n | first = S.\n | title = Live Life. Mansion-Size.\n | newspaper = Outlook India\n | publisher = OutlookIndia.com\n | date = 11 March 2002\n | url = http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?214874\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"HousesOnTheBeach\">{{cite news\n | last = Iyengar\n | first = Pushpa\n | title = Houses On The Beach\n | newspaper = Outlook India\n | publisher = OutlookIndia.com\n | date = 8 March 2010\n | url = http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?264466\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Recently, these boarding houses have started attracting a more gentrified crowd.<ref name=\"BusinessStandard_ChennaiCentral\"/>\n\n==Roads==\n[[File:Ezhilagam.jpg|thumb|200px|Ezhilagam]]\n[[File:Triplicane High Road.JPG|thumb|200px|Triplicane High Road]]\nThe main roads of Triplicane include Beach Road (Kamarajar Salai), Pycrofts Road (Bharathi Salai), Triplicane High Road, and Besant Road. Pycrofts Road, also known as Bharathi Salai, is known for its numerous book shops, including pavement shops selling old and used books.<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Mithran\n | first = Ashoka\n | title = Good old Pycrofts road\n | newspaper = Chennai Online\n | publisher = ChennaiOnline.com\n | date = 9 January 2009\n | url = http://chennaionline.com/Columns/Retrochennai/Jan09/01RC06.aspx\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Frederick\n | first = Prince\n | title = The knowledge street\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n\n | date = 23 April 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/article1719464.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> [[Zam Bazaar]] is one of the oldest bazaar in the city and was set up in the pre-Independence era. The western end of the market is bordered by an old monument known as the '''[[Amir Mahal]]''', the palace of the Nawab of Arcot two centuries ago. The building is currently being renovated by the government.<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Damani\n | first = Neha\n | title = Market value\n | newspaper = India Today\n | publisher = IndiaToday.com\n | date = 9 January 2009\n | url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Market+value/1/24736.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Jona Gilon\n | first = Catherine\n | title = Bazaar Buzz\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n\n | date = 23 March 2008\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/rp/2008/03/23/stories/2008032350130300.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe neighbourhood, however, suffers from drainage issues and other civic problems.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Sewage floods Triplicane roads\n | newspaper = Deccan Chronicle\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 30 April 2012\n | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/sewage-floods-triplicane-roads-136\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title = Drainage issues plague Triplicane\n | newspaper = IBN Live\n | location = Chennai\n | publisher = Express News Service\n | date = 2 May 2012\n | url = http://ibnlive.in.com/news/drainage-issues-plague-triplicane/253671-60-120.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:University of Madras campus in Triplicane.jpg|thumb|left|190px|Triplicane campus of the University of Madras]]\n[[File:State Council for Higher Secondary Education, Chennai.jpg|thumb|left|190px|State Council for Higher Secondary Education at the Lady Wellingdon College campus]]\nThe famous colleges in the locality are [[Queen Mary's College, Chennai|Queen Mary's College]], [[Presidency College, Chennai|Presidency College]] and [[Madras University]] on the Beach Road.\nThe popular schools in this area include [[Hindu Senior Secondary School, Triplicane|Hindu Senior Secondary School]], the Kellett higher secondary school, NKT, Rex,  [[Hindu High School]], Lady Wellington school, etc. Some of these schools are very old and even dating back to the British Era, like the latter two schools.<ref name=\"Hindu high school\"/>\n\n===Library===\nLibraries in this area include Kasthuri Srinivasan Library on Besant Road, one on Peyalwar Koil street, Muhammadan Public Library<ref>{{cite news|title=Historic library at Triplicane reopens for readers|url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/21/stories/2005122121140300.htm|accessdate=4 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=21 December 2005}}</ref>  and one on Big street. The Kasturi Srinivasan library is more than 50 years old.<ref name=\"kasthuri srinivasan library\">[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article1554817.ece \"Golden jubilee celebrated\"], ''The Hindu'', Downtown, Chennai, 20 March 2011. Retrieved 3 April 2012</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nTriplicane has a rich culture. The culture associated with Parthasarathy temple and its mada veethis is a traditional and an age old one.<ref name=\"ShatteringTheStillnessOfTime\">{{cite news | last = Parthasarathy | first = Anusha | title = Shattering the stillness of time | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | date = 24 April 2012 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/society/article3349084.ece | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Rooted in tradition, Triplicane is also known for its fine artistic taste in music, dance and arts.<ref name=\"ThiruvallikeniThiruvizha_ACommunityEvent\">{{cite news\n | author = Lalithasai\n | title = Thiruvallikeni Thiruvizha: a community event\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 14 January 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article1091019.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> An annual community even known as the '''Thiruvallikeni Thiruvizha''' (literally ''Triplicane Festival'') is celebrated in January.<ref name=\"ThiruvallikeniThiruvizha_ACommunityEvent\"/><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Soman\n | first = Sandhya\n | title = A trip down memory lane\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 9 January 2007\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/2007/01/09/stories/2007010916930200.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Other festivals include Triplicane Music Festival and ''Marghazhi'' (winter) festival.<ref name=\"LinkRecaptured\">{{cite news\n | last = Ramanathan\n | first = Saradha\n | title = Link recaptured\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 21 May 2010\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/fr/2010/05/21/stories/2010052161340300.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Madhavan\n | first = T.\n | title = Triplicane Music Festival\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 25 December 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article2745871.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ColourfulTradition\">{{cite news\n | last = Suresh\n | first = S.\n | title = Colourful tradition\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 7 January 2003\n | url = http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2003/01/07/stories/2003010700050200.htm\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Triplicane is known for some of the traditionally famous cuisines of Chennai, with age-old restaurants, such as the Rathna Cafe,<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Shanmugham\n | first = Sujatha\n | title = Thali destinations\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 18 August 2010\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/Food/article580023.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Shetty\n | first = Deepika\n | title = Charming and cultured Chennai\n | newspaper = The Straits Times\n | publisher = Asia One Travel\n | date = 30 October 2008\n | url = http://travel.asiaone.com/Travel/Places%2B%2526%2BInterests/Region/Europe/Story/A1Story20081030-97292.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = Badrinath\n | first = Mallika\n | title = Off the menu\n | newspaper = India Today\n | publisher = IndiaToday.in\n | date = 3 September 2008\n | url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Off+the+menu/1/14399.html\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> being based here.\n\n===Architecture===\n[[File:AnnieBesantPark Triplicane Chennai.jpg|thumb|210px|[[Dr. Annie Besant Park, Chennai|Annie Besant Park]]]]\n[[File:AnnieBesantPark Triplicane Chennai FishermenStatue.jpg|thumb|210px|Fishermen statue at Annie Besant Park]]\nTriplicane, similar to few other areas in the city such as Mylapore and West Mambalam, is known for its traditional row houses, known as ''agraharams''.<ref name=\"Agraharam_TimeVirtuallyStandsStill\">{{cite news\n | last = Sujatha\n | first = R.\n | title = Agraharam \u2014 time virtually stands still here\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | date = 29 April 2012\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article3367816.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref> Typically, these can be seen where an entire street is occupied by Brahmins, particularly surrounding a temple. The architecture is distinctive with Madras terraces, country tile roofing, Burma teak rafters and lime plastering. The longish homes consisted of the ''mudhal kattu'' (receiving quarters), ''irandaam kattu'' (living quarters), ''moondram kattu'' (kitchen and backyard) and so on. Most houses had an open to sky space in the centre called the ''mitham'', large platforms lining the outside of the house called the ''thinnai'' and a private well in the backyard. The floors were often coated with red oxide and sometimes the roofs had glass tiles to let in light. The agraharam quadrangle seen in Triplicane is around the Parthasarathy Temple and its tank.<ref name=\"VanishingAgraharams\"/>\n\nAbout 50 families continue to live in the agraharams in Triplicane.<ref name=\"Agraharam_TimeVirtuallyStandsStill\"/> However, many of these houses are being replaced with modern multi-storied apartments, resulting in a reduction in their numbers.<ref name=\"VanishingAgraharams\">{{cite news\n | last = Iyer\n | first = Aruna V.\n | title = Chennai's vanishing agraharams\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n\n | date = 7 October 2011\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/homes-and-gardens/article2518383.ece\n | accessdate =9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Places of worship===\nAlthough [[Parthasarathy Temple]] remains the most important temple of Triplicane, there exists indeed several other temples in the neighbourhood, including [[Ellamman temple|Ellai Amman Temple]] and nearby Sundaramurthy vinayaka temple, Kulathangarai Anjeneya Temple (on the steps on the Parthasarathy temple tank), Anjeneya Temple on Tank Street, Tula Singa Perumal Temple, [[Ahobila Mutt]] Temple on Car Street, Kaamakala Kameshwarar Temple on Raja Hanumantha lala street, Anjaneyar temple on Hanumantha Rayan street, Muthu Vinayakar Temple on Muthu Kallathy Street, Anjeneya Temple on Besant Road, [[Ettampadai Temple|Ettampadai Murugan Temple]], Raghavendra Temple and Mutt on T.P Koil Street, Panduranga swami temple on Venkatachalam street, Vinayaka temples on big street and at the market, Temples on Raja Hanumantha Lala Lane, Udupi Sri Krishna Temple and Mutt, Sri Krishna mandiram, Peyalwar Temple built on the 13th century.<ref name=\"peyalwar\" /> and Thiruveteeswarar Temple. The thevaram has a reference of Thiruvateeswarar temple, which suggests its existence since the 7th century.\n\nMutts in the region include [[Uttaradi Matha|Uttradi Mutt]] on Singrachari Street, [[Ahobila Mutt]] and Temple on Car Street, Vanamamalai Mutt on East Tank Square Street,<ref>http://www.vanamamalai.com/mutt/mutt.html</ref> Raghavendra Mutt and Temple on T. P. Koil Street, Vysaraja Mutt, Yadugiri Yathiraja Mutt, and few others situated around Parthasarathy Temple or mada veethis.\n\n[[The Wallajah Mosque]], also known as the Big Mosque, is one of the famous historical mosques in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapsofindia.com/chennai/places-of-interest/religious-places/big-mosque.html|title=Big Mosque, Chennai|website=www.mapsofindia.com}}</ref> Built in 1795 in remembrance of Nawab Wallajah, the mosque was constructed with grey granite, without the use of wood or steel.<ref name=\"ChennaiBest_History1751-1800\"/>\n\n====Vaikunta Ekadesi====\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nVaikunta Ekadesi Festival is very famous in this temple and huge crowds gather to visit the temple on this day.<ref name=\"temple tales of triplicane toi\">{{cite news|title=Temple tales of Triplicane|author=Srinivasa Ramanujam|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-15/travel/29922568_1_parthasarathy-temple-triplicane-vaikunta-ekadasi|accessdate=19 March 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/chennai/religious-fervour-marks-vaikunta-ekadasi-chennai-347 \"Religious fervour marks Vaikunta Ekadasi in Chennai\"], ''Deccan Chronicle'', Chennai, 6 January 2012. Retrieved on 3 April 2012</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=In City|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RgBFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YrcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4047,1197453&dq=triplicane+parthasarathy&hl=en|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=The Indian Express, Madras|date=12 March 1949}}</ref>\nVaikunta Ekadesi vrata is observed on Dhanur Masa Shukla Paksha Ekadasi or on the 11th day of bright fortnight during Dhanur Masam. This festival is celebrated with lot of devotion in many Vaishnavaite temples including Parthasarathy temple in South India. Vaikunta Dwara lies in the North side of the temple. Vaikunta Ekadesi is also observed as Mukkoti Ekadesi.\n\nUnmindful of the chill, the streets of Triplicane would be milling with people as early as 2&nbsp;am on Vaikunta Ekadesi. Women adorning the traditional nine yards or a silk sari would be seen hurrying towards the Parthasarathy Temple to find a place in the long winding queues that stretched infinitely even in those wee hours.\n\nJostling against each other  people at a snail's space towards the shrine. It was obvious that they want to cross the Paramapadavaasal along with the presiding deity. More than '''one lakh devotees''' visit the temple who are helped by volunteers, temple authorities and police personnel, to move around the prakarams. Police would be stationed around the temple and atop watchtowers at the junction of the Mada Streets to maintain strict vigil.<ref>Lalithasai. [http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/article962339.ece \"When the doors of Paramapadavaasal open...\"], ''The Hindu'', Downtown, Chennai, 19 December 2010. Retrieved 3 April 2012</ref><ref>M Bharat Kumar, K Vivek prasad. [http://www.newstodaynet.com/newsindex.php?id=20795+&+section=7 \"Devotees throng temples for Vaikunta Ekadesi\"], ''[[The News Today (India)|News Today]]'', 28 December 2009, Chennai. Retrieved 3 April 2012</ref>\n\n===Carnatic Music===\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nTriplicane was also once the seat of [[Carnatic music]]. Many famous personalities in this industry visited or resided in triplicane.<ref name=\"when streets resonated with ragas\">Gowri Ramnarayan. [http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/12/24/stories/2002122400210300.htm \"When streets resonated with ragas\"], ''The Hindu'', Metro Plus, Chennai, 24 December 2002. Retrieved on 3 April 2012</ref>  Triplicane was not only known for weekend visits by famous musicians, but also for resident legends such as G.N. Balasubramaniam and M.S. Subbulakshmi. The right atmosphere for music and dance permeated Triplicane. A proliferation of sabhas \u2013 Triplicane Arts Academy, Thiruvateeswarar Sabha, N.K.T. Muthu Sabha and Parthasarathy Swami Sabha \u2013 drew these heavyweights in the classical arts to the locality.<ref name=\"my heart beats for triplicane\">Written by Prince Frederick, as told by Vikku Vinayakram. [http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article1480313.ece \"Memories of Madras - \u2018My heart beats for Triplicane'\"], ''The Hindu'', Arts - History & Culture, 22 February 2011. Retrieved on 3 April 2012.</ref>\nOnce musicians used to talk of how they had sung at the Hindu High School or heard GNB at some other Triplicane venue. Sadly, with time, that kind of talk died out. Legends M.S. Subbulakshmi and GNB lived in Triplicane once, and it was said that this was where vidwans would spend afternoons discussing music over hot rava pongal at the Krishna Iyer Hotel. The 1965s and 1970s saw music and dance pervade the area in various sabhas. From the concerts of M.S. and GNB to Manakkal Rangarajan; from the stage plays of M.G. Ramachandran and Sivaji Ganesan to actor Sivakumar's debut play \u2013 this place has hosted leading artists of those days. You name them and they have been performed here. Thus Triplicane was the central locality where all the cultural happenings of the city took place, and all the famous personalities used to come down to perform.<ref>{{cite news|last=Renuka Suryanarayan|title=Back in full force...|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/history-and-culture/article2677239.ece|accessdate=9 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu, Chennai|date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Chennai assembly constituencys Chepauk-Triplicane.png|thumb|right|100px|Chennai assembly Chepauk-Triplicane constituency]]\nTriplicane is a part of Chepauk-Triplicane assembly constituency which in turn a part of [[Chennai South (Lok Sabha constituency)|Chennai South constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2001/background/S22/TN_ACPC.pdf\n |title       = List of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies\n |accessdate  = 8 October 2008\n |work        = Tamil Nadu\n |publisher   = Election Commission of India\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060504185928/http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2001/background/S22/TN_ACPC.pdf\n |archivedate = 4 May 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> The MLA Hostel is located on [[Wallajah Road, Chennai|Wallajah Road]]. [[Rajaji Hall]] in the same campus, which was built between 1800 and 1802,<ref name=\"groseclosep34\">{{cite book|title=British sculpture and the Company Raj: church monuments and public statuary in Madras, Calcutta, and Bombay to 1858|first=Barbara S.|last=Groseclose|page=34|publisher=University of Delaware Press|year=1995|isbn= 978-0-87413-406-3}}</ref> used to have a role in state administration. At present, it houses the offices of the Tamil Nadu State Raffle.<ref name=\"chopra\">{{cite book|title=Monuments of the Raj: British buildings in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and Myanmar|pages=7\u20138|first=Prabha|last=Chopra|publisher=Aryan Books International|year=1999|isbn= 978-81-7305-094-7}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\n{{See also|Thiruvallikeni (Chennai MRTS)}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2012}}\nBeing situated in the central region of the city, Triplicane is well connected to various places in Chennai. The [[Metropolitan Transport Corporation (Chennai)|MTC]] had bus termini such as the Ice House and Triplicane (located at Pycrofts Road). The Triplicane bus terminus, one of the oldest bus termini in the city, is not functional now. The MTC has moved all services which were originating from Triplicane to the near-by Anna square terminus and some services are extended to Broadway. The [[Mass Rapid Transit System (Chennai)|MRTS]] has a station [[Thiruvallikeni (Chennai MRTS)|Thiruvallikeni]] on the Chennai Beach\u2013Velachery elevated rail corridor serving the neighbourhood. In addition, the neighbourhood is served by private auto rickshaws.\n\n==Famous personalities==\n<!--THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE COPYEDITED AND WIKIFIED YET-->\nTriplicane is famous for the various personalities it has produced over the years. Mathematician [[Srinivasa Ramanujan]],<ref>Hema Vijay. [http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/society/article2134518.ece \"The man who knows Ramanujan\"],''Life & Style - Society, The Hindu'', 26 June 2011. Retrieved on 3 April 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=K. Srinivasa Rao|title=Srinivasa Ramanujan|url=http://www.imsc.res.in/~rao/ramanujan.html|work=Article from The Institute of Mathematical Sciences official website|publisher=The Institute of Mathematical Sciences (IMSC)|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Prince Frederick|title=The street where Ramanujan lived|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2003/12/24/stories/2003122400180100.htm|accessdate=4 April 2012|newspaper=The Hindu|date=24 December 2003}}</ref> Writer [[Sujatha Rangarajan]], and cricketers [[M.J. Gopalan]], [[Krishnamachari Srikkanth|Krish Srikkanth]] and [[W.V. Raman]] all hailed from Triplicane. [[Nobel prize]] winner [[Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar]] did his schooling in the [[The Hindu Higher Secondary School|Hindu High School]] (1922\u20131925) in Triplicane. [[Subramanya Bharathy]], a freedom fighter and poet, lived his last years in the house opposite the parthasarathy temple's western entrance; the house has since been bought and renovated by the Government of Tamil Nadu in 1993, and it was named Bharathiyar Illam (Home of Bharathiyar).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods of Chennai}}\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Chennai district]]\n[[Category:Coastal neighbourhoods of Chennai]]\n", "name_user": "V Ramamurthy IAS 59-94", "label": "safe", "comment": "Gave full names and future posts of Annaadurai and Karunaandhi. Corrected grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triplicane"}
{"title_page": "The Little Rascals (animated TV series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Little Rascals\n| image                    = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = A screenshot from the ''Little Rascals'' Saturday morning cartoon.\n| genre                    = [[Animation]]<br />[[Comedy]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = ''[[Our Gang]]'' created by<br />[[Hal Roach]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = George Gordon<br />Bob Hathcock<br />[[Carl Urbano]]<br />[[Rudy Zamora]]\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = \n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = [[Julie McWhirter|Julie McWhirter Dees]]<br />[[Patty Maloney]]<br />[[Scott Menville]]<br />[[Shavar Ross]]<br />[[B. J. Ward (actress)|B.J. Ward]]<br />[[Peter Cullen]]\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| language                 = \n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = 22\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = [[William Hanna]]<br />[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = Gil Iverson\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 30 minutes (11 minutes a cartoon)\n| company                  = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]]<br />[[King World Productions]]\n| distributor              = [[Worldvision Enterprises]] (1982\u20131989)<br />Great American Broadcasting (1989\u20131991)<br />King World Productions (1991\u20132007)<br />[[CBS Television Distribution]] (2007\u2013present)\n| network                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format           = [[NTSC]]\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = September 25, 1982\n| last_aired               = December 2, 1983\n| related                  = \n| website                  = \n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''The Little Rascals''''' is a 30-minute [[Saturday-morning cartoon|Saturday morning animated series]] produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and [[King World Productions]]. It first aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on September 25, 1982.<ref name=\"Perlmutter\">{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739}}</ref>{{rp|365-366}} A [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] based on the live-action ''[[Our Gang]]'' comedy shorts, it was broadcast as part of ''[[The Pac-Man/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show]]'' in 1982 and then as part of ''[[The Monchhichis/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show]]'' in 1983.<ref name=\"Perlmutter\" />{{rp|503}}\n\nThe characters were designed by [[Iwao Takamoto]] and [[Bob Singer]] by using tracing paper on top of actual photographs of the real-life characters, and used a pencil to sketch the characters.  The same technique was also used in previous Hanna-Barbera spin-offs such as ''[[Fonz and the Happy Days Gang]]'' and ''[[Laverne & Shirley (1981 TV series)|Laverne and Shirley in the Army]]''.\n\n==Overview==\n\n===Previous ''Little Rascals''/''Our Gang'' animated television programs===\n''The Little Rascals'' had been animated for television twice before. In the 1960s, a series of nine clay-animated ''Little Rascals Color Specials'' were produced for syndication, presumably by Bura & Hardwick, the British studio responsible for ''[[Camberwick Green]]'', using soundtracks from the original ''Our Gang'' films. The episodes include \"[[Shiver My Timbers]]\", \"[[Our Gang Follies of 1936]]\", \"[[Second Childhood (film)|Second Childhood]]\", \"[[Hearts Are Thumps]]\", \"[[Came the Brawn]]\", \"[[Bear Shooters]]\", \"[[Readin' and Writin']]\", \"[[The Pinch Singer]]\", and \"[[Teacher's Beau]]\". {{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn 1979, [[Fred Wolf (animator)|Fred Wolf]] produced an animated ''[[The Little Rascals Christmas Special]]'' for [[NBC]]. That company's version was further used in animated [[public service announcement]]s.\n\n===Differences between the animated series and the live-action ''Our Gang'' films===\nThe animated series and the original live-action ''Our Gang'' films differ in a number of ways. The gang now lives in a contemporary 1980s setting, with [[computer]]s and [[television]]. Buckwheat is now a clever [[inventor]] and is interested in science, always creating new devices for the gang, and Darla's eyes were changed from hazel to blue (although this detail was trivial given that all of the ''Our Gang'' shorts were in black-and-white). Also in the animated series, the Rascals met in a treehouse and drove around the town of Greenpoint in a dog-drawn vehicle. Also, the [[theme music]] was completely different.\n\n==Lawsuit==\nIn March 1984, ''Our Gang'' actor [[Eugene Gordon Lee|Eugene Lee]], who had played Porky in the original theatrical short films as a child from 1935 to 1939, sued Hanna-Barbera Productions for nearly $2 million, claiming that the animated character was a violation of his likeness rights. He was joined in the lawsuit by other former ''Our Gang'' kids: [[George McFarland]], who had played Spanky, [[Tommy Bond]], who had played Butch, and [[Sidney Kibrick]], who had played The Woim. [[Carl Switzer]], [[Darla Hood]] and [[Billie Thomas]], who had played Alfalfa, Darla and Buckwheat respectively were already deceased. It was found that Hanna-Barbera's license from King World did not include the likeness rights of the former child actors, and the case was settled out of court.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wgAfDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Trial+by+Fire:+One+Man%27s+Battle+to+End+Corporate+Greed+and+Save+Lives&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwicv5X5qLnTAhWLOyYKHSiGCBAQ6AEIIzAA#v=onepage&q=spanky&f=false |title=Trial by Fire: One Man's Battle to End Corporate Greed and Save Lives |last=Burg |first=Mike |publisher=BenBella Books, Inc. |year=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other languages==\nThe French dub for [[Antenne 2]], ''Les Petites Canailles'', replaced the original theme music with a new theme song, performed by a chorus of children over a montage of clips from both the theatrical ''Our Gang'' shorts and the animated shorts.\n\n==Episode titles==\n\n===Season 1===\nAired as part of ''The Pac-Man/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" width=10 | #\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Title/Plot\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Airdate\n|-\n|| 1\n|\n* '''Rascals' Revenge''': Butch and Woim lure the Rascals into a supposedly haunted house.\n* '''Yachtsa Luck''': The Rascals try to get Waldo's treasure back from a couple of robbers.\n* '''Fish Fright''': 30 second vignette. Spanky and Alfalfa go fishing.\n| September 25, 1982\n|-\n|| 2\n|\n* '''Grin and Bear It''': During the Rascals' camping trip, Porky is abducted by the Phantom Lumberjack, who is apparently a bank robber in disguise.\n* '''Beauty Queen for a Day''': After the boys fall for Dolly Van Dumpling, the new girl in town, Darla enters the Little Miss Big City Beauty Pageant.\n* '''The Serenade''': 30 second vignette. Alfalfa serenades Darla, but his off-key singing scares Pete away.\n| October 2, 1982\n|-\n|| 3\n|\n* '''Big City Rascals''': The Rascals visit Darla's uncle on his farm.\n* '''Alfalfakazam!''': During Spanky's magic show, Alfalfa supposedly turns into a rabbit.\n* '''Scoop Dupes''': 30 second vignette.\n| October 9, 1982\n|-\n|| 4\n|\n* '''Showdown at the Rascal Corral''': Alfalfa plays cowboy; two outlaws \"arrest\" him for singing in a no-singing zone.\n* '''Poached Pooch''': Butch and Woim steal Pete's dog license.\n* '''Ice Escapades''': 30 second vignette.  Despite a heat wave, Buckwheat, Spanky and Alfalfa are eager to go ice skating.\n| October 16, 1982\n|-\n|| 5\n|\n* '''Porky-O and Julie-Et''': Porky falls for the daughter of an ice cream magnate.\n* '''Just Deserts''': The boys enter Darla's cake in a baking contest. Unfortunately, Darla is sick with the turkey pox and Alfalfa has to dress as a girl for the contest.  The recipe card becomes illegible.\n* '''No Hit Wit''': 30 second vignette.\n| October 23, 1982\n|-\n|| 6\n|\n* '''Alfalfa for President''': Alfalfa and Waldo compete for class president.\n* '''Rock and Roll Rascals''': Darla wants an autograph from Greg Groover, a rock musician.\n* '''A Swimming We Will Go''': 30 second vignette. Officer Ed finds the boys in a pond, in violation of a \"no swimming\" sign.\n| October 30, 1982\n|-\n|| 7\n|\n* '''The Irate Pirates''': On the beach, the Rascals hunt for treasure, then encounter two adult troublemakers dressed as pirates.\n* '''All the Loot That's Fit to Print''': The Rascals start a newspaper, The Neighborhood Bugle; Alfalfa unwittingly spends counterfeit money.\n* '''The Spare''': 30 second vignette.\n| November 6, 1982\n|-\n|| 8\n|\n* '''Alfalfa's Athlete Feat''': Butch challenges Alfalfa to a [[pentathlon]].\n* '''Darla's Dream Dance''': Darla organizes the school dance.  The boys try to sabotage the event, after Alfalfa learns that Waldo is Darla's date.\n* '''Fiscal Fitness''': 30 second vignette.\n| November 13, 1982\n|-\n|| 9\n|\n* '''Cap'n Spanky's Showboat''': The Rascals clean up the [[Mississippi Queen (steamboat)|Mississippi Queen]], an old steamboat.\n* '''Case of the Puzzled Pals''': Alfalfa plays detective to find Darla's doll.\n* '''Go Cart Go''': 30 second vignette. Butch takes Buckwheat's go cart for a spin.\n| November 20, 1982\n|-\n|| 10\n|\n* '''Falling Heir''': Spanky inherits a castle that is said to be haunted.\n* '''Flim Flam Film Fans''': A movie director comes to town; Darla gets tied to a railroad gate ''\u00e1 la'' [[Penelope Pitstop]].\n* '''Do or Diet''': 30 second vignette. Darla asks Buckwheat how many meals Porky eats in a day; the answer shocks her.\n| November 27, 1982\n|-\n|| 11\n|\n* '''Trash Can Treasures''': The Rascals find an [[Aladdin]]-type lamp. Darla adopts a stray horse.\n* '''King of the Hobos''': After eating the other Rascals' food, Porky gets banned from the club, runs away and meets an old hobo.\n* '''Out on a Limb''': 30 second vignette. Alfalfa is pushing Spanky in a swing, but is distracted by Darla.\n| December 4, 1982\n|-\n|| 12\n|\n* '''Tiny Terror''': Butch leaves his baby brother Spike with the Rascals.\n* '''Science Fair and Foul''': Buckwheat builds a robot for a science fair.\n* '''Sea Song''': 30 second vignette. While Spanky, Alfalfa, and Buckwheat are swimming, Alfalfa decides to sing \"Oh My Darla\", a parody of \"[[Oh My Darling Clementine]]\". Spanky and Buckwheat know how to keep him quiet.\n| December 11, 1982\n|-\n|| 13\n|\n* '''Big Top Rascals''': After being caught sneaking into the Ding-a-Ling Brothers circus, the Rascals decide to put on their own circus; Butch and Woim take unfair advantage of their free admission.\n* '''Class Act''': The Rascals enter Pete in a dog show, but Waldo doesn't think Pete has a chance against the show's pedigree dogs. Things get hectic when somebody kidnaps Pete.\n* '''He Who Runs Away''': 30 second vignette.\n| December 18, 1982\n|}\n\n===Season 2===\nAired as part of ''The Monchhichis/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" width=10 | #\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Title/Plot\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Airdate\n|-\n|| 14\n|\n'''Wash and Werewolf''': After seeing a 3-D horror movie, Alfalfa thinks he is a werewolf.\n| September 10, 1983\n|-\n|| 15\n|\n'''Save Our Treehouse!''': A used car dealer wants to destroy the Rascals' treehouse.  The Rascals protest his actions, like unionized workers on strike.\n| September 17, 1983\n|-\n|| 16\n|\n'''Horse Sense''': Alfalfa and Waldo are fighting for Darla's affections again. This time, Waldo challenges Alfalfa to a horse race. There's just one problem: Alfalfa doesn't know how to ride.\n| September 24, 1983\n|-\n|| 17\n|\n'''After Hours''': The Rascals get jobs in a department store warehouse.\n| October 1, 1983\n|-\n|| 18\n|\n'''A Not So Buenos D\u00edas''': Alfalfa is suspicious of Darla's Latina friend, Maria.\n| October 15, 1983\n|-\n|| 19\n|\n'''Fright Night''': The Rascals go trick-or-treating. Buckwheat dresses as [[George Washington Carver]], and Darla dresses so as to resemble Alfalfa. \n| October 29, 1983\n|-\n|| 20\n|\n'''The Big Sneeze''': The Rascals meet up with a goat, to which Alfalfa is allergic to.\n| November 12, 1983\n|-\n|| 21\n|\n'''Pete's Big Break''': When Pete saves another dog from drowning, he and the Rascals are rewarded a chance to star in a dog food commercial.\n| November 19, 1983\n|-\n|| 22\n|\n'''The Zero Hero''': Darla wins a date with Captain Muscles, a TV superhero, in order to impress Darla, Alfalfa assumes the identity of Alpha-Man.\n| December 2, 1983\n|}\n\n\"Tiny Terror\", \"Class Act\", \"Porky-O and Julie-Et\" and \"Cap'n Spanky's Showboat\", previously aired during the first season, were rebroadcast on October 8 and 22, and November 5 and 26, 1983 respectively.\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Main voices===\n* [[Peter Cullen]] as [[Pete the Pup]] and Officer Ed<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/360/mode/2up|accessdate=19 March 2020|page=360}}</ref>\n* [[Patty Maloney]] as [[Darla Hood]]\n* [[Julie McWhirter]] as [[Carl \"Alfalfa\" Switzer|Alfalfa]], [[Eugene \"Porky\" Lee|Porky]], and [[Sidney \"The Woim\" Kibrick|The Woim]]\n* [[Scott Menville]] as [[George \"Spanky\" McFarland|Spanky]]\n* [[Shavar Ross]] as [[Billie \"Buckwheat\" Thomas|Buckwheat]]\n* [[B. J. Ward (actress)|B.J. Ward]] as [[Tommy \"Butch\" Bond|Butch]] and [[Darwood \"Waldo\" Kaye|Waldo]].\n\n===Additional voices===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Richard Balin\n* [[Jered Barclay]]\n* [[Julie Bennett]]\n* [[Susan Blu]]\n* [[Bill Callaway]]\n* [[Brian Cummings]]\n* [[Jeff Doucette]]\n* [[Peggy Frees]]\n* [[Phil Hartman]]\n* [[Ery Immerman]]\n* [[Kip King]]\n* [[Earl Kress]]\n* [[Sherry Lynn]]\n* [[Larry D. Mann]]\n* [[Kenneth Mars]]\n* Joe Medalis\n* [[Robert Ridgely]]\n* Michael Sheehan\n* [[Gary Stamm]]\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]]\n* [[Russi Taylor]]\n* [[Lennie Weinrib]]\n* [[Jimmy Weldon]]\n* [[Frank Welker]]\n* Ted Zeigler\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Home media releases==\nIt was announced on Facebook on April 23, 2016 that the series will not be released on DVD due to reasons beyond [[Warner Archive Collection|Warner Archive]]'s control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/warnerarchive/posts/10154139254756563?comment_id=10154140997636563&notif_t=feed_comment&notif_id=1461448068375846|title=No DVD release for Little Rascals cartoon|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2016-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0770584|title=The Little Rascals}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-little-rascals-show|The Little Rascals}}\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Pac-Man___047__Little_Rascals___047__Richie_Rich_Show/The_Little_Rascals/index.html ''The Little Rascals''] at BCDB\n\n{{Our Gang}}\n{{Children's programming on the American Broadcasting Company in the 1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little Rascals, The (animated TV series)}}\n[[Category:1980s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1982 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1983 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Animation based on real people]]\n[[Category:Our Gang]]\n[[Category:Television series by King World Productions]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:Television articles with disputed naming style]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Little Rascals\n| image                    = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = A screenshot from the ''Little Rascals'' Saturday morning cartoon.\n| genre                    = [[Animation]]<br />[[Comedy]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = ''[[Our Gang]]'' created by<br />[[Hal Roach]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = George Gordon<br />Bob Hathcock<br />[[Carl Urbano]]<br />[[Rudy Zamora]]\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = \n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = [[Julie McWhirter|Julie McWhirter Dees]]<br />[[Patty Maloney]]<br />[[Scott Menville]]<br />[[Shavar Ross]]<br />[[B. J. Ward (actress)|B.J. Ward]]<br />[[Peter Cullen]]\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| language                 = \n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = 22\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = [[William Hanna]]<br />[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = Gil Iverson\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 30 minutes (11 minutes a cartoon)\n| company                  = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]]<br />[[King World Productions]]\n| distributor              = [[Worldvision Enterprises]] (1982\u20131989)<br />Great American Broadcasting (1989\u20131991)<br />King World Productions (1991\u20132007)<br />[[CBS Television Distribution]] (2007\u2013present)\n| network                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format           = [[NTSC]]\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = September 25, 1982\n| last_aired               = December 2, 1983\n| related                  = \n| website                  = \n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''The Little Rascals''''' is a 30-minute [[Saturday-morning cartoon|Saturday morning animated series]] produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and [[King World Productions]]. It first aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on September 25, 1982.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=365-366}}</ref> A [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] based on the live-action ''[[Our Gang]]'' comedy shorts, it was broadcast as part of ''[[The Pac-Man/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show]]'' in 1982 and then as part of ''[[The Monchhichis/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show]]'' in 1983.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=503}}</ref>\n\nThe characters were designed by [[Iwao Takamoto]] and [[Bob Singer]] by using tracing paper on top of actual photographs of the real-life characters, and used a pencil to sketch the characters.  The same technique was also used in previous Hanna-Barbera spin-offs such as ''[[Fonz and the Happy Days Gang]]'' and ''[[Laverne & Shirley (1981 TV series)|Laverne and Shirley in the Army]]''.\n\n==Overview==\n\n===Previous ''Little Rascals''/''Our Gang'' animated television programs===\n''The Little Rascals'' had been animated for television twice before. In the 1960s, a series of nine clay-animated ''Little Rascals Color Specials'' were produced for syndication, presumably by Bura & Hardwick, the British studio responsible for ''[[Camberwick Green]]'', using soundtracks from the original ''Our Gang'' films. The episodes include \"[[Shiver My Timbers]]\", \"[[Our Gang Follies of 1936]]\", \"[[Second Childhood (film)|Second Childhood]]\", \"[[Hearts Are Thumps]]\", \"[[Came the Brawn]]\", \"[[Bear Shooters]]\", \"[[Readin' and Writin']]\", \"[[The Pinch Singer]]\", and \"[[Teacher's Beau]]\". {{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn 1979, [[Fred Wolf (animator)|Fred Wolf]] produced an animated ''[[The Little Rascals Christmas Special]]'' for [[NBC]]. That company's version was further used in animated [[public service announcement]]s.\n\n===Differences between the animated series and the live-action ''Our Gang'' films===\nThe animated series and the original live-action ''Our Gang'' films differ in a number of ways. The gang now lives in a contemporary 1980s setting, with [[computer]]s and [[television]]. Buckwheat is now a clever [[inventor]] and is interested in science, always creating new devices for the gang, and Darla's eyes were changed from hazel to blue (although this detail was trivial given that all of the ''Our Gang'' shorts were in black-and-white). Also in the animated series, the Rascals met in a treehouse and drove around the town of Greenpoint in a dog-drawn vehicle. Also, the [[theme music]] was completely different.\n\n==Lawsuit==\nIn March 1984, ''Our Gang'' actor [[Eugene Gordon Lee|Eugene Lee]], who had played Porky in the original theatrical short films as a child from 1935 to 1939, sued Hanna-Barbera Productions for nearly $2 million, claiming that the animated character was a violation of his likeness rights. He was joined in the lawsuit by other former ''Our Gang'' kids: [[George McFarland]], who had played Spanky, [[Tommy Bond]], who had played Butch, and [[Sidney Kibrick]], who had played The Woim. [[Carl Switzer]], [[Darla Hood]] and [[Billie Thomas]], who had played Alfalfa, Darla and Buckwheat respectively were already deceased. It was found that Hanna-Barbera's license from King World did not include the likeness rights of the former child actors, and the case was settled out of court.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wgAfDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Trial+by+Fire:+One+Man%27s+Battle+to+End+Corporate+Greed+and+Save+Lives&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwicv5X5qLnTAhWLOyYKHSiGCBAQ6AEIIzAA#v=onepage&q=spanky&f=false |title=Trial by Fire: One Man's Battle to End Corporate Greed and Save Lives |last=Burg |first=Mike |publisher=BenBella Books, Inc. |year=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other languages==\nThe French dub for [[Antenne 2]], ''Les Petites Canailles'', replaced the original theme music with a new theme song, performed by a chorus of children over a montage of clips from both the theatrical ''Our Gang'' shorts and the animated shorts.\n\n==Episode titles==\n\n===Season 1===\nAired as part of ''The Pac-Man/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" width=10 | #\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Title/Plot\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Airdate\n|-\n|| 1\n|\n* '''Rascals' Revenge''': Butch and Woim lure the Rascals into a supposedly haunted house.\n* '''Yachtsa Luck''': The Rascals try to get Waldo's treasure back from a couple of robbers.\n* '''Fish Fright''': 30 second vignette. Spanky and Alfalfa go fishing.\n| September 25, 1982\n|-\n|| 2\n|\n* '''Grin and Bear It''': During the Rascals' camping trip, Porky is abducted by the Phantom Lumberjack, who is apparently a bank robber in disguise.\n* '''Beauty Queen for a Day''': After the boys fall for Dolly Van Dumpling, the new girl in town, Darla enters the Little Miss Big City Beauty Pageant.\n* '''The Serenade''': 30 second vignette. Alfalfa serenades Darla, but his off-key singing scares Pete away.\n| October 2, 1982\n|-\n|| 3\n|\n* '''Big City Rascals''': The Rascals visit Darla's uncle on his farm.\n* '''Alfalfakazam!''': During Spanky's magic show, Alfalfa supposedly turns into a rabbit.\n* '''Scoop Dupes''': 30 second vignette.\n| October 9, 1982\n|-\n|| 4\n|\n* '''Showdown at the Rascal Corral''': Alfalfa plays cowboy; two outlaws \"arrest\" him for singing in a no-singing zone.\n* '''Poached Pooch''': Butch and Woim steal Pete's dog license.\n* '''Ice Escapades''': 30 second vignette.  Despite a heat wave, Buckwheat, Spanky and Alfalfa are eager to go ice skating.\n| October 16, 1982\n|-\n|| 5\n|\n* '''Porky-O and Julie-Et''': Porky falls for the daughter of an ice cream magnate.\n* '''Just Deserts''': The boys enter Darla's cake in a baking contest. Unfortunately, Darla is sick with the turkey pox and Alfalfa has to dress as a girl for the contest.  The recipe card becomes illegible.\n* '''No Hit Wit''': 30 second vignette.\n| October 23, 1982\n|-\n|| 6\n|\n* '''Alfalfa for President''': Alfalfa and Waldo compete for class president.\n* '''Rock and Roll Rascals''': Darla wants an autograph from Greg Groover, a rock musician.\n* '''A Swimming We Will Go''': 30 second vignette. Officer Ed finds the boys in a pond, in violation of a \"no swimming\" sign.\n| October 30, 1982\n|-\n|| 7\n|\n* '''The Irate Pirates''': On the beach, the Rascals hunt for treasure, then encounter two adult troublemakers dressed as pirates.\n* '''All the Loot That's Fit to Print''': The Rascals start a newspaper, The Neighborhood Bugle; Alfalfa unwittingly spends counterfeit money.\n* '''The Spare''': 30 second vignette.\n| November 6, 1982\n|-\n|| 8\n|\n* '''Alfalfa's Athlete Feat''': Butch challenges Alfalfa to a [[pentathlon]].\n* '''Darla's Dream Dance''': Darla organizes the school dance.  The boys try to sabotage the event, after Alfalfa learns that Waldo is Darla's date.\n* '''Fiscal Fitness''': 30 second vignette.\n| November 13, 1982\n|-\n|| 9\n|\n* '''Cap'n Spanky's Showboat''': The Rascals clean up the [[Mississippi Queen (steamboat)|Mississippi Queen]], an old steamboat.\n* '''Case of the Puzzled Pals''': Alfalfa plays detective to find Darla's doll.\n* '''Go Cart Go''': 30 second vignette. Butch takes Buckwheat's go cart for a spin.\n| November 20, 1982\n|-\n|| 10\n|\n* '''Falling Heir''': Spanky inherits a castle that is said to be haunted.\n* '''Flim Flam Film Fans''': A movie director comes to town; Darla gets tied to a railroad gate ''\u00e1 la'' [[Penelope Pitstop]].\n* '''Do or Diet''': 30 second vignette. Darla asks Buckwheat how many meals Porky eats in a day; the answer shocks her.\n| November 27, 1982\n|-\n|| 11\n|\n* '''Trash Can Treasures''': The Rascals find an [[Aladdin]]-type lamp. Darla adopts a stray horse.\n* '''King of the Hobos''': After eating the other Rascals' food, Porky gets banned from the club, runs away and meets an old hobo.\n* '''Out on a Limb''': 30 second vignette. Alfalfa is pushing Spanky in a swing, but is distracted by Darla.\n| December 4, 1982\n|-\n|| 12\n|\n* '''Tiny Terror''': Butch leaves his baby brother Spike with the Rascals.\n* '''Science Fair and Foul''': Buckwheat builds a robot for a science fair.\n* '''Sea Song''': 30 second vignette. While Spanky, Alfalfa, and Buckwheat are swimming, Alfalfa decides to sing \"Oh My Darla\", a parody of \"[[Oh My Darling Clementine]]\". Spanky and Buckwheat know how to keep him quiet.\n| December 11, 1982\n|-\n|| 13\n|\n* '''Big Top Rascals''': After being caught sneaking into the Ding-a-Ling Brothers circus, the Rascals decide to put on their own circus; Butch and Woim take unfair advantage of their free admission.\n* '''Class Act''': The Rascals enter Pete in a dog show, but Waldo doesn't think Pete has a chance against the show's pedigree dogs. Things get hectic when somebody kidnaps Pete.\n* '''He Who Runs Away''': 30 second vignette.\n| December 18, 1982\n|}\n\n===Season 2===\nAired as part of ''The Monchhichis/Little Rascals/Richie Rich Show''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" width=10 | #\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Title/Plot\n! style=\"background-color: #00B7EB\" | Airdate\n|-\n|| 14\n|\n'''Wash and Werewolf''': After seeing a 3-D horror movie, Alfalfa thinks he is a werewolf.\n| September 10, 1983\n|-\n|| 15\n|\n'''Save Our Treehouse!''': A used car dealer wants to destroy the Rascals' treehouse.  The Rascals protest his actions, like unionized workers on strike.\n| September 17, 1983\n|-\n|| 16\n|\n'''Horse Sense''': Alfalfa and Waldo are fighting for Darla's affections again. This time, Waldo challenges Alfalfa to a horse race. There's just one problem: Alfalfa doesn't know how to ride.\n| September 24, 1983\n|-\n|| 17\n|\n'''After Hours''': The Rascals get jobs in a department store warehouse.\n| October 1, 1983\n|-\n|| 18\n|\n'''A Not So Buenos D\u00edas''': Alfalfa is suspicious of Darla's Latina friend, Maria.\n| October 15, 1983\n|-\n|| 19\n|\n'''Fright Night''': The Rascals go trick-or-treating. Buckwheat dresses as [[George Washington Carver]], and Darla dresses so as to resemble Alfalfa. \n| October 29, 1983\n|-\n|| 20\n|\n'''The Big Sneeze''': The Rascals meet up with a goat, to which Alfalfa is allergic to.\n| November 12, 1983\n|-\n|| 21\n|\n'''Pete's Big Break''': When Pete saves another dog from drowning, he and the Rascals are rewarded a chance to star in a dog food commercial.\n| November 19, 1983\n|-\n|| 22\n|\n'''The Zero Hero''': Darla wins a date with Captain Muscles, a TV superhero, in order to impress Darla, Alfalfa assumes the identity of Alpha-Man.\n| December 2, 1983\n|}\n\n\"Tiny Terror\", \"Class Act\", \"Porky-O and Julie-Et\" and \"Cap'n Spanky's Showboat\", previously aired during the first season, were rebroadcast on October 8 and 22, and November 5 and 26, 1983 respectively.\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Main voices===\n* [[Peter Cullen]] as [[Pete the Pup]] and Officer Ed<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/360/mode/2up|accessdate=19 March 2020|page=360}}</ref>\n* [[Patty Maloney]] as [[Darla Hood]]\n* [[Julie McWhirter]] as [[Carl \"Alfalfa\" Switzer|Alfalfa]], [[Eugene \"Porky\" Lee|Porky]], and [[Sidney \"The Woim\" Kibrick|The Woim]]\n* [[Scott Menville]] as [[George \"Spanky\" McFarland|Spanky]]\n* [[Shavar Ross]] as [[Billie \"Buckwheat\" Thomas|Buckwheat]]\n* [[B. J. Ward (actress)|B.J. Ward]] as [[Tommy \"Butch\" Bond|Butch]] and [[Darwood \"Waldo\" Kaye|Waldo]].\n\n===Additional voices===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Richard Balin\n* [[Jered Barclay]]\n* [[Julie Bennett]]\n* [[Susan Blu]]\n* [[Bill Callaway]]\n* [[Brian Cummings]]\n* [[Jeff Doucette]]\n* [[Peggy Frees]]\n* [[Phil Hartman]]\n* [[Ery Immerman]]\n* [[Kip King]]\n* [[Earl Kress]]\n* [[Sherry Lynn]]\n* [[Larry D. Mann]]\n* [[Kenneth Mars]]\n* Joe Medalis\n* [[Robert Ridgely]]\n* Michael Sheehan\n* [[Gary Stamm]]\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]]\n* [[Russi Taylor]]\n* [[Lennie Weinrib]]\n* [[Jimmy Weldon]]\n* [[Frank Welker]]\n* Ted Zeigler\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Home media releases==\nIt was announced on Facebook on April 23, 2016 that the series will not be released on DVD due to reasons beyond [[Warner Archive Collection|Warner Archive]]'s control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/warnerarchive/posts/10154139254756563?comment_id=10154140997636563&notif_t=feed_comment&notif_id=1461448068375846|title=No DVD release for Little Rascals cartoon|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2016-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0770584|title=The Little Rascals}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-little-rascals-show|The Little Rascals}}\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Pac-Man___047__Litt